<DOCNO> APW19990802.0005 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 20:00:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Barton's Children Laid to Rest  
</P>
<P>
	LITHIA SPRINGS, Ga. (AP) -- Boy and girls dressed in their scout  
uniforms escorted the caskets today of Matthew and Mychelle Barton, 
whose father killed them and tucked them into bed with their toys 
before going on a deadly shooting spree. Pictures of the victims in 
soccer and cheerleading outfits had been placed in a hallway 
outside the White Columns Chapel in this Atlanta suburb, where they 
were eulogized as lovable and active children. Their father, Mark 
O. Barton, killed the children Wednesday, a day after he had killed 
their stepmother. He bashed in their skulls with a hammer and 
dunked them in a bathtub to make sure they were dead. 

</P>
<P>
	Hillary Interview a Political Move  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- An unidentified confidante of Hillary Rodham  
Clinton said the first lady's candid interview with Talk magazine 
about her husband's infidelities was a political calculation to put 
personal questions to rest before they popped up in her Senate 
campaign. Mrs. Clinton called her husband's adultery ``a sin of 
weakness,'' and the product of emotional scars -- ``abuse,'' she 
termed it -- left by battles between his mother and grandmother when 
he was 4 years old. White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said 
President Clinton was ``comfortable with the views expressed in the 
article.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Russia Denies Yugoslavia Arms Sale  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Russia's top arms dealer denied today a report  
that the government exported anti-aircraft missiles to Yugoslavia 
shortly before NATO began its bombing campaign. Jane's Defense 
Weekly, based in Britain, reported today that Russia shipped parts 
for the S-300 surface-to-air missile system to the government of 
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic. The report said Russians hid 
the components in railway cars full of scrap metal. A spokesman for 
Russia's Rosvooruzheniye arms company called the report 
``non-scientific fantasies,'' the ITAR-Tass news agency reported. 

</P>
<P>
	Feds Boast of Exposing Tax Cheats  
</P>
<P>
	NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- Federal officials boasted today that they  
have finally breached Cayman Islands bank secrecy with the aid of a 
former bank owner who provided records that exposed hundreds of 
U.S. citizens as tax cheats. The one-time banker, John M. 
Mathewson, 71, was sentenced in federal court here on conspiracy 
and money laundering charges. U.S. authorities claim the case 
demonstrates that the approximately 500 banks in the tiny British 
colony exist only to serve as illegal tax shelters for a mainly 
American clientele. 

</P>
<P>
	215 Killed in India Train Collision  
</P>
<P>
	GAISAL, India (AP) -- About 200 people remained trapped inside  
the wreckage of two trains that crashed early Monday, killing 215 
people. The accident also injured 310 people, and authorities 
expected the death toll to climb. Some 2,500 passengers were on the 
trains. Officials said a signal error may have put the trains on 
the same track. 

</P>
<P>
	Report: N.Korea Upgrades Missile Base  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- North Korea is improving and expanding facilities  
at its ballistic missile launch base on the country's east coast, a 
Japanese newspaper reported Tuesday. The Sankei newspaper, quoting 
unnamed Japanese and U.S. sources, said North Korea is constructing 
facilities for storing and injecting liquid fuel and oxidizing 
agents inside the compound of the launch base. U.S. and Japanese 
officials in Tokyo refused to comment. The report came amid fear 
that North Korea is preparing to test a long-range ballistic 
missile. The reclusive regime test-fired a missile last August that 
flew over Japan and landed in the Pacific. 

</P>
<P>
	Bradley Moves Ahead of Bush in N.Y.  
</P>
<P>
	ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Former Sen. Bill Bradley is gaining on Vice  
President Al Gore in polling in New York and actually outdoes the 
vice president when matched against Republican George W. Bush. In a 
Democratic primary matchup, Gore led Bradley 47 percent to 38 
percent in a survey by the Quinnipiac College Polling Institute. 
That's just half the margin of the poll released in early July, 52 
percent to 34 percent. Against Bush, Bradley led 46 percent to 39 
percent in the poll released today, up from the earlier survey that 
had Bush at 44 percent and Bradley at 43 percent. 

</P>
<P>
	Japan Stocks Higher in Early Trading  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo share prices rose on buying of international  
blue chips in early trading Tuesday. The Nikkei Stock Average 
gained 13.17 points to 17,838.87. On Wall Street on Monday, the Dow 
Jones industrial average ended down 9.19 at 10,645.96. 

</P>
<P>
	Sosa, McGwire Tied With 41 Homers  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Sammy Sosa briefly regained the major league home  
run lead tonight, hitting his 41st for the Chicago Cubs. Sosa and 
St. Louis' Mark McGwire started the day tied for the lead with 40 
homers each. McGwire hit his 41st -- shortly after Sosa connected -- 
in the fifth inning of the Cardinals' game against the San Diego 
Padres. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by ELIZABETH A. KENNEDY  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
