<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Hillary Interview a Political Move  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- An unidentified confidante of Hillary Rodham  
Clinton said the first lady's candid interview with Talk magazine 
about her husband's infidelities was a political calculation to put 
personal questions to rest before they popped up in her Senate 
campaign. Mrs. Clinton called her husband's adultery ``a sin of 
weakness,'' and the product of emotional scars -- ``abuse,'' she 
termed it -- left by battles between his mother and grandmother when 
he was 4 years old. White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said 
President Clinton was ``comfortable with the views expressed in the 
article.'' 

</P>
<P>
	INS Officer Says He Didn't Smuggle  
</P>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- An immigration inspector was charged Monday  
with accepting $350,000 to allow thousands of pounds of marijuana 
and 20 illegal immigrants to enter the United States over the 
course of a year. Richard Lawrence Pineda, 41, pleaded innocent at 
his arraignment in federal court to charges of racketeering, drug 
and immigrant smuggling. Pineda faces life in prison if convicted. 
Pineda has worked as an inspector for the Immigration and 
Naturalization Service since 1987. 

</P>
<P>
	Sweepstakes Cos. Face Crackdown  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Legislation that calls for million-dollar  
fines for sweepstakes companies that entice consumers with 
misleading promises of riches was passed unanimously by the Senate 
on Monday. Supporters said too many people are being deceived into 
thinking they can improve their chances of winning cash, luxury 
cars, overseas vacations and other prizes by buying products 
because of mailings that often breathlessly announce that the 
recipient ``may have already won.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Russia Denies Yugoslavia Arms Sale  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Russia's top arms dealer denied Monday a report  
that the government exported anti-aircraft missiles to Yugoslavia 
shortly before NATO began its bombing campaign. Jane's Defense 
Weekly, based in Britain, reported Monday that Russia shipped parts 
for the S-300 surface-to-air missile system to the government of 
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic. A spokesman for Russia's 
Rosvooruzheniye arms company called the report ``non-scientific 
fantasies,'' the ITAR-Tass news agency reported. 

</P>
<P>
	223 Killed in India Train Collision  
</P>
<P>
	GAISAL, India (AP) -- About 200 people remained trapped inside  
the wreckage of two trains that crashed early Monday, killing 223 
people. The accident also injured 310 people, and authorities 
expected the death toll to climb. Some 2,500 passengers were on the 
trains. Officials said a signal error may have put the trains on 
the same track. 

</P>
<P>
	Report: N.Korea Upgrades Missile Base  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- A Japanese newspaper reported Tuesday North Korea  
is improving and expanding facilities at its ballistic missile 
launch base on the country's east coast. The Sankei newspaper, 
quoting unnamed Japanese and U.S. sources, said North Korea is 
constructing facilities for storing and injecting liquid fuel and 
oxidizing agents inside the compound of the launch base. U.S. and 
Japanese officials in Tokyo refused to comment. The report came 
amid fear that North Korea is preparing to test a long-range 
ballistic missile. 

</P>
<P>
	Fla. Judge: Electric Chair Not Cruel  
</P>
<P>
	ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- A judge ruled Monday that Florida's  
electric chair is not cruel or unusual punishment, saying it worked 
as intended in the bloody execution of a 344-pound killer. The 
execution of Davis, 54, who bled from his nose during his 
execution, prompted lawyers for the next man scheduled for death to 
argue that the chair is cruel and unusual punishment and that Davis 
suffered pain as he died. 

</P>
<P>
	Japan Stocks Mixed at Midday  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo share prices turned mixed after opening  
slightly higher Tuesday morning. The Nikkei fell 46.22 points to 
finish the morning session at 17,779.48. On Wall Street on Monday, 
the Dow Jones industrial average ended down 9.19 at 10,645.96. 

</P>
<P>
	Woods Beats Duval in Prime Time  
</P>
<P>
	THOUSAND OAKS, Calif. (AP) -- Tiger Woods went prime time Monday  
night, winning his showdown over David Duval under floodlights at 
Sherwood Country Club and the spotlight of a national television 
audience. Fittingly, Woods closed out a 2&AMP;1 victory on the par-3 
17th with a two-putt par. He won the first four par-3s to take a 
commanding lead, and hung on when Duval made one mistake too many. 
With a sun tucked behind the foothills, Duval conceded the match as 
the floodlights cast long shadows across the green. Whether the 
first golf event televised live in prime time by a network was a 
success won't be clear until overnight ratings for ABC Sports are 
released on Tuesday. Woods won $1.1 million, and Duval had to 
settle for $400,000. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by ELIZABETH A. KENNEDY  
  	   	
</P>
