<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Sturm Vows Not To Meddle With Teams </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Describing himself as a devoted sports fan who was  
determined to maintain local ownership, Donald Sturm vowed to 
operate the Denver Nuggets and Colorado Avalanche much like his 
other businesses: as an overseer. 
</P>
<P>
	Sturm, whose $461 million purchase of the two franchises and the  
new $160 million Pepsi Center still must be approved by the city of 
Denver and both the NBA and NHL, addressed the media for the first 
time Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Saying he planned no immediate changes in either team, Sturm  
called the Nuggets' Dan Issel and the Avalanche's Pierre Lacroix 
``very competent general managers'' and said he would defer to them 
on player personnel matters. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm probably going to be the same kind of owner I've been in  
my other businesses,'' said Sturm, 67, who made his fortune in 
telecommunications and banking and lives in Denver. 
</P>
<P>
	``Somebody gave me the advice in the newspaper that I ought to  
get the best people and give them authority and responsibility. 
Well, that's about what I've done in everything I've been involved 
in. 
</P>
<P>
	``I oversee things. I want to know what the strategic plans are.  
I want to know what the budgets are. I want to know why there's 
going to be deviations there. But on a day-to-day basis, I'm not a 
micromanager.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked if he intended to be a visible owner like the New York  
Yankees' George Steinbrenner or more private, he said, ``I have no 
concept of that. I'm going to be my own person and handle it as I 
see it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sturm, a low-key billionaire who has stayed out of the public  
eye until now, admitted he isn't comfortable in the spotlight. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been in business for over 40 years, and I've been  
involved in many major transactions, some a lot larger than this 
one,'' Sturm said. ``But this is my first press conference. So be 
kind to me, be gentle. 
</P>
<P>
	``I must admit to you that I didn't expect the notoriety that  
we're getting. Maybe I was naive. I hope that once these events 
pass it will become more of a stable situation and we won't find 
our names all over the place every day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In April, Ascent Entertainment Group believed it had sold the  
three properties to Wal-Mart heirs Bill and Nancy Laurie of 
Columbia, Mo., for $400 million. However, after Ascent shareholders 
sued, saying the price was too low, the sale was set aside and a 
two-stage bidding process was established. 
</P>
<P>
	Sturm, whose inquiries into purchasing the properties originally  
were rebuffed during Ascent's negotiations with the Lauries, then 
prevailed in the first round over two other groups, one of which 
included former Broncos quarterback John Elway. 
</P>
<P>
	That gave Sturm the right to advance to the second stage and  
engage in a bidding war with the Lauries, but they declined to 
participate. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wasn't shocked at all,'' Sturm said when asked about the  
Lauries' abruptly withdrawal. ``I must admit to you that part of my 
strategy was to bring in a number that perhaps would dissuade the 
Lauries from bidding. I've done that before in other 
transactions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sturm said he had two principal reasons for purchasing the  
Nuggets, Avalanche and Pepsi Center. 
</P>
<P>
	``These are Colorado assets, and they ought to be owned by  
somebody in the community,'' he said. ``The other reason is the 
intense interest that I have had and continue to have in sports. 
You name it, I've played it. I grew up in Brooklyn, N.Y., and I 
played street hockey on roller skates. I played high school 
basketball. I stopped playing three-man basketball maybe 10 or 15 
years ago, but I'm still teaching my son, who is going to be 9 
years old, the art, assuming I have any, of basketball. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been to the last two Broncos' championship games, and  
I've been to the French Open and Wimbledon. So I have a long-term 
interest in sports and I love the games. I watch a lot of sports on 
television. I find sports to be extremely entertaining and 
relaxing.'' 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
