<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico Beats U.S. 1-0 in Overtime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- The new kid on the block won the respect of  
the big boys, even if it lost the fight. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States lost to Mexico 1-0 in sudden death overtime  
Sunday at Azteca Stadium in the semifinals of the FIFA 
Confederations Soccer Cup, but gained respect as a powerful 
opponent. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. plays Saudi Arabia in the third-place game Wednesday,  
while Mexico and Brazil play for the title. 
</P>
<P>
	Brazil routed Saudi Arabia 8-2 in the other semifinal in  
Guadalajara, with Ronaldinho scoring three times and Alex twice. 
</P>
<P>
	With less then 48 hours of rest, the Americans faced a Mexican  
squad that has never lost to the United States at Azteca Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	Goalie Kasey Keller inspired a solid U.S. defense that survived  
a Mexican siege for 95 minutes and occasionally threatened the 
Mexican net. 
</P>
<P>
	But in the sixth minute of overtime, Cuauhtemoc Blanco pushed a  
loose ball into the net to dash the Americans' hopes. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought it was a very good game,'' U.S. coach Bruce Arena  
said. ``There were two champions out there. Both teams played well. 
I congratulate Mexico for a very fine victory.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Blanco had been tied up by Jeff Agoos and later Eddie Lewis for  
most of the game. But he broke through early in overtime. 
</P>
<P>
	He first tried to kick the loose ball with his right foot, but  
it bounced off a defender as Keller went to his left. Blanco then 
pushed the ball in for his fifth goal of the tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	``Their goalie played very well,'' Mexico coach Manuel Lapuente  
said. ``It was a tough game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The loss dropped the Americans' record to 6-3-1 this season and  
to 0-16-1 at Azteca. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. got to the semifinals by defeating New Zealand 2-1,  
losing to world champion Brazil 2-1 and then shocking Germany 2-0 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Cobi Jones and Frankie Hejduk missed with wide shots during a  
stretch, but the U.S. attackers never posed a serious threat to 
Mexican goalie Jorge Campos. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 53rd minute, Jones got away down the left side. He passed  
to Ernie Stewart whose clear shot was stopped by Campos. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones took advantage of a Mexican mistake in the 66th minute and  
swept down the left side. But his lob went high over the crossbar. 
</P>
<P>
	Arena criticized FIFA organizers saying, ``the schedule was not  
well thought out.'' He said his players did not have enough time to 
adjust to Mexico City's 7,350-feet altitude or have enough rest 
after playing Germany on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Not to be disrespectful to FIFA, but the tournament is very  
unfair to the players,'' Arena said. ``It has been a great stay for 
us in Mexico. The competition has been great to help build our 
team. Unfortunately, we have not been able to put our full team 
together.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brazil suffered an early shock when Saudi Arabia tied it 2-2  
early in the first, but recovered for an 8-2 route. 
</P>
<P>
	Ronaldinho scored three times and Alex twice, and goals also  
came from Joao Carlos, Ze Roberto and Roni. Marzouk Al Otaibi 
scored twice for the Saudis -- the first points Brazil has given up 
in the entire tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm very happy,'' Ronaldinho said. ``It was a good team and a  
tough game. Now we have to do everything we can to come out of here 
as champions.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
