<HEADLINE> Report: Magic May Trade Anderson </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- Nick Anderson, the only player remaining in  
Orlando from the Magic's inaugural season, is reportedly on the 
verge of being traded to the Sacramento Kings for Tariq 
Abdul-Wahad. 
</P>
<P>
	The Orlando Sentinel reported Monday that both teams had agreed  
to the deal, but an announcement could be delayed by salary cap 
complications. The Magic, rebuilding after losing in the first 
round of the playoffs, had no comment on the report. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not going to comment on speculation regarding any player  
transaction,'' director of media relations Joel Glass told The 
Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	Anderson, who has averaged 15.4 points and 5.3 rebounds in 10  
NBA seasons, was the first college draft pick of the expansion 
Magic in 1989. 
</P>
<P>
	The move to get the 24-year-old Abdul-Wahad would be in line  
with Orlando's commitment to put a younger, more athletic team on 
the floor under new coach Doc Rivers. 
</P>
<P>
	``The talk (of a trade) followed me throughout my career in  
Orlando,'' Anderson told the Sentinel on Monday from Los Angeles, 
where he played in a charity basketball game Sunday night. ``It 
seemed that every year, I was going somewhere else. Maybe now it 
has finally happened. I love Orlando, but I'll be going to a pretty 
good situation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With the Kings, the 31-year-old Anderson would be united with  
good friend Jason Williams, the former University of Florida star 
who lived in Orlando with Anderson before Williams' rookie season 
with Sacramento. 
</P>
<P>
	Abdul-Wahad has played two seasons with the Kings, who made him  
the 11th pick in the 1997 draft. He played two seasons at Michigan 
and his final two at San Jose State. He changed his name from 
Olivier Saint-Jean early in his rookie year. 
</P>
<P>
	As a starter with the Kings last season, Abdul-Wahad averaged  
9.3 points and 3.8 rebounds. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
