<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Up 77.25; Nasdaq Up 9.70 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rose solidly today, recovering from some  
of last week's big losses, after a new report suggested the economy 
has not expanded quite as fast as market watchers had feared. 
</P>
<P>
	At 3 p.m. on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
up 77.25 at 10,732.40. The index had risen as much as 136 points 
earlier in the session. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were modestly higher. The Standard &AMP;  
Poor's 500 index was up 9.21 at 1,337.93, and the Nasdaq composite 
index was up 9.70 at 2,648.19. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, stocks reeled amid a growing belief that hints of  
inflation will prompt the Federal Reserve to raise interest rates 
when its policy-making group meets later this month. The Dow fell 
255.81 points, or 2.3 percent, for the week, and the Nasdaq lost 
53.91 points, or 2 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, stocks rebounded from a sluggish opening when the  
National Association of Purchasing Management said the U.S. 
manufacturing sector grew in July for the sixth consecutive month, 
but not as strongly as most analysts expected. 
</P>
<P>
	The market had expected that the report, which gauges  
manufacturing activity, would show continued economic expansion and 
raise the likelihood of the Federal Reserve hiking interest rates 
later this year. The report is the first reading on the U.S. 
economy's performance for July. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's the excuse for some buying today,'' said William  
Meehan, chief market analyst for Cantor Fitzgerald, who said 
investors were also lured by buying opportunities resulting from 
last week's steep market losses. 
</P>
<P>
	Bond prices also rebounded once the report was released. The  
yield on the 30-year Treasury bond, which had reached 6.17 percent 
this morning, dropped back to 6.12 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The high yields on bonds have been contributing to a difficult  
environment for stocks, presenting an attractive and less volatile 
investment vehicle. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial stocks, which were battered last week as the threat of  
higher interest rates rattled the market, rose today. Chase 
Manhattan was up 1 at 78 1/16. Morgan Stanley Dean Witter gained 
13/16 to 91 1/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors seeking bargains boosted Daimler Chrysler 2 3/4 to 74 7/8 on  
the New York Stock Exchange. The automaker's shares slid last week 
after the company reported flat operating earnings. 
</P>
<P>
	Sears rose 1 7/8 to 42 3/8 following reports that the company will cut  
10 percent of the work force at its headquarters. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 4-to-3 margin on the  
NYSE, where volume came to 491.09 million shares, behind Friday's 
quiet pace. 
</P>
<P>
	Meehan said the low volume indicated many investors are staying  
out of the market for now and looking ahead to the Aug. 24 meeting 
of the Fed's Open Market Committee, which sets interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	``Volume is sluggish and will remain so until Aug. 24 unless we  
get some really negative news,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index was up 2.71 at 628.78, and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index was down 4.17 at 784.06. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000, which measures the performance of smaller  
companies, slipped 1.30 to 443.47. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
