<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Soccer Coach, Directors Quit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAIRO, Egypt (AP) -- The board of directors of the Egyptian  
Football Federation and the team's coach resigned Monday amid 
widespread shock at Egypt's 5-1 defeat against Saudi Arabia at the 
Confederations Cup tournament in Mexico last week. 
</P>
<P>
	The team returned home Sunday to shouts of ``shame, shame'' from  
disappointed fans and blistering criticism in the local media for 
its unexpectedly poor performance. 
</P>
<P>
	Two men in the Mediterranean city of Alexandria were so saddened  
by the defeat that they reportedly died of heart attacks, according 
to Egypt's leading Al-Ahram newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
	President Hosni Mubarak demanded Sunday an urgent report from  
Prime Minister Kamal el-Ganzoury detailing why the team, which 
returned in triumph in February 1998 after winning the African Cup 
soccer tournament, suffered such a humiliating loss. 
</P>
<P>
	Following a meeting of EFF's board of directors, its president,  
Samir Zaher, headed to el-Ganzoury's office to hand in the 
resignation of the nine-member body. The team's coach, Mahmoud 
el-Gohary, also resigned. 
</P>
<P>
	The Youth and Sports Committee at the People's Assembly, or  
parliament, will hold an emergency meeting on Thursday to discuss 
``the reasons for the heavy defeat of the Egyptian soccer team,'' 
said the head of the committee, Abdul-Rahim al-Ghoul. 
</P>
<P>
	The players complained that the criticism was too harsh, noting  
that Paraguayan referee Ubaldo Aquino expelled three Egyptian 
players during the game, leaving only eight to compete against 
Saudi Arabia's 11 players. 
</P>
<P>
	Egypt did not qualify to the second round of the tournament  
after it tied 2-2 with Bolivia and Mexico and following its loss to 
Saudi Arabia. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
