<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 09:30:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Women's Basketball Team Loses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WINNIPEG, Manitoba (AP) -- His team trailed by a point, he was  
trapped near the basket with no place to go. 
</P>
<P>
	For Travis Williams, it was shoot or die. So he shot.  
</P>
<P>
	Williams pump faked and then knifed between two defenders for  
the go-ahead basket as the United States beat Brazil 73-71 Sunday 
night for a key victory in Pan American Games basketball. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was open, but they submerged real quick and I had nowhere to  
throw the ball,'' Williams said. ``There was no way out. I had no 
choice but to go up with it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. women had a much easier time, beating the Dominican  
Republic 92-80 to clinch a berth in the medal round. But the 
Americans (2-2) couldn't hold a 16-point lead against Brazil today 
and lost 77-72. 
</P>
<P>
	Brazil, which came from 21 points down to beat Cuba earlier in  
the tournament, slowed the United States with a zone defense in the 
second half and scored six straight points in the final 2:11 to 
take the lead. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams' basket with 20 seconds left gave the U.S. men a 72-71  
lead, and then Doug Smith made the defensive play of the game, 
sliding over from the weak side to block Tesch Aylton's driving 
layup. 
</P>
<P>
	Where did Smith come from? That's what U.S. coach Mo McHone  
would like to know. 
</P>
<P>
	``What a great play,'' McHone said. ``I've been around him a  
long time and I don't know if I've ever seen Doug block a shot. I 
wasn't expecting that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Smith slapped the ball to teammate Damon Bailey, who got fouled  
and sank a free throw with six seconds remaining. Brazil still had 
time, but Vanderlei Mazzuchini lost the ball driving to the basket 
and Williams grabbed it. 
</P>
<P>
	Bailey and Michael Hawkins scored 13 points each to lead the  
Americans, who are 2-0 with one game left in their four-team pool. 
While the victory didn't assure the United States of a berth in the 
medal round, it puts them in great position to get there. 
</P>
<P>
	``We told our guys going in that whoever won this game would  
probably be the top seed in our pool,'' said McHone, whose team is 
made up of CBA players. ``Brazil beat the Dominican Republic and we 
beat Cuba, so we felt like we were playing for the No. 1 
position.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It almost didn't happen. Brazil, getting the support of the fans  
who stayed after Canada's game, rallied from an 11-point deficit by 
getting the Americans in foul trouble and making their free throws. 
</P>
<P>
	Two of the United States' best inside players, 7-foot Mikki  
Moore and burly Byron Houston, committed late fouls. Luckily for 
the Americans, the 6-10 Smith stayed in. 
</P>
<P>
	``Tremendous help defense,'' Hawkins said of Smith. ``You can't  
stress that enough. That was the game right there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the women's game with the Dominican Republic, the Americans  
were taller and deeper than their opponent and capitalized by 
taking the ball to the basket for a succession of layups and 
close-in shots. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States, bouncing back from a 95-64 loss to Cuba that  
was its worst ever in Pan Ams play, shot 52 percent and only two of 
its 35 baskets came from beyond 10 feet -- a pair of 3-pointers by 
Michelle Marciniak. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we really wanted to redeem ourselves more than  
anything,'' said Lynn Pride, who led the Americans with 20 points 
and 11 rebounds. ``It was a real confidence booster.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Marciniak scored 16 points, Danielle McCulley had 11 and Edwina  
Brown 10. 
</P>
<P>
	Against Cuba, the United States missed some good shots early,  
fell behind 14-3 and never recovered. The Americans trailed again 
on Sunday, but their early shots were falling and they took control 
midway through the first half by scoring on four straight fast 
breaks to finish a 12-0 run. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought we felt good about what we were doing,'' U.S. coach  
Nell Fortner said. ``They were much more confident with their 
transition game and just being able to really get the ball to the 
hole and get it inside.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The strong inside play enabled the United States to withstand  
Teresa Duran's 33 points for the Dominican Republic. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
