<DOCNO> APW19990802.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 15:20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jets Re-Sign Keith Byars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. (AP) -- Over the first three days of training  
camp, New York Jets coach Bill Parcells lost two prime candidates 
for the F-back position. On Sunday night, he called an old friend. 
</P>
<P>
	Parcells announced Monday that he has re-signed 14-year veteran  
Keith Byars, the team's starting fullback last season, to a 
one-year contract. 
</P>
<P>
	An All-Pro with the Philadelphia Eagles, Byars immediately steps  
back into his starting role in the Jets offense, a hybrid 
fullback-tight end spot. Serving primarily as a blocker for running 
back Curtis Martin, Byars rushed for 34 yards on four carries last 
year, adding 258 yards and three touchdowns on 26 catches. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been talking to Keith in the spring and (Sunday) a little  
bit,'' Parcells said. ``We've been on the same page. He knew that 
if I couldn't find what I wanted, I'd call. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's like every other vet. I told him, `You're going to have  
to show me you can still do something.' He understands that. He 
knows I'm going to be patient with him and give him some time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 6-foot-1, 255-pound Byars, who also played two seasons for  
Parcells with the New England Patriots, was en route to the Jets 
camp from his home in Cherry Hill, N.J., on Monday and was 
unavailable for comment. 
</P>
<P>
	The need for Byars heightened when, in a two-day span, former  
first-round draft pick Johnny Mitchell quit and left camp and 
second-year player Blake Spence partially separated his right 
shoulder. Mitchell was officially waived by the Jets Monday, while 
Spence faces up to a month of rehabilitation. 
</P>
<P>
	Veteran Richie Anderson also is working at F-back. But, Parcells  
said, ``I can't risk going into the season with just one guy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Neither Spence nor Anderson would comment Monday.  
</P>
<P>
	Soured by his costly fumble after a reception in the Jets' 23-10  
conference championship game loss to the Denver Broncos, Byars said 
he wasn't sure if he wanted to continue to play football. During 
the offseason, however, the ex-Ohio State standout continued to 
work out alongside receiver Cris Carter of the Minnesota Vikings, 
an old friend from their days in Philadelphia. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't ever tell players when it's time for them to do  
something,'' Parcells said. ``I only tell them what I'm going to 
do. I told Keith at the end of the season I was going to try to 
replace him if I could. I was looking for younger players, more 
cap-friendly players. Keith always said he wanted to play if he 
could. 
</P>
<P>
	``There were certain situations I don't think Keith would go  
back into, like a team just starting to come up,'' Parcells added. 
``He doesn't want to go through that. He wanted to be someplace 
where he thought he had a chance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Jets are favored to repeat as AFC East champions, and are  
forecast by many as the favorite to represent the conference in the 
Super Bowl. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no question I'm very excited about Keith coming  
back,'' quarterback Vinny Testaverde said. ``He was a big part of 
our offense last year and he's a leader, a veteran and a player 
that can help our offense like he did a year ago.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
