<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tomko Makes Reds Feel Better </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Juan Guzman will make the Cincinnati Reds'  
rotation whole. Brett Tomko could make it much more dangerous. 
</P>
<P>
	A few hours after the Reds got Guzman from Baltimore in a trade  
to restock their rotation, Tomko pitched the second complete game 
of his career Sunday to provide another measure of hope. 
</P>
<P>
	If the Reds are to stay in contention in the NL Central, Tomko  
is going to have to come through in the last two months. 
</P>
<P>
	``Last year, when we had (Pete) Harnisch or Tomko going, you  
knew you had a chance to win,'' manager Jack McKeon said. ``Now, 
you can say that again. Sometimes guys go into ruts and it takes a 
while for them to work out of them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It's taken Tomko half of a season to get out of his.  
</P>
<P>
	When Harnisch had to be scratched from his opening day start,  
Tomko took over and took the loss, lasting only 3 2-3 innings. It 
was a bad beginning that only got worse. 
</P>
<P>
	He was 0-1 in five starts with a 7.76 earned run average when  
the Reds optioned him to Triple-A Indianapolis on April 29. The 
best young pitcher in the organization was getting a wake-up call. 
</P>
<P>
	The right-hander was still erratic when he returned on May 16.  
He would pitch well one game, then give up five homers to the New 
York Mets in his next outing. 
</P>
<P>
	Things have smoothed out in his last four starts. Tomko has  
given up three or fewer runs each time out. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's got his confidence again,'' McKeon said. ``He's pitching  
the way he pitched last year. It's nice to see the Brett Tomko that 
we're used to seeing. He's pitched four or five pretty good 
ballgames in a row.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tomko was 11-7 with a 3.43 ERA as a rookie in 1997 and 13-12  
with a 4.44 ERA last season as the Reds began rebuilding. They need 
him on top of his game now that they're contending. 
</P>
<P>
	Harnisch is limited by a sore shoulder that might need surgery  
after the season. Steve Avery and Steve Parris are on the disabled 
list. Ron Villone has been erratic as he's tried to adjust to 
starting. Denny Neagle just returned after a second stint on the 
disabled list because of a weak shoulder. 
</P>
<P>
	The Reds have never needed him more.  
</P>
<P>
	``I know everybody's been pulling for me,'' Tomko said. ``(Sean)  
Casey is always yelling at me to stay focused. It's a big push 
knowing your teammates are behind you. I'm just trying to stay 
relaxed, see the strike zone and throw the ball.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He allowed only five hits Sunday in a 9-1 victory over San  
Francisco, only his second complete game in 73 career starts. He 
threw 126 pitches on a steamy afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	He won his manager over as well.  
</P>
<P>
	``I don't worry about Tomko anymore,'' McKeon said. ``What I  
see, I like. In his last three or four starts, he's been 
consistent. He's realized that if you go after the hitters, you can 
beat them.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
