<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Another Defection From Cuban Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WINNIPEG, Manitoba (AP) -- Cuban officials denounced organizers  
of the Pan American Games on Monday after defections and 
disappearances that have plagued the team. 
</P>
<P>
	With 19-year-old pitcher Danys Baez leaving the world champion  
baseball team, and in the wake of a demonstration at the ballpark 
by a man carrying a sign saying ``Human Right First,'' the Cubans 
insisted that organizers tighten security. They also criticized 
officials for failing to stop the demonstrator from disrupting 
Sunday's semifinal victory over Canada. 
</P>
<P>
	``Cuban athletes will not permit anyone or anything to humiliate  
them ... if their dignity is at stake,'' a statement from the Cuban 
delegation said. ``From now on we will react with full energy to 
provocations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	They already did that Sunday night as four Cubans got into a  
street fight with the demonstrator. The police said the protester 
was speaking to someone when the Cubans noticed him and ``became 
involved in a dispute. Prior to police arriving there was a 
physical confrontation between those parties that was brought under 
control immediately.'' 
</P>
<P>
	No charges were filed, but the protester, who police said gave a  
Miami address, was detained by immigration authorities and was in 
custody. 
</P>
<P>
	Sports agent Joe Cubas, responsible for helping many Cubans  
defect to the United States, claimed in a release Monday that Baez 
sought asylum in Canada after the semifinal win. Although 
immigration officials were not available for confirmation -- Monday 
was a civic holiday -- Baez spoke to Miami television station WSCV 
51 via telephone and said he was moving to the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to tell the people of Miami that another Cuban in  
search of freedom is about to become part of the people of Miami,'' 
Baez said. ``Wait for me over there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Baez's departure brings to eight the number of Cubans to leave  
that nation's delegation during the games. Runner Michal Ortiz, an 
unidentified female artistic gymnast and a soccer goalkeeper -- the 
goalies here were Rene Castro and Rodney Valdes -- also left the 
team on the weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cubans met the United States for the baseball gold medal at  
night. 
</P>
<P>
	Canadian roller hockey goalkeeper Steve Vezina apologized for  
testing positive for three banned substances, costing his team a 
gold medal. At a news conference in Saint-Adele, Quebec, Vezina 
said, ``Those actions were not up to a high standard of an athlete 
that represents Canada.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It apparently wasn't enough for teammate Kevin Kerr.  
</P>
<P>
	``He ruined the chance of a lifetime for nine guys,'' Kerr said.  
``I know he's my teammate and I should be sticking up for him. I 
know I, along with nine other guys, we're clean. We did it the way 
we were supposed to do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A Canadian Broadcasting Corporation report said Juana Rosario of  
the Dominican Republic, winner of the women's high jump, failed the 
`A' portion of her drug test. Games officials would not confirm 
that report; rarely is drugging information made avilable before 
the `B' sample is tested. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. women's soccer team advanced to the gold medal game by  
beating Costa Rica 2-0. Marcia Wallis and Kim Patrick scored for 
the Americans, who outshot Costa Rica 22-0 in the second half and 
34-1 for the game. 
</P>
<P>
	Mexico beat Canada in a shootout for the other spot in the  
finals, but Canada's baseball team beat Mexico 9-2 for the bronze 
medal. 
</P>
<P>
	The world champion American softball squad gave up its first run  
in 100 innings of Pan Ams competition, but still won easily, 8-1 
over Colombia. Lori Harrigan pitched a three-hitter, striking out 
16. 
</P>
<P>
	Tennis phenom Alexandra Stevenson got her first test at the Pan  
Ams, needing a third-set tiebreaker to edge Renata Kolbovic of 
Canada 7-6 (9-7), 4-6, 7-6 (7-4). She advanced to the semifinals, 
but teammate Lilia Osterloh lost to Maria Vento of Venezuela 6-4, 
6-0. 
</P>
<P>
	In men's action, Bob Bryan beat Mexico's Marco Osorio 6-2, 6-3,  
and Cecil Mamiit beat Adrian Garcia of Chile 6-2, 7-6 (7-4). 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. women played their best basketball game so far, but  
couldn't hold a 16-point lead and lost to Brazil 77-72. 
</P>
<P>
	Brazil's zone defense in the second half slowed down the  
Americans (2-2). The Brazilians chipped away steadily before going 
ahead for good with a 6-0 run in the final two minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think this team played like they're capable of playing,''  
said U.S. coach Nell Fortner, whose team already has made the medal 
round. ``Take away some defensive errors in the second half and we 
win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Americans collected one gold, by Ed Moses in the 100-meter  
breaststroke in games record time (1:00.99), and four silvers in 
swimming. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
