<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 07:30:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Four Die in Plane Crash in Ohio </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NORTH LIMA, Ohio (AP) -- Investigators examined the engine of a  
wrecked small airplane today to determine why the craft plunged 
into a cornfield shortly after taking off, killing four. 
</P>
<P>
	The six-seat Piper Cherokee went down Sunday about a half-mile  
north of the runway at Youngstown Elser-Metro Airfield. 
</P>
<P>
	Witnesses gave conflicting reports about whether the plane's  
engine was running when it went down, said Trooper Howard Craft. 
</P>
<P>
	Representatives of the National Transportation Safety Board and  
the Federal Aviation Administration were at the scene today, 
checking the engine and other wreckage. 
</P>
<P>
	Adam Wetzl, 57, said he heard the plane from his home near the  
crash site. 
</P>
<P>
	``His engines were roaring. It looked like he couldn't get  
enough elevation,'' said Wetzl. 
</P>
<P>
	He called 911 after hearing the crash. ``I jumped up on a hay  
wagon to see where he went down,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Rescue workers had to trample 6-foot-tall corn stalks in an area  
about the size of half a football field to so medical helicopters 
could land. 
</P>
<P>
	The plane was flying from Oshkosh, Wis., to Pennsylvania and had  
stopped to refuel at the airport in North Lima, about 65 miles 
southeast of Cleveland, said Highway Patrol Lt. Brian Girts. 
</P>
<P>
	The victims were identified as Lendon Pridgen, 43, of  
Collegeville, Pa., believed to be the pilot; Daniel Diggin, 56, of 
Chester, Md.; Kenneth Tubman, 47, of Norristown, Pa., and Pridgen's 
stepson, Anthony Cipparone, 15, of Collegeville, Pa. 
</P>
<P>
	The only survivor, Tyler P. Johnson, 15, of Perkiomenville, Pa.,  
Pridgen's nephew, was in serious condition today at MetroHealth 
Medical Center in Cleveland, a nursing supervisor said 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
