<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Drug Test Takes Away Canada Medal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WINNIPEG, Manitoba (AP) -- Steve Vezina broke no laws, his agent  
claims. 
</P>
<P>
	But the professional hockey player has broken a few hearts and  
tarnished the host country at the 13th Pan American Games. 
</P>
<P>
	Vezina, whose urine sample revealed two stimulants and an  
enormous quantity of anabolic steroid, cost Canada the gold medal 
in roller hockey. The United States, which fell to the Canadians 
7-6 in the final, was awarded the title Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``He feels sorry for his teammates, his coach and his country,  
but he didn't take any illegal substance, law-wise,'' agent Paul 
Hamel told The Canadian Press. 
</P>
<P>
	A urine sample showed unacceptable levels of both  
pseudo-ephedrine and ephedrine, contained in over-the-counter 
decongestants such as Sudafed that professional hockey players 
often use as stimulants. 
</P>
<P>
	There was also a massive amount of Nandrolone, a steroid that  
builds muscles and increases strength. 
</P>
<P>
	Vezina said at his drug test that he had taken Sudafed prior to  
competition. He will be subject to an automatic four-year ban, but 
that would not appear to affect his pro career. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe the only mistake he did was not being aware Sudafed was  
not legal for the Pan Am Games,'' Hamel said. ``Keep in mind Steve 
is a professional hockey player and not used to competing with the 
amateurs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Canadian Broadcasting Company reported that Juana Rosario,  
the winner of the women's high jump, tested positive for illegal 
substances. The CBC said her A sample came out positive and now her 
B-sample must be tested. If it comes back positive as well, she 
would be stripped of her medal. 
</P>
<P>
	Games officials would not comment on the report.  
</P>
<P>
	Mario Vazquez Rana, president of the Pan American Sports  
Organization, said professional athletes must adhere to the games' 
rules. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't say he did it because he was a professional,'' Rana  
said. ``He was foolish and he made a mistake.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The level of steroids in the drug test stunned Canadian  
officials, erasing any thoughts of an appeal in the case. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a very large amount,'' said Andrew Pipe, chair of the  
Canadian Centre for Ethics and Sport. ``It is probably the largest 
level that I have ever seen reported.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Canadian Olympic Association officials now must reclaim the gold  
medals from the 10 members of the roller hockey team. Argentina 
gets the silver and Brazil the bronze. 
</P>
<P>
	Vezina, 23, is a distant relative of Georges Vezina, the Hall of  
Fame goaltender after whom the Vezina Trophy is named. In the last 
six years he's been a hockey vagabond, playing for 12 teams in 
eight leagues. 
</P>
<P>
	He now plays ice hockey for the Utah Grizzlies of the  
International Hockey League and roller hockey for the Buffalo Wings 
of Roller Hockey International. 
</P>
<P>
	``It comes as a big shock ... Steve is not an abuser of anabolic  
steroids,'' said Lou Franceschetti, his coach with the Wings. 
</P>
<P>
	``Until we have a chance to gather all of the facts and speak to  
everyone involved, Steve Vezina is scheduled to be in goal Friday 
against Dallas,'' Wings vice president of operations Benny Gulakiw 
added. 
</P>
<P>
	The episode is a body blow for in-line hockey, which hoped to  
use its Pan Am debut as a springboard to the Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is unfortunate that due to the actions and poor judgment on  
the part of one player the entire team must suffer the 
consequences,'' said Maxine McKenzie, Canada's team leader for 
roller sports. 
</P>
<P>
	Scott Burfoot, a member of the Canadian team, was stunned by the  
news, which he got by telephone from his sobbing wife. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel like I've been kicked in the stomach,'' he said when  
reached in Grand Rapids, Mich., where he was conducting a hockey 
clinic. Burfoot said giving up the gold medal will be ``the hardest 
thing I'll probably ever have to do.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
