<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fla. Judge: Electric Chair Not Cruel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- A judge ruled Monday that Florida's  
electric chair is not cruel and unusual punishment, saying it 
worked as intended in the bloody execution of a 344-pound killer. 
</P>
<P>
	``Allen Lee Davis did not suffer any conscious pain while being  
electrocuted in Florida's electric chair,'' Judge Clarence Johnson 
ruled. ``Rather, he suffered instantaneous and painless death once 
the current was applied to him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The execution of Davis, 54, who bled from his nose during his  
execution, prompted lawyers for the next man scheduled for death to 
argue that the chair is cruel and unusual punishment and that Davis 
suffered pain as he died. 
</P>
<P>
	The Florida Supreme Court ordered a hearing held by Johnson, a  
retired circuit judge. The high court will still hear arguments on 
the constitutionality of the electric chair. That hearing is 
scheduled for Aug. 24. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Monday's ruling will receive substantial weight by the  
high court, according to Assistant Attorney General Kenneth 
Nunnelley. 
</P>
<P>
	``The burden is going to be on the losing party to convince the  
Florida Supreme Court that the circuit court is wrong,'' Nunnelley 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	David was executed July 8 for murdering a pregnant woman and her  
two daughters in Jacksonville in 1982. Thomas Provenzano, 50, is 
awaiting execution for a 1984 shooting spree in an Orlando 
courtroom that killed two bailiffs and left another paralyzed. 
</P>
<P>
	Martin McClain, one of Provenzano's attorneys, said he believed  
the high court will overturn the judge's order. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am hopeful, and or optimistic, that the Florida Supreme  
Court will see things differently,'' McClain said. 
</P>
<P>
	The attorneys said photos of Davis following the execution  
showed him grimacing as a leather mouthstrap covered his mouth and 
pushed up against his nose. They argued that the photos indicated 
Davis suffocated before electricity was sent to his body. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's difficult to rectify the photos with any state position  
that this is a humane or a dignified death,'' said lawyer Harry 
Brody, who also represents Provenzano. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorneys for the state argued there is no evidence that Davis  
suffocated. They said the mouth strap is necessary to keep an 
inmate's head in place during execution. The judge agreed, but 
suggested a smaller mouthstrap might be preferable. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge also concluded the electrical current did not cause  
Davis' nose to bleed, although he said he was not sure what did. 
</P>
<P>
	Following the electrocution of Pedro Medina in 1997, the state  
decided to photograph inmates if anything unusual occurred during 
an execution. When Medina was put to death, flames shot out from 
behind the leather mask covering his face. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
