<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans Soar on Weather / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures soared anew Monday on  
the Chicago Board of Trade as hot, dry weather threatened to reduce 
crop yields. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices continued their sharp gains even as temperatures in  
Midwest growing regions fell back to more-tolerable temperatures in 
the lower 80s from highs in the 90s and 100s late last week. 
</P>
<P>
	While the threat of heat stress no longer appears to be in the  
picture, vulnerable corn and soybean crops could suffer from a lack 
of rainfall. Forecasters currently say there is no chance for 
appreciable rainfall in the next week, which could affect crops 
that are seeing dangerously low moisture levels. 
</P>
<P>
	A lack of heavy rainfall in recent weeks has caused alarm bells  
to go off across farming regions. Parts of Maryland, Ohio, 
Pennsylvania, West Virginia and Virginia were declared drought 
disaster areas by U.S. Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman, with 
some farmers reporting their expected average yields had been 
reduced by half. 
</P>
<P>
	Fields in Illinois and Iowa, the two largest corn and soybean  
growing states, were expected to fare better, but dryness also 
persisted in those regions. 
</P>
<P>
	Futures investors were expected to closely examine the USDA's  
latest crop development update, which was to be released late 
Monday. The report could provide a more reliable indication of 
final production numbers. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for December delivery rose 19 cents to $2.98 3/4 a bushel;  
December corn rose the limit 12 cents to $2.26 1/2 a bushel; December 
oats jumped 6 1/2 cents to $1.18 1/4 a bushel; November soybeans rose the 
limit 30 cents to $4.63 1/4 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Beef and pork bellies advanced on the Chicago Mercantile  
Exchange, while feeder cattle retreated. 
</P>
<P>
	August live cattle rose .48 cent to 64.70 cents a pound; August  
feeder cattle fell .05 cent to 76.82 cents a pound; October lean 
hogs rose 2 cents to 45.35 cents a pound; August pork bellies rose 
the limit 3 cents to 55.12 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
