<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Highway, Railroad Safety Bills Filed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration recommended two  
bills Monday aimed at improving safety on the nation's highways and 
railroads. 
</P>
<P>
	The ``Motor Carrier Safety Act of 1999'' calls for strengthened  
commercial driver's license requirements, increased use of trip 
data recorders and a $50 million appropriation to help states 
increase roadside truck inspections. 
</P>
<P>
	The ``Federal Railroad Safety Enforcement Act of 1999'' would  
require train operators to submit fatigue-management plans, provide 
help for improving grade crossings and give industry employees new 
whistle-blower protection to encourage reporting of dangerous 
situations. 
</P>
<P>
	Referring to the highway bill, Transportation Secretary Rodney  
Slater said: ``It will help keep high-risk drivers from taking the 
wheel of a big rig.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Federal Railroad Administrator Jolene Molitoris said rail safety  
has been improving, ``but in order to achieve our goal of zero 
tolerance, our challenge must be to greatly accelerate this pace 
and build upon the lessons we have learned.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997, the last year for which official statistics are  
available, 5,355 people died in truck-related accidents on the 
nation's highways. Many accidents were caused by drivers who 
traveled too closely to trucks or cut in front of them, reducing 
the truckers' safety buffers. 
</P>
<P>
	The highway bill would strengthen trucking oversight through a  
variety of means. The administration has been criticized for being 
lax on the industry, and a recent audit found that the federal 
Office of Motor Carriers worked with truckers in an effort to foil 
a plan to change oversight of the industry. 
</P>
<P>
	One proposal would record all moving traffic convictions on a  
trucker's record, not just those committed in commercial vehicles. 
In addition, new applicants for a federal commercial driver's 
license would have to have alcohol- and drug-free driving records 
for three years prior to their application. 
</P>
<P>
	Another provision would launch a study to examine how existing  
compensation plans, such as payment-per-mile-driven, push drivers 
to operate when tired. A third proposal would require regulations 
providing for some carriers to use onboard recorders or other 
technology to manage drivers' time. 
</P>
<P>
	``This bill challenges everyone to take responsibility for  
saving lives on our nation's highways,'' said Federal Highway 
Administrator Kenneth Wykle. 
</P>
<P>
	The railroad bill seeks to address fatigue and grade-crossing  
safety through a variety of means. 
</P>
<P>
	Chief among them is asking major railroads and commuter lines to  
submit fatigue-management plans covering their train, dispatching 
service, signal and track maintenance employees. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
