<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Injury Forces Breedlove To Postpone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RENO, Nev. (AP) -- A painful bone spur has forced Craig Breedlove  
to scrap his quest for a sixth world land speed record and a return 
of the title to the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're a little disappointed. We're just going to have to  
readjust our plans, be optimistic about it and start planning for 
next year,'' Breedlove said Monday from his home in Rio Vista, 
Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	Breedlove's last attempt at the record was a dismal outing in  
the Black Rock Desert in the fall of 1997 that saw him fall far 
short of a record-breaking British effort that shattered the speed 
of sound. 
</P>
<P>
	Breedlove was the first person to reach 400, 500 and 600 mph on  
land, but the world mark has been in British hands since October 
1983, when Richard Noble streaked across the desert 100 miles north 
of Reno at 633.47 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	Two years ago, Noble handed over his car to Andy Green, his  
35-year-old protege from the Royal Air Force. Green sent shock 
waves thundering across the desert on Oct. 15, 1997, when he roared 
along the dry lake bed at 763.035 mph, becoming the first person to 
officially break the sound barrier on land. 
</P>
<P>
	On the other side of the playa, Breedlove struggled to edge  
Noble's record of 13 years earlier with a peak speed of 636 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	He took last year off to regroup financially, emotionally and  
physically. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the bone spur, pressing against a rotator cuff, had been  
a problem for about four years that he tried to control with 
physical therapy. 
</P>
<P>
	``It got to the point where it was very painful. It was keeping  
me up at night and wasn't responding to cortisone and lidocane. 
It's just got to be repaired,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	That nixed a speed run this year because of the pain involved in  
lowering himself into the cockpit of the car and, more importantly, 
the likelihood of his getting out quickly in an emergency. 
</P>
<P>
	The surgery will be conducted within the next two weeks at the  
U.C. Davis Medical Center in Sacramento, Calif. While it's a 
relatively minor procedure, the 12-week recovery time will last far 
too late into the fall to allow any runs in 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll put the time to very good use ... on the car. It'll give  
us more time to be better prepared,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	In the back of his mind, Breedlove can't dismiss turning 63 next  
March. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm in excellent health except for my shoulder. One more year  
is not going to be that detrimental. I'm in very good shape.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But he concedes a sense of urgency in his quest for one more  
outing. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously it is a diminishing return. Eventually I'm not going  
to be able to do this. I realize that time's not too far away,'' he 
said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
