<HEADLINE> Dollar rises against euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar rose against the euro Monday, boosted  
by an early rally on Wall Street and a report that eased inflation 
and interest rate worries. 
</P>
<P>
	In late New York trading, the euro was quoted at $1.0683, down  
from $1.0705 late Friday. The dollar also was quoted at 114.22 
Japanese yen, down from 114.48. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar initially followed stocks higher and held on to those  
gains against the euro even as share prices retreated and finished 
lower. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average fell 9 points on the day after  
rising as much as 136 points following a report showing that U.S. 
manufacturing businesses grew at a slower pace in July than 
analysts had expected. Investors have been edgy about signs of 
rapid economic growth that could aggravate inflationary pressures 
and prompt the Fed to nudge interest rates higher. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also was quoted at 1.4947 Swiss francs, up from  
1.4907, and 1.5048 Canadian dollars, up from 1.5046. The British 
pound fell to $1.6173 from $1.6221. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
Based on Monday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.8308 German 
marks, up from 1.8272; 6.1387 French francs, up from 6.1275. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
