<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> APME Names 10 Entries for FOI Award </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Ten entries were selected as finalists in the  
Associated Press Managing Editors association's 1998-99 Freedom of 
Information contest. 
</P>
<P>
	Their work ranges from exposing hidden records of mismanagement  
in law enforcement, to challenging a judicial order demanding prior 
restraint of publication, to joint statewide projects testing how 
well public agencies respond to citizens' requests for public 
information. 
</P>
<P>
	The top winner will be announced at the association's annual  
conference, Oct. 13-16 in Memphis, Tenn. 
</P>
<P>
	The 10 finalists:  
</P>
<P>
	--Asheville (N.C.) Citizen-Times, for its committed efforts to  
open records to the public. 
</P>
<P>
	--The Advocate, Baton Rouge, La., for its watchdog efforts on the  
state's Open Meetings Law. 
</P>
<P>
	--Courier-Post, Cherry Hill, N.J., for its examination of  
mismanagement and abuse within the Camden Police Department. 
</P>
<P>
	--The News-Sentinel, Knoxville, Tenn., for leading a two-year  
battle to open records detailing public costs for the defense of an 
accused serial killer. Efforts included resistance of a judicial 
attempt at prior restraint of publication. 
</P>
<P>
	--The Day, New London, Conn., for its battle to force a  
quasi-public agency to comply with FOI laws. 
</P>
<P>
	--Omaha (Neb.) World-Herald, for its eight-year effort to obtain  
crime statistics from the city. 
</P>
<P>
	--Star Tribune, Minneapolis, for exposing a company's attempt to  
conceal details of a $6.9 million settlement in an environmental 
case and fighting in court the company's claim that withholding 
information was intended to protect the whistleblowers involved. 
</P>
<P>
	--Waco (Texas) Tribune-Herald, for forcing a charter school to  
release records showing financial problems during a period in which 
board members met in secret. 
</P>
<P>
	Two finalists were recognized for similar projects conducted by  
separate alliances of newspapers in two states. 
</P>
<P>
	--Seven New Jersey newspapers owned by Gannett Co. tested open  
records laws in that state by asking 601 public agencies to respond 
to requests. Patterns of resistance and misapplication of the law 
were found. Participating newspapers: Asbury Park Press; The 
Courier-News, Bridgewater; Courier-Post, Cherry Hill; Home News 
Tribune, East Brunswick; Daily Record, Morristown; Ocean County 
Observer, Toms River; The Daily Journal, Vineland. 
</P>
<P>
	--Fourteen newspapers in Virginia and The Associated Press in  
Richmond conducted a statewide project with similar results, 
exposing inadequate responses by various agencies and explaining to 
readers how open records laws should work. Participating 
newspapers: Herald-Courier, Bristol; The Daily Progress, 
Charlottesville; Culpeper Star-Exponent; Danville Register &AMP; Bee; 
The Free Lance-Star, Fredericksburg; The News &AMP; Advance, Lynchburg; 
Manassas Journal Messenger; Daily Press, Newport News; The 
Virginian-Pilot, Norfolk; The Coalfield Progress, Norton; The 
News-Virginian, Waynesboro; Potomac News, Woodbridge; The Roanoke 
Times; Richmond Times-Dispatch. 
</P>
<P>
	Finalists were selected from 31 entries and covered work  
published or pursued between July 1998 and June 1999. Judges for 
APME's 29th annual contest were E.J. Mitchell, executive editor of 
the Statesman Journal in Salem, Ore., and chairman of the FOI 
Committee, and other members of the association. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990802.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 18:50:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Baby's Death in Hot Car Probed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- Police are investigating a woman who allegedly  
abandoned her 8-month-old son at a gas station, where he died 
inside her locked car while outside temperatures hit the 90s. 
</P>
<P>
	A sheriff's deputy found the boy, Senon Arteaga, in the car  
Sunday afternoon. The boy appeared to have been dead for hours. 
</P>
<P>
	Houston's high temperature was 97 Sunday. A thermometer police  
used to measure the heat inside the car only went as high as 106, 
but officers estimated the temperature to be much higher. 
</P>
<P>
	The boy's mother, Sandra Ann Arteaga, who police say was  
intoxicated, had driven to the gas station early Sunday but decided 
to take a taxi home with another of her children, who is 3. 
</P>
<P>
	Hours later, the children's father asked the woman where the  
younger child was, and the woman said she did not know but 
remembered leaving the car at the gas station, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, Ms. Arteaga, 30, was charged with reckless injury to  
a child. She faces up to 20 years in prison if convicted. Her 
arraignment was scheduled for Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In San Jose, Calif., on Sunday, a 2 1/2-year-old boy disappeared  
while playing and later died in a locked car parked in warm 
afternoon sun. 
</P>
<P>
	Luis Fernando Pineda was found unconscious on the back floor of  
the car three hours after his family began searching for him. 
Paramedics could not revive him. 
</P>
<P>
	``One minute he was playing here,'' said an aunt, Lorena  
Salgado. ``Then we could not find him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was 76 degrees when Luis disappeared, but authorities said  
the temperature inside the car could have been 95. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
