<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dole Puts Emphasis on Values </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MARSHALLTOWN, Iowa (AP) -- With a new emphasis on values,  
Elizabeth Dole said Monday that a president should use the White 
House as a ``bully pulpit'' to show the difference between right 
and wrong. ``I don't think President Clinton has been the leader 
that he should be,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Republican presidential candidate was asked her reaction to  
Hillary Rodham Clinton's discussion of her husband's affairs in an 
upcoming magazine article, mistakes that Mrs. Clinton referred to 
as ``a sin of weakness.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not even reading it or looking at it because, frankly, I'm  
focused on campaigning and the issues that are important to 
people'' Mrs. Dole said. ``In terms of what's going on in their 
marriage, that's their business.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even as she was declining to wade into the latest discussion of  
the Clinton marriage, Mrs. Dole was trotting out a new stump speech 
with a heavy emphasis on values. 
</P>
<P>
	``We really have sort of lost touch with that sort of universal  
set of rights and wrongs,'' Mrs. Dole said. ``I think right now 
that what we have to reiterate is that, while the soundness of the 
economy is very important, ... we need to reaffirm those basic 
values.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With her approach, Mrs. Dole was seeking to take advantage of a  
worrisome issue for Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
	While the economy is sound and polls show most voters happy with  
the direction the country is headed, Vice President Al Gore, lags 
in the polls. 
</P>
<P>
	Some attribute that to weariness with Clinton and White House  
scandals. The president was impeached in the wake of an affair with 
a young intern, and Mrs. Clinton's latest comments inject that 
issue back into the public debate. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Dole hammered hard at values.  
</P>
<P>
	``We've begun to lose touch with that sort of universal set of  
right and wrongs,'' she said. ``We have to lead a crusade across 
America.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If elected, Mrs. Dole said she would lead the way to ``a rebirth  
of our values.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Integrity never goes out of style,'' she said.  
</P>
<P>
	She pointed to student test scores and youth drug use as  
evidence of a fraying of the social fabric. 
</P>
<P>
	``Clearly it's a matter of leadership, using the bully pulpit to  
stress what is right and change what is wrong, and we have not had 
that kind of leadership from the president,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Dole also made it clear she was referring to personal  
characteristics that some find lacking in Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm speaking of things like integrity, honesty, respect for  
your fellow man, personal responsibility,'' said Mrs. Dole. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
