<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Calif. May Cut Sulfur in Gas Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A California agency may lower the amount of  
sulfur allowed in the state's gasoline so autos can more 
effectively cut smog-producing emissions. 
</P>
<P>
	The California Air Resources Board issued a preliminary proposal  
Monday to lower the amount of sulfur allowed in gas from a maximum 
of 80 parts per million for any single batch to a maximum of 20 to 
30 parts per million, according to documents written by the 
agency's staff. 
</P>
<P>
	The amount of sulfur allowed in gas at the pump in California  
currently is 30 parts per million on average over six months -- not 
as a per batch maximum. That average would also be reduced, 
although the preliminary draft proposal did not indicate by exactly 
how much. 
</P>
<P>
	The California Air Resources Board was to hold a public workshop  
Wednesday to hear the views of engineers for automakers, 
environmentalists and others. Its final proposal is expected by 
late October and probably would be phased in for gasoline in 2003 
or 2004, said a spokesman for the agency, Allan Hirsch. 
</P>
<P>
	California, which has the nation's worst air quality, has long  
set the pace for the strictest sulfur standard in gasoline in the 
nation. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Environmental Protection Agency recently proposed a  
national sulfur standard that would match that in California today. 
</P>
<P>
	Domestic automakers have been pushing for lower sulfur gasoline,  
arguing cars need it to allow their catalytic converters to 
effectively cut hydrocarbon and nitrogen oxide emissions. 
</P>
<P>
	With catalytic converters, emissions flow out of the engine's  
combustion chamber and over metals, such as platinum and rhodium, 
that chemically react with the gases to filter them. Sulfur can 
coat those metals, reducing their effectiveness permanently. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sulfur is the Achilles' heel of the catalytic converter,''  
Hirsch said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gasoline across the county on average has about 340 parts per  
million of sulfur, but it can be as high as 1,000 parts per million 
in some parts of the country. 
</P>
<P>
	The preliminary proposal by the California Air Resources Board  
staff also called for increasing the options available to refiners 
to reduce or eliminate oxygenates in gasoline, Hirsch said. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposal was in response to California's recent ban on MTBE,  
methyl tertiary butyl ether, used in so-called reformulated 
gasoline that allowed for a cleaner burning fuel. 
</P>
<P>
	Congress in 1990 required that gasoline sold in areas with  
severe air pollution contain a higher amount of oxygen. Oil 
companies responded by using MTBE, the most widely used additive. 
</P>
<P>
	But a study showed that the additive has affected at least  
10,000 groundwater sites throughout California, and Gov. Gray Davis 
declared it an environmental risk, banning it by the end of 2002. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990802.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 17:10:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Harricks Sever Ties With R.I. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) -- Ties between the Harrick family and the  
University of Rhode Island have been officially severed. 
</P>
<P>
	Assistant basketball coach Jim Harrick Jr. resigned over the  
weekend, according to school spokesman Mike Ballweg. 
</P>
<P>
	Ballweg does not know where the younger Harrick will go next,  
but The Providence Journal reported he is being considered for an 
assistant's position at Gonzaga. 
</P>
<P>
	On June 30, Harrick's contract expired and was not renewed.  
Instead, the contract was extended one month. That provision ended 
over the weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	``Senior has gone down to Georgia and junior has gone now,  
too,'' Ballweg said. 
</P>
<P>
	On April 1, Jim Harrick Sr. left Rhode Island to accept the head  
coaching position at the University of Georgia. He hesitated before 
finally accepting the job because of the state's anti-nepotism law 
but his son supported his father's decision anyway. 
</P>
<P>
	URI has already started the search for Harrick Jr.'s  
replacement, Ballweg said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ballweg said it was Harrick Jr.'s decision to leave the program,  
not URI's. He said Harrick submitted his resignation before URI was 
able to extend a new contract to him. 
</P>
<P>
	Coaches from several major colleges told The Journal they saw  
Harrick Jr. on the recruiting trail in July and said he spoke 
freely about the end of his employment at the school. 
</P>
<P>
	In their two years at URI, the Harricks led the Rams to two  
straight appearances in the NCAA tournament. They reached the 
regional final in 1998 and lost in the first round last season. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990802.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 09:40:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Heat Breaks in Much of Midwest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- The heat wave death toll kept rising today even  
as cooler temperatures brought an end to the heat wave across the 
Midwest and most of the East. 
</P>
<P>
	The Oklahoma Medical Examiner's Office reported today that the  
state's heat-related death toll had reached eight with the deaths 
of four people in their 70s and 80s. 
</P>
<P>
	That number, plus two more reported today in South Carolina and  
30 names added to Chicago's list on Sunday, brought the nationwide 
total since July 19 to at least 197. 
</P>
<P>
	Chicago authorities said they were sure the number of deaths  
there would go even higher. 
</P>
<P>
	A cold front that pushed across the region during the weekend  
brought much-needed relief, dropping high temperatures by 10 
degrees to 20 degrees from last week's levels. Chicago's high on 
Sunday was just 84, compared to Friday's high of 104. 
</P>
<P>
	By late morning today, temperatures were in the 70s across most  
of the Ohio Valley into the Northeast. 
</P>
<P>
	In Wisconsin, the mercury had slipped to an almost crisp 59  
degrees when Bill Hansche left for work. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today, it's just perfect,'' Hansche said Sunday as he headed  
for the Maple Grove County Club in West Salem, Wis. ``I wish you 
could box these up and bring one out every day you need one.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Louisville, Ky., the afternoon temperature was down to 78 --  
from a high of 104 on Friday and 99 on Saturday. In Missouri, where 
44 people died, temperatures returned to seasonable levels. 
</P>
<P>
	``This feels wonderful,'' said Scott Kissell as he took a Sunday  
morning walk along Brush Creek near Kansas City's Country Club 
Plaza shopping district. ``It's been nutty. A hundred and six! 
That's a little much. This is a lot better.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Deaths were reported in 20 states and many shared a tragic  
thread: People most at risk from the heat were often the ones who 
wouldn't -- or couldn't -- wrap themselves in the icy blast of an air 
conditioner. 
</P>
<P>
	Bill and Sandy Folak repeatedly offered to pay the electricity  
bill and install an air conditioner in Eddie Slautas' apartment 
above their tavern. Each time, they said, he refused. 
</P>
<P>
	``He said, `Why should I make my electric bill higher. The fan  
is good enough,''' Sandy Folak said. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday night, with his fan still running, the heat killed  
Eddie Slautas, two days before his 75th birthday. 
</P>
<P>
	Another Chicago resident, Ilko Homziak, also didn't want any  
help. 
</P>
<P>
	``I tried to get him (air) conditioning,'' said Olga Romanei of  
her 82-year-old younger brother, whose body was found in the 
upstairs room of the house they shared. ``He say, `I no want, I no 
want.''' 
</P>
<P>
	In dozens of states, authorities found heartbreaking scenes when  
worried neighbors or friends called about those missing or at risk. 
</P>
<P>
	Police in Nashville, Tenn., kicked down a door and discovered  
the body of a 95-year-old woman in her 95-degree home. Gertrude 
Williams was dressed for church and sitting in a wheelchair with an 
offering check in her hand. 
</P>
<P>
	Church members say they wanted to help Ms. Williams get an air  
conditioner but she refused, saying it would make her sneeze and 
uncomfortably cold. 
</P>
<P>
	In Newnan, Ga., a 14-year-old boy confined to a bed and  
requiring a ventilator to breathe died of heat stroke in a home 
where the electricity had been turned off by the utility company. 
</P>
<P>
	The teenager's ventilator continued to run on batteries, but the  
home's central air conditioning shut down. The boy's body 
temperature was 107 degrees when he died, the coroner said. 
</P>
<P>
	Dennis McEntire of Newnan Utilities said the power was turned  
off as a result of miscommunication. The family had moved in last 
week. 
</P>
<P>
	Six bodies were found Sunday in South Carolina, and Charleston  
County Coroner Susan Chewning said some of the victims had access 
to air conditioners but weren't using them. 
</P>
<P>
	In Chicago, where the heat wave of 1995 contributed to more than  
700 area deaths, officials said they've learned many lessons about 
helping the elderly and other vulnerable residents handle the heat. 
Mayor Richard M. Daley said people must take responsibility for 
checking up on loved ones. 
</P>
<P>
	``Why don't family members check on other family members and  
parents?'' he asked. ``Why are they calling the city to do that? 
That is the most frustrating thing in any crisis.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Phil Jackson, executive director of the Chicago Housing  
Authority, agreed. ``We found out that there is no substitute for 
human contact,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	But even that isn't always enough. The Folaks, for example,  
brought breakfast, lunch and dinner to their upstairs neighbor 
every day, including the meal the couple's daughter was bringing 
him when she discovered his body. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990802.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 18:00:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Finishing $12.6B Aid Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Many House Democrats are supporting a $12.6  
billion foreign aid bill in hopes that spending can be increased 
and anti-abortion language deleted to avoid a presidential veto. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate already has approved a similar measure but without  
the one amendment sure to bring a veto: a ban on any U.S. funding 
for groups working to liberalize abortion laws. 
</P>
<P>
	The House, voting 315-103 late Monday, rejected an effort to  
stop the government's Overseas Private Investment Corp. from 
insuring any more corporate investments abroad. Debate on the bill 
continued into the evening, but lawmakers put off votes on any 
further amendments or the final bill until Tuesday or later. 
</P>
<P>
	Several Democrats on the Appropriations Committee's foreign  
operations panel said they would support the foreign operations 
legislation in the hope it can be modified before it goes to 
President Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	In an unusual move, lawmakers last week approved a parallel  
provision that is more palatable to family planning groups that 
view the abortion language as a prohibition on free speech and an 
effort to stop family planning, not just abortions. 
</P>
<P>
	The second amendment, approved 221-208, reflects the contention  
that family planning prevents abortions. It would require that 
groups receiving aid certify only that they work to reduce the 
number of abortions. 
</P>
<P>
	The original amendment, a version of which has doomed several  
foreign affairs bills in the past five years, passed 228-220. It 
would ban aid to any group lobbying for changes in abortion laws 
even if the group uses privately raised funds. Family planning 
groups hope that language can be removed during the House-Senate 
conference committee that will shape the final bill. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration says the legislation's cuts of $1.9 billion  
from Clinton's requests would harm a wide range of foreign policy 
efforts, hurting the poorest countries and diminishing the ability 
to respond to foreign crises, to prevent nuclear smuggling, to deal 
with the Asian crisis, to expand the Peace Corps and to help 
refugees. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill's funding is $715 million below that of last year's  
bill and $20.7 billion below this year's actual spending on foreign 
assistance, including emergency appropriations. 
</P>
<P>
	A Clinton administration statement said senior advisers would  
recommend a veto if foreign operations funding is not increased. 
</P>
<P>
	``Funding at this level would seriously impair the president's  
ability to conduct an effective foreign policy,'' the statement 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	It said the bill would cut funding to international lending  
institutions by $493 million from amounts needed to meet U.S. 
commitments. 
</P>
<P>
	Other major provisions of the foreign operations bill include:  
</P>
<P>
	--$2.88 billion for Israel, representing a $120 million reduction  
in economic and a $60 million increase in military aid. 
</P>
<P>
	--$2 billion for Egypt, a $40 million reduction in economic aid  
but no change in military aid. 
</P>
<P>
	--$725 million for former Soviet states, $307 million below  
Clinton's request. It would withhold 50 percent of aid to Russia 
unless it ends missile cooperation with Iran. 
</P>
<P>
	--$680 million for child survival programs.  
</P>
<P>
	Among hotly contested provisions, the bill includes the first  
cut in funding for a military school in Fort Benning, Ga., which 
has been criticized for human rights abuses committed in Latin 
American by some of its graduates. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	The bill is H.R. 2606.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990802.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 15:00:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Packers' Robert Brooks Retires </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREEN BAY, Wis. (AP) -- Robert Brooks played football longer than  
he ever thought he would. When his body couldn't endure any more 
pain, he accepted it. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just couldn't cover it up any more,'' the Packers wide  
receiver said. ``I found myself missing so many practices and 
taking so much medication just to practice. When you get to that 
point, I think it's time to call it quits.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brooks retired Monday after seven injury-plagued seasons with  
the Green Bay Packers during which he never became the superstar 
many thought he would. He said his knees, back and hamstrings could 
no longer withstand the punishment of pro football. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can fool a lot of people, but you can't fool yourself,''  
he said. ``I'm 29 years old, and after a practice, I feel like I'm 
50.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brooks retires as the Packers' career leader in postseason  
catches and receiving yards. He is the seventh-leading receiver in 
the club's 80-year history. 
</P>
<P>
	His career followed the arc of the Packers' franchise rebirth,  
and he was one of the team's most popular players during its run to 
consecutive NFC championships and a league title. Brooks originated 
the ``Lambeau Leap,'' the Packers' trademark jump into the Lambeau 
Field stands to celebrate a touchdown. 
</P>
<P>
	``Robert has meant a great deal to this organization and to me  
personally,'' offensive coordinator Sherman Lewis said. ``If he 
couldn't perform at the level he wanted to, then I understand 
that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brooks was drafted out of South Carolina in 1992, the same year  
coach Mike Holmgren and Lewis were hired. In 1995, Brooks caught 
102 passes for a team-record 1,497 yards. 
</P>
<P>
	But the next three seasons he had just 114 catches for 1,774  
yards while missing 16 games with injuries. He had 31 receptions 
for 420 yards in 12 games last season while playing in he what 
called ``almost constant pain.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brooks participated in a team minicamp this summer and said he  
was in the best shape of his life. But when he dropped several 
balls during his first day of practice Friday at training camp, it 
was obvious something was still wrong. 
</P>
<P>
	He skipped weekend workouts and told coach Ray Rhodes on  
Saturday he would retire. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't put up the facade any more of being a tough guy,''  
Brooks said. ``I think I've done that long enough. It's allowed me 
to play in this game longer than I think anybody expected me to 
play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His departure leaves the Packers alarmingly short of depth at  
wide receiver. 
</P>
<P>
	Green Bay's top receiver, All-Pro Antonio Freeman, is in the  
midst of a contract dispute which the team may now be ready to 
resolve quickly. Freeman's agent, Joel Segal, did not immediately 
return a phone call Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Corey Bradford, Bill Schroeder, Derrick Mayes and an assortment  
of free agents and rookies are left to be quarterback Brett Favre's 
targets. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously, that concerns me a great deal,'' Lewis said. ``But  
we'll get Antonio in here and some of our young guys will step up. 
We have a fine group of receivers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Packers' first exhibition game is Aug. 14 against the New  
York Jets. 
</P>
<P>
	Brooks' injury problems began in October 1996, when he tore both  
the ACL and the patellar tendon in his right knee on the first 
offensive play of a game against San Francisco. 
</P>
<P>
	Such a catastrophic injury would have ended many careers, but  
Brooks surprised team doctors by returning for the 1997 season and 
catching 60 passes for 1,010 yards and seven touchdowns. 
</P>
<P>
	But Brooks said his gimpy knee caused him to overwork his other  
joints, leading to chronic back pain. He had arthroscopic surgery 
during training camp last year for a herniated disc, and he had a 
similar operation Jan. 6. 
</P>
<P>
	Brooks attended minicamp in June but various aches remained. He  
thought about retiring then but reconsidered after talking with 
Rhodes. 
</P>
<P>
	``They gave me the feeling as if they were counting on me,''  
Brooks said. 
</P>
<P>
	Brooks, who signed a five-year, $15 million contract in 1998,  
agreed to a $1.1 million pay cut in June, which the Packers said 
eased their salary-cap restrictions. 
</P>
<P>
	Brooks said he will keep a home in Green Bay and he plans to  
focus his energies on his interest in music and a ministry he 
recently founded. 
</P>
<P>
	``I really feel comfortable about closing this chapter of my  
life and opening whatever chapter God has for me,'' Brooks said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990802.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 18:01:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Canadian Apologizes for Scandal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAINT-ADELE, Quebec (AP) -- Steve Vezina, Canada's roller hockey  
goaltender, apologized Monday for costing his country the Pan 
American Games gold medal. 
</P>
<P>
	That didn't stop one of his teammates from lashing out at him.  
</P>
<P>
	Vezina admitted taking the over-the-counter cold remedy Sudafed  
during the games and capsules of the anabolic steroid Nandrolone, 
purchased at a pharmacy, in June. During a news conference with his 
agent, Paul Hamel, Vezina said he took Nandolone because he was 
losing weight during the busy roller hockey schedule. 
</P>
<P>
	``Those actions were not up to a high standard of an athlete  
that represents Canada,'' Vezina said. ``I would like to apologize 
for that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It apparently wasn't enough for Vezina's teammate Kevin Kerr.  
</P>
<P>
	``He ruined the chance of a lifetime for nine guys,'' Kerr said  
from Anaheim, Calif., where he plays professional roller hockey. 
``I know he's my teammate and I should be sticking up for him. I 
know I, along with nine other guys, we're clean. We did it the way 
we were supposed to do it. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's going to be guys on this team that will never have an  
opportunity to represent their country again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Canada won the Pan Ams roller hockey final 7-6 over the United  
States on July 27, with Kerr getting the game-winning goal. Roller 
hockey, played on in-line skates, has a professional summer league 
in the United States and is one of six non-Olympic sports being 
contested in Winnipeg. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday, the gold medals were taken away when officials  
announced Vezina tested positive for two stimulants and an 
abnormally high amount of Nandrolone. 
</P>
<P>
	Vezina said he could not explain why his doping test detected  
16,000 parts per million of Nandrolone, when one or two parts per 
million raises immediate suspicions. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know. I'm not a doctor,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think I'm a bad person because I did that. I don't  
think I'm a criminal because I did that. My prime object was to 
improve my performance on the ice.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't commit any crimes. I maybe just misunderstood. I took  
something I should not take when you play at the Pan Am Games. I 
did nothing wrong for my ice hockey (career).'' 
</P>
<P>
	Vezina played last season for the Utah Grizzlies of the  
International Hockey League. He also is a goalie for Roller Hockey 
International's Buffalo Wings. 
</P>
<P>
	As for the future, Hamel said his client has signed a two-year  
deal with a professional ice hockey team, but would not identify 
that team. Hamel said Vezina orignally had three offers and that 
two teams he contacted Monday still were interested in his client 
should he become available. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not going to affect his ice hockey,'' Hamel said.  
</P>
<P>
	Andrew Pipe, chairman of the Canadian Centre for Ethics and  
Sport, said Monday that blanket testing of athletes before events 
such as the Pan Am Games won't guarantee a dope-free games. 
</P>
<P>
	``Will it provide an absolute guarantee there are going to be no  
embarrassment? The answer is no,'' said Pipe, Canada's top 
anti-doping official. 
</P>
<P>
	Pipe said athletes could test clean in the days prior to a  
games, then inadvertently, or purposely, ingest a banned substance 
prior to their event. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990802.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 18:01:00 </DATE_TIME>
