<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Headlines Headlines Headlines ..... / T-Bills  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Interest rates on short-term Treasury  
securities rose in Monday's auction to the highest level in just 
over one month. 
</P>
<P>
	The Treasury Department sold $8 billion in three-month bills at  
a discount rate of 4.695 percent, up from 4.535 percent last week. 
An additional $8 billion was sold in six-month bills at a rate of 
4.750 percent, up from 4.520 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The three-month rate was the highest since June 28 when the  
bills sold for 4.750 percent. The six-month rate also was the 
highest since June 28 when the rate was 4.960. 
</P>
<P>
	The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors  
-- 4.831 percent for three-month bills with a $10,000 bill selling 
for $9,881.30, and 4.947 percent for a six-month bill selling for 
$9,759.90. 
</P>
<P>
	In a separate report, the Federal Reserve said Monday that the  
average yield for one-year Treasury bills, the most popular index 
for making changes in adjustable rate mortgages, rose to 5.07 
percent last week from 4.98 percent the previous week. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990802.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 21:30:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Christie's Opens Shop in Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- After helping liquidate artworks seized  
from bankrupt Thai finance companies, the auction house Christie's 
is bidding on a revival of the post-Asian crisis luxury market and 
setting up shop in Thailand. 
</P>
<P>
	The famed auctioneer will inaugurate its presence in Bangkok  
this weekend with auctions of paintings, rare books, maps, 
manuscripts and photographs. Thailand will host the company's 
fourth salesroom in the region after Australia, Singapore and Hong 
Kong. 
</P>
<P>
	Christie's gained the limelight in Bangkok some months back when  
it handled the auction of paintings owned by 56 finance companies 
that were closed by the government, part of the shakeout from the 
regional economic crisis that struck in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	The government's Financial Restructuring Authority, charged with  
liquidating the assets, ranging from luxury cars to condo projects, 
asked Christie's to handle the art sale. The 400 lots were expected 
to fetch $270,000, but pulled in five times that. 
</P>
<P>
	Dimitri Karukin, manager of client services for Christie's  
Thailand, said Monday that the luxury market is showing signs of 
life as the economy slowly recovers from the worst recession since 
World War II. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market is getting better,'' Karukin said. ``We don't just  
have buyers, we have sellers, too.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the first auction Saturday, Christie's will sell 286 lots of  
rare books, maps, manuscripts and photographs on Thailand from the 
collection of an unidentified single owner. 
</P>
<P>
	Choice items include a four-volume, 1873 first edition of French  
explorer Francois Garnier's account of his travels up the wilds of 
the Mekong River, with maps, plates, and plans. 
</P>
<P>
	Sunday, 146 lots of important Thai paintings, prints and  
sculpture go on the block. Two extremely rare portraits of kings 
Rama III and Rama IV being offered. No public price estimates were 
made. 
</P>
<P>
	They were painted in the early part of this century by Phra  
Soralaklikit, court painter to King Rama V, considered the greatest 
of the Chakri Dynasty monarchs. 
</P>
<P>
	There are also paintings by Thai artists Fua Haripitak, Tawee  
Nandakwang, Suchao Sisganes, Pratuan Emjaroen and Thawan Dachanee, 
with estimates ranging from $16,200 to $95,000. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990802.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 12:20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Celebrex Beats Viagra in Sales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- It didn't create a national sensation like  
Viagra, but the new arthritis pill Celebrex has surpassed the 
impotence medicine as the nation's fastest-selling new drug ever. 
</P>
<P>
	Celebrex promises pain relief with fewer stomach problems than  
other drugs. Unlike Viagra, patients take it every day and it's 
usually covered by insurance. 
</P>
<P>
	Celebrex, which was introduced in January, sold 6.86 million  
prescriptions during its first six months on the market, compared 
with 6.05 million for Viagra during its first six months, according 
to IMS Health, a research company. Celebrex began to outpace Viagra 
in prescriptions after four months. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales of Celebrex in the first six months added up to about $600  
million, said Monsanto, which co-markets the drug with Pfizer. In 
comparison, Viagra had $552 million in sales its first six months 
beginning in April 1998. Viagra is also made by Pfizer. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Celebrex and Viagra serve huge markets. Arthritis effects  
about 37 million Americans; impotence affects 30 million men. 
</P>
<P>
	But Celebrex has some key advantages.  
</P>
<P>
	Many arthritis sufferers need pain relief every day. Men only  
need to take Viagra when they plan to have sex. 
</P>
<P>
	Further, Celebrex users also have largely stayed with the drug.  
Industry experts said thousands of men were inspired by the hype 
surrounding Viagra, and tried it only as an experiment. 
</P>
<P>
	``A significant amount of usage of Viagra was recreational and  
after a while those users got over the novelty of it,'' said Jack 
Lamberton, an analyst with HSBC Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	Another big factor is insurance.  
</P>
<P>
	Most insurance programs consider Viagra a lifestyle medication,  
and as a result either don't cover it or severely restrict coverage 
to a few pills per month. As a treatment for a serious, chronic 
disease, Celebrex enjoys greater insurance coverage. 
</P>
<P>
	Without coverage, patients may balk at paying the $2.42 a day  
for Celebrex or $8 per Viagra pill, industry analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	Celebrex was the first in a class of new arthritis drugs called  
cox-2 inhibitors, which target an enzyme called cyclo-oxegenase-2 
that causes inflammation. Unlike earlier drugs, cox-2 inhibiters 
don't act against a second enzyme, cyclo-oxegenase-1, which 
protects the stomach lining. 
</P>
<P>
	Ulcers, stomach bleeding and other gastrointestinal side effects  
are a major problem with many painkillers, such as ibuprofen or 
aspirin, causing an estimated 16,500 deaths a year. 
</P>
<P>
	While tests show that cox-2 inhibitors may cause fewer ulcers  
than other drugs, the Food and Drug Administration still required 
Monsanto to put the same warning about side effects on Celebrex's 
label as the older drugs. Monsanto is conducting further tests to 
confirm that Celebrex is safer. 
</P>
<P>
	Ed Sudol, of Sleepy Hollow, N.Y,. has taken medications for his  
rheumatoid arthritis for 30 years. When he heard about Celebrex, he 
immediately asked his doctor for it. 
</P>
<P>
	Though Sudol has suffered no stomach problems from the other  
drugs, he also takes an ulcer medication just in case. Sudol said 
he can stop taking that medication because he feels more confident 
he is not hurting his stomach. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's all about quality of life,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Both Celebrex and Viagra are expected to surpass $1 billion in  
worldwide sales in 1999 as they are introduced in new countries. 
But analysts then expect Celebrex sales to continue climbing to 
nearly $4 billion in 2002, while Viagra grows more slowly to about 
$1.5 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Marketers note that despite its rapid launch, Celebrex still has  
just 20 percent of the market for arthritis drugs. Many people 
still rely on generic or over-the-counter medicines. 
</P>
<P>
	Does carrying the mantle of the hottest selling new drug really  
matter in the long run? 
</P>
<P>
	``It's great for publicity's sake and the company that  
introduced it,'' Lamberton said. ``It helps keep the drug in the 
public eye.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990802.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 14:57:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Meyer Named CEO at Warner Bros. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Longtime Warner Bros. executive Barry Meyer  
was named chairman and chief executive officer of the studio 
Monday, while Castle Rock Entertainment chairman Alan Horn was 
appointed president and chief operating officer. 
</P>
<P>
	Meyer will take over from departing chiefs Terry Semel and Bob  
Daly, who had worked together running studio operations since 1980. 
Semel and Daly announced their resignations last month. 
</P>
<P>
	``Barry Meyer and Alan Horn are the ideal team to run Warner  
Brothers,'' Gerald Levin, Time Warner Inc. chairman and chief 
executive, said in a statement. ``Both are seasoned entertainment 
executives with the right mix of business and creative savvy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meyer will head film and TV operations but will not inherit  
Semel and Daly's duties overseeing Warner Music Group. A new leader 
at the music division will be named soon, Levin said. 
</P>
<P>
	Meyer, 56, has been executive vice president since 1984 and  
chief operating officer of the Burbank-based studio since 1994. He 
came to work for Warner television in 1971. 
</P>
<P>
	Horn co-founded Castle Rock in 1987. The production company's  
films include ``When Harry Met Sally,'' ``City Slickers'' and ``A 
Few Good Men.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
