<HEADLINE> Europe: Dollar Mostly Up; Gold Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The U.S. dollar rose against most other major  
currencies in European trading Monday. Gold fell. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro was quoted at $1.0660 in late European trading, down  
from $1.0690 on Friday. Later, in afternoon trading in New York, 
the euro traded at $1.0681. 
</P>
<P>
	Other dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Friday,  
included 114.35 Japanese yen, down from 115.18; 1.4970 Swiss 
francs, up from 1.4931; 1.5118 Canadian dollars, up from 1.5057. 
</P>
<P>
	The British pound was quoted at $1.6158, down from $1.6192.  
</P>
<P>
	In afternoon trading in New York, the dollar bought 114.25 yen,  
and the pound was worth $1.6168. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately, though they remain in use. Based on euro 
rates, the dollar is worth 1.8347 German marks, up from 1.8296; 
6.1534 French francs, up from 6.1362; 2.0673 Dutch guilders, up 
from 2.0615; 1,816.39 Italian lire, up from 1,811.29. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold closed in London at $254.30 bid per troy ounce, down from  
$255.80 on Friday. In Zurich, the bid price was $254.35, down from 
$255.75. Gold fell 70 cents in Hong Kong to close at $255.25. 
</P>
<P>
	Silver closed in London at $5.36 bid per troy ounce, down from  
$5.43. 
  	   	
</P>
