<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Stocks Close Lower / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks closed lower today following another  
drop on Wall Street. The dollar continued its decline against the 
yen late today afternoon amid concerns about inflation in the 
United States. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average closed down 36.16  
points, or 0.20 percent, finishing at 17,825.70. On Friday, the 
average closed down 8.06 points, or 0.05 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 114.04 yen in late afternoon trading, down  
1.22 yen from late Friday in Tokyo and below its late New York 
level of 114.48 yen Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The stronger yen also weighed on sentiment in the stock market.  
</P>
<P>
	``Most analysts were using 125 yen in their calculations for  
this year, and now they will have to revise them downward,'' said 
Robert Sasaki, head of the quantitative strategy group at Jardine 
Fleming Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	A weak dollar makes Japanese exports costlier abroad while  
reducing the yen value of foreign revenue. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section closed down 10.31 points, or 0.70 percent, to 
1,468.62. The TOPIX closed down 11.20 points, or 0.76 percent, on 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	An estimated 437 million shares traded on the first section,  
down from Friday's 512 million. Declining shares overwhelmed 
gainers by more than two to one. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, traders said the dollar's basic weakness  
remained unchanged amid concerns about inflation in the United 
States. 
</P>
<P>
	Those fears had also driven the Dow Jones industrial average  
down for a second straight session Friday, losing 1.3 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Concerns of U.S. inflation have grown since the U.S. Labor  
Department said its Employment Cost Index, considered the best 
measure of changes in wages and benefit costs, rose 1.1 percent in 
the second quarter of this year. The jump was larger than expected. 
</P>
<P>
	Signs of inflation have led investors to fret about the overall  
health of the U.S. economy, driving the dollar to a five-month low 
of 114.20 yen in New York on Friday. The greenback trades as low as 
113.95 yen and as high as 115.00 yen in Tokyo on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 121.78 yen, down  
from 123.46 yen late Friday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 214 10-year Japanese government  
bond rose to 1.8250 percent from Friday's finish of 1.7850 percent, 
driving its price down to 99.78 yen from 100.12 yen. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
