<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> A-to-Z Guide To War-Time Atrocities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Chechnya, Bosnia, Rwanda, Kosovo. Deportation,  
torture, willful killing of civilians, ethnic cleansing. 
</P>
<P>
	The century in which ``genocide'' and ``concentration camp''  
entered the vocabulary is ending with a decade that has forced the 
world to confront crimes against humanity, not once but several 
times. 
</P>
<P>
	It is easy to forget that wars have rules.  
</P>
<P>
	But 50 years after the Geneva Conventions outlined the laws of  
war in the aftermath of World War II, a group of combat 
correspondents and legal scholars has written a guide to the ways 
fighting men have broken those codes of conduct. Their goal is to 
build political support for rules that are all too rarely enforced. 
</P>
<P>
	``Humanitarian law and international rights law have never been  
more developed; yet never before have so many innocent civilians 
been the victims of war crimes,'' South African jurist Richard 
Goldstone, the first chief prosecutor for the Yugoslav war crimes 
tribunal, writes in ``Crimes of War: What the Public Should Know.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The book, published by W.W. Norton, is an alphabetical catalogue  
of international humanitarian law, from act of war and biological 
weapons through death squads, forced labor and refugees' rights to 
torture and wanton destruction. It is both legal text and battle 
glossary. 
</P>
<P>
	CNN correspondent Christiane Amanpour writes about Bosnian Serb  
paramilitaries. German law scholar Horst Fischer describes the 
legal ambiguity of carpet bombing. Retired British Army Maj. Gen. 
A.P.V. Rogers sets out rules governing civil wars, which are 
murkier than those of cross-border conflicts. 
</P>
<P>
	Former U.S. Army law professor H. Wayne Elliott offers a how-to  
guide for judging whether prisoner of war camps meet the Geneva 
Conventions' standards: Is it located far enough from the combat 
zone? Are the prisoners adequately fed? Are they properly clothed 
or uniformed? 
</P>
<P>
	Most compelling are case studies on the horror such warfare  
inflicts and the vagaries of war crime law. 
</P>
<P>
	The Khmer Rouge's slaughter of more than a million of their  
fellow Cambodians in the mid 1970s was ignored by the United States 
and others because of Cold War politics, says former New York Times 
reporter Sydney Schanberg. 
</P>
<P>
	``Realpolitik, not (international) law, was the governing  
force,'' writes Schanberg, who won a Pulitzer Prize for reporting 
on ``the killing fields.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Barry Renfrew, Moscow bureau chief for The Associated Press,  
recounts the nationalism and ethnic hatred that plunged into 
carnage the Russian enclave of Chechnya in 1991. International law 
had little to say about the Chechens' right to secede. 
</P>
<P>
	Russian troops indiscriminately killed civilians, who in turn  
were used by the Chechens as human shields. And while both sides 
broke the laws of war, the international community treated the 
fighting as an internal matter. 
</P>
<P>
	The conscription of children younger than 15 is a recognized --  
if oft-ignored -- war crime. Yet Reuters photographer Corinne Dufka 
writes about the child soldiers she came across in Liberia, all 12 
or younger, putting their assault weapons aside to play soccer with 
a human skull. 
</P>
<P>
	Writer David Rieff and Newsday correspondent Roy Gutman, the  
book's co-editors, argue that war doesn't have to work this way. 
</P>
<P>
	The four Geneva Conventions of Aug. 12, 1949, and other accords  
covering crimes against humanity whether in war or peace, ``were 
intended to establish, even in war, a firebreak between 
civilization and barbarism,'' they write. 
</P>
<P>
	These laws, rarely put to use since the war crimes trials in  
Nuremberg and Tokyo after World War II, can be complex and their 
enforcement often complicated by political factors. 
</P>
<P>
	For example, the Clinton administration avoided using the word  
``genocide'' during the 1994 massacres of at least a half-million 
people in Rwanda, even though that case clearly was genocide as 
defined by international law. Members of one ethnic group, the 
Hutus, tried to destroy another ethnic group, the Tutsis. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1948 Convention on the Prevention and Punishment of the  
Crime of Genocide would have required signatory states, including 
the United States, to intervene -- something American leaders feared 
after 18 U.S. soldiers were killed in Somalia during a peacekeeping 
mission the year before. 
</P>
<P>
	The book's authors hope it will be used by journalists  
chronicling future Rwandas, Bosnias or Kosovos to report on the 
arcane laws of war in ``real time,'' and thus provoke public 
outrage and build political support for intervention. 
</P>
<P>
	``When the outside world pays no attention, war turns into war  
crimes on both sides,'' Gutman said in an interview. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 1990s, the only two war crimes tribunals set up since the  
post-World War II period were established, for Rwanda and the 
former Yugoslavia. And last year, 120 countries approved a treaty 
to create a standing war crimes court. The United States has yet to 
sign on. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
