<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Paper: Hard Times for Kosovo Family </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The parents of the first Albanian Kosovar  
refugee born in the United States say they face a destitute life 
because of unfulfilled promises of aid, the New York Post reported 
today. But the agency charged with helping the family denies the 
claims. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are having a hard time,'' said Naim Karaliju, who named his  
baby boy Amerikan in honor of his new life in the United States. 
``There is not enough money to buy milk for the baby.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Karaliju, 28, said his 63-year-old mother, a hotel cleaner, is  
the only employed member of the family, which now lives in Dallas. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are being told that our food stamps will be cut off and we  
will have to pay the rent,'' Karaliju told the Post through an 
interpreter. ``For me it's just too depressing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Refugee advocates claim that Refugee Services of North Texas,  
which is funded by federal taxpayers to help refugees for their 
first 30 days of resettlement, failed to provide the family with 
adequate housing, furniture, food and clothing. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency is then supposed to enlist charities and social  
services to further assist refugees if they still are in need. 
</P>
<P>
	Chip Corcoran, the executive director of Refugee Services, said  
today that his agency has provided the family with quality housing 
and helped 11 of the 24 refugees in the Karaliju family gain 
employment. 
</P>
<P>
	``I simply don't understand where the claims are coming from,''  
Corcoran said. ``Some of our people visited them last week, and 
their only complaint was that they did not have enough money for 
cigarettes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Officials at the agency's national organization, Church World  
Services, also denied the complaints and said Karaliju had turned 
down a job. 
</P>
<P>
	``My assumption is he was offered a job and refused,'' CWS  
spokeswoman Deborah DeWinter said in New York. ``These people are 
not in need.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Amerikan was born in May, days after his mother, Lebibe  
Karaliju, was airlifted to Fort Dix, N.J., from Macedonia. He drew 
national attention and was photographed holding an American flag. 
His name follows Albanian spelling. 
</P>
<P>
	The Karalijus, who were showered with blessings, including one  
from President Clinton, await word from family members in Kosovo on 
the condition of their properties there. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't see any optimism,'' said Karaliju, who added that he  
is willing to ``take any job.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know what will happen,'' he said. ``Who is going to  
pay the bills?'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
