<DOCNO> APW19990802.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 12:40:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> At the Movies: 'Get Real' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	As if dating when you're a teen-ager isn't hard enough, imagine  
being a gay teen-ager in an elite private school in an insular 
English town. 
</P>
<P>
	This is Steven Carter's reality in ``Get Real,'' a funny,  
engaging film about growing up and falling in love under difficult 
circumstances. 
</P>
<P>
	Steven (Ben Silverstone) has known he's gay since age 11, a  
secret he keeps from everyone in his homophobic environment except 
his best friend, Linda (Charlotte Brittain), whose ample size and 
brash demeanor make her somewhat of a misfit herself. 
</P>
<P>
	As his high school graduation looms, his yearnings to come out  
of the closet grow stronger, yet he must continue meeting men 
furtively. 
</P>
<P>
	In a series of funny, awkward scenes, we see Steven at a gay  
cruising spot in a park bathroom. ``He's got eyes like Brad Pitt,'' 
Steven coos to Linda about an attractive blond with whom he's 
become intimate and who turns out to be married. 
</P>
<P>
	One sunny afternoon, he finds an unlikely partner in the park --  
the best-looking, most popular guy at school, track star John Dixon 
(Brad Gorton). John has a girlfriend -- who models underwear for 
mail-order catalogs -- but clearly is confused about his sexuality. 
</P>
<P>
	The two boys are more than a little startled to find each other,  
and seem a mismatched pair. Skinny Steven is all gangly limbs and 
long eyelashes. John is rugged and muscular, with wavy dark hair 
and a strong jaw. 
</P>
<P>
	Quickly, each finds in the other a much-needed friend and  
companion, and the scenes in which Steven and John explore their 
relationship are tender and sweet. 
</P>
<P>
	A sense of melancholy blankets their bliss, however, because we  
know it can't last. John is wealthy, athletic and Oxford-bound. 
There's no way his love affair with Steven can be exposed. 
</P>
<P>
	Patrick Wilde's screenplay, adapted from his play, ``What's  
Wrong With Angry?'', is lively and warm. The teen-agers are smart 
and endearing, and they talk like young people really talk. 
Throughout the adaptation process, the filmmakers held readings at 
several schools, and the input they received from students makes 
the dialogue ring true. 
</P>
<P>
	Even a scene at a school dance -- obligatory for any movie about  
teen-agers -- feels authentic. The students don't appear to be 
having fake, contrived fun, and director Simon Shore even let the 
young actors choose the music playing in the background. 
</P>
<P>
	But what truly makes this film shine are the performances.  
</P>
<P>
	Silverstone seamlessly embodies his character. He adeptly shows  
a wide range of emotions -- awkwardness, anxiety, adoration, 
confusion, frustration and, ultimately, joy. His moment of truth at 
the end is a little too feel-good, but he plays it with great 
heart. 
</P>
<P>
	Gorton, whose character simply could have been a vapid pretty  
boy, is surprisingly compelling as the complacent jock who doubts 
everything he's made of, even though he's truly fallen in love for 
the first time. As John, he shows an impressive balance between his 
love for Steven and his paranoia of being found out. 
</P>
<P>
	Brittain is terrific as Linda, who's tough and saucy on the  
outside but clearly lonely and a little sad underneath. A scene in 
which she tells off a drunk jock at the school dance is a powerful, 
you-go-girl moment. 
</P>
<P>
	Shore's direction is edgy and reminiscent of ``Rushmore,'' also  
set in a private school, with its wide-angle shots and variety of 
camera angles, and while his film is about a gay relationship, its 
themes of loneliness, love and loss are universal. 
</P>
<P>
	``Get Real,'' a Paramount Classics release, runs 110 minutes and  
is rated R for language and sexual issues. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:  
</P>
<P>
	G -- General audiences. All ages admitted.  
</P>
<P>
	PG -- Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be  
suitable for children. 
</P>
<P>
	PG-13 -- Special parental guidance strongly suggested for  
children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young 
children. 
</P>
<P>
	R -- Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult  
guardian. 
</P>
<P>
	NC-17 -- No one under 17 admitted.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
