<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Coach at Rutgers-Camden Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) -- Wilbur ``Pony'' Wilson, athletic director at  
Rutgers-Camden for nearly three decades, has died at age 66. 
</P>
<P>
	Wilson, of Cherry Hill, N.J. died Saturday night at the Hospital  
of the University of Pennsylvania in Philadelphia after a brief 
battle with pancreatic cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	He coached the men's basketball team for 18 1/2 years during three  
stints, compiling a 187-273 record. He led the Pioneers to NAIA 
district championships in 1972 and 1976. But the school landed in 
NCAA Division III history books in the mid-1990s, compiling a 
117-game losing streak that spanned five seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	When the streak reached 84 games in March 1995, Wilson returned  
as coach. The team lost 14 more games before health problems forced 
him to step down. He lost 50 pounds and his wife, Betty, got 
worried when he began yelling out the names of players in his 
sleep. 
</P>
<P>
	The publicity got so bad that then-Provost Walter Gordon decided  
to eliminate the program in 1996, over Wilson's objections. Gordon 
later reversed his decision, and the streak finally ended on Jan. 
7, 1997, with a 77-72 victory over Bloomfield College. 
</P>
<P>
	Wilson became athletic director in 1969 when the branch campus  
only had five men's sports teams and no playing facilities of its 
own. He retired in 1998. The school currently has 14 teams for men 
and women, an intramural program and a gym with two basketball 
courts. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to his wife, Wilson is also survived by two children  
from a previous marriage, a son, Darryl, a daughter, Diane, a 
step-daughter, Saundra Umstead-Capers, and five grandchildren. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990802.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 22:40:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Meyer Named CEO at Warner Bros. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Longtime Warner Bros. executive Barry Meyer  
has been named the studio's chairman and chief executive officer, 
while Castle Rock Entertainment chairman Alan Horn was appointed 
president and chief operating officer. 
</P>
<P>
	Meyer will take over from Terry Semel and Bob Daly, who had  
worked together running studio operations since 1980. Semel and 
Daly announced their resignations last month. 
</P>
<P>
	``Barry Meyer and Alan Horn are the ideal team to run Warner  
Brothers,'' Gerald Levin, Time Warner Inc. chairman and chief 
executive, said Monday. . ``Both are seasoned entertainment 
executives with the right mix of business and creative savvy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meyer will head film and TV operations but will not inherit  
Semel and Daly's duties overseeing Warner Music Group. A new leader 
at the music division will be named soon, Levin said. 
</P>
<P>
	Meyer, 56, has been executive vice president since 1984 and  
chief operating officer of the Burbank-based studio since 1994. He 
came to work for Warner television in 1971. 
</P>
<P>
	Horn co-founded Castle Rock in 1987. The production company's  
films include ``When Harry Met Sally,'' ``City Slickers'' and ``A 
Few Good Men.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
