<HEADLINE> Brooklyn Man Charged in Bank Fraud </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- An assistant treasurer at the Bank of New York  
has been charged with bank fraud for allegedly embezzling $700,000, 
prosecutors announced Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	John Sanchez, 31, of Brooklyn was accused in a complaint filed  
in U.S. District Court in Manhattan of illegally transferring 
millions of dollars since January 1998 in a scheme to siphon away 
interest for his own benefit. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Attorney Mary Jo White alleged in court papers that Sanchez  
moved the money into an account at one of the bank's subsidiaries 
in the Cayman Islands during weekends to generate interest. 
</P>
<P>
	Sanchez has been an assistant treasurer in the Foreign Banks  
Custody Department of the Bank of New York since 1997, supervising 
six administrators, according to a release from prosecutors. 
</P>
<P>
	Sanchez had the authority to open accounts, transfer funds and  
approve check requests and overdrafts for accounts belonging to the 
bank's customers, prosecutors said. 
</P>
<P>
	The complaint said Sanchez had provided the FBI a written  
confession, conceding that he pocketed interest from the bank 
account for his own personal use. 
</P>
<P>
	It said he used the money to buy a $40,000 sports utility  
vehicle, to open a stock trading account and to provide loans to 
friends and family. 
</P>
<P>
	If convicted, Sanchez faces a maximum of 30 years in prison and  
a fine of up to $1 million. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
