<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Butler Chides Annan on Arms Probes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Former U.N. weapons chief Richard Butler  
has accused U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan of trying to destroy 
the weapons inspection operation he headed because it was ``too 
independent.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview in the debut issue of Talk magazine, Butler said  
Annan repeatedly confused Iraqi President Saddam Hussein's 
``superficial cooperation'' with U.N. weapons inspectors ``with 
substantive compliance'' on Baghdad's disarmament obligations. 
</P>
<P>
	The secretary-general and his staff reacted to systematic  
cheating by Iraq in destroying and accounting for its banned 
weapons by ``papering over'' problems with diplomacy, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Talk magazine issued a press release with excerpts from the  
interview, to be published Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked Monday to comment on Butler's accusations, Annan said: ``I  
don't think I have to comment. Everybody knows what happened. ... 
It's not relevant in the scheme of things.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After two stormy years, Butler left his job as executive  
director of the U.N. Special Commission, known as UNSCOM, when his 
contract expired on June 30. He is now a diplomat-in-residence at 
the Council on Foreign Relations and is writing a book. 
</P>
<P>
	In the article, Butler said he decided against seeking another  
term because ``the situation within the U.N. had become 
untenable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Butler, an Australian diplomat, pulled UNSCOM inspectors out of  
Iraq in mid-December on the eve of U.S. and British airstrikes, and 
Baghdad has banned them from returning. The Security Council is 
debating a new Iraq policy that will likely include a successor 
organization to UNSCOM. 
</P>
<P>
	``Iraq possesses the knowledge required to make a sophisticated  
atomic bomb, has long-range missiles and has been hard at work on 
extending their range, (and) possesses the means to make both 
chemical and biological weapons,'' Butler said. 
</P>
<P>
	He described UNSCOM as a ``thorn in the side'' of both Saddam  
and Annan and said the secretary-general wanted the ``destruction'' 
of UNSCOM because it was ``too independent to work within the 
mainstream of the U.N.'' 
</P>
<P>
	UNSCOM was created by the Security Council after the 1991  
Persian Gulf War to ensure the elimination of Iraq's nuclear, 
chemical and biological weapons and the long-range missiles to 
deliver them. 
</P>
<P>
	But he said its tough inspection provisions were weakened, and  
Annan at one point asked him to exclude American inspectors as Iraq 
demanded. He refused. 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview on ABC's Nightline, Butler said Annan had make a  
mistake in seeking diplomatic solutions ``rather than dealing 
substantively, practically with the weapons issues.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a wonderful person. But I think in professional terms,  
that was a mistake,'' Butler said. ``When you separate process from 
substance in the way that he did, then I think you inevitably have 
failure. And the failure is now in our hands. We've been out of 
Iraq for a year, and Lord knows what Iraq is doing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the article, Butler denied allegations by former UNSCOM  
inspector Scott Ritter, an American, that the CIA was directing the 
organization's activities. 
</P>
<P>
	Ritter ``misrepresented facts and reconstructed events,  
conversations, and decisions in which he played no part'' and his 
assertions hurt UNSCOM's credibility, Butler said. 
</P>
<P>
	Butler also said former Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov  
told him Moscow was motivated to act as Iraq's ``most aggressive 
advocate'' because it hopes to recoup $7 billion in war debts if 
sanctions against Baghdad are lifted. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
