<DOCNO> APW19990802.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 14:20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Defense Health Care Fraud Said Ample </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Defense Department may have lost more than  
$1 billion from health care fraud and abuse during the past three 
years, according to a congressional report that criticized the 
Pentagon for lax oversight. 
</P>
<P>
	From 1996 through 1998, companies providing health care services  
for Pentagon employees reported 100 potential fraud cases, a 
fraction of the 50 million claims filed during the three-year 
period, said the report by the General Accounting Office, the 
investigative arm of Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	No precise accounting could be made, but the GAO said more  
accurate estimate of the amount of fraud would be 10 percent to 20 
percent of the $5.7 billion in managed health care claims -- or 
between $570 million and $1.14 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	The report said $14 million in fraudulent payments was  
retrieved. 
</P>
<P>
	``The small amount of recoveries indicates that DoD efforts have  
considerable room for improvement and that DoD's vulnerability to 
fraud and abuse is still high,'' the report concluded. 
</P>
<P>
	The GAO recommended that the Pentagon require health care  
providers to train their employees to better detect fraudulent 
claims, develop computer software and enforce existing anti-fraud 
measures. 
</P>
<P>
	In its response to the report, the Pentagon criticized the GAO's  
estimate of fraud, suggesting it was unfair to suppose abuse is 
being ignored just because few fraud cases were reported compared 
to overall claims. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Sue Baily, assistant secretary of defense for health  
affairs, said the Pentagon agreed with the GAO's recommendations to 
take steps to improve its implementation of anti-fraud measures. 
But she questioned setting any goal that would assess contractors 
based solely on their ability to crack down on abuse and fraud 
rather than their ability to provide health care services. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are not aware of any methodology that would allow us to  
establish such goals without creating perverse incentives,'' Baily 
said in a written response. 
</P>
<P>
	Some contractors the GAO interviewed said they were not  
adequately trained to identify fraud and abuse, and were unclear 
about what potential fraud cases to report to the management of the 
Pentagon health care programs. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Armed Services Committee Chairman John Warner, R-Va.,  
requested the GAO review of the program, which provides health care 
to about 1.5 million beneficiaries, including dependents of 
active-duty military personnel. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
