<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Grain Harvest Doing Better </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Russian farms will harvest 66 million tons of  
grain this year, according to Ministry of Agriculture estimates 
released Monday, the Interfax news agency reported. 
</P>
<P>
	The figure is higher than previous estimates. It suggests that a  
drought and locusts in the south, where most of the country's grain 
grows, have not cut into output as severely as originally feared. 
Estimates for 1999 have fluctuated nearly every week, dipping as 
low as 55 million tons. 
</P>
<P>
	But Minister of Agriculture and Food Vladimir Shcherbak said  
yields per acre were up about 20 percent compared with last year. 
Fuel shortages brought on by domestic gas price increases are the 
main worry for farmers, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	As of Aug. 1, farmers had harvested 19 million tons of grain on  
19.5 million acres, or 18 percent of the country's total planted 
area, Shcherbak said. 
</P>
<P>
	Previous reports were less optimistic.  
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday, a top grain official, Leonid Chesinsky of the baking  
company Roskhlebprodukt, predicted that Russia's harvest would 
reach only 55 to 60 million tons. He said the government should ask 
for another package of food aid from Western countries to cover the 
shortfall. 
</P>
<P>
	A 53-million ton harvest in 1998 prompted the Russian government  
to accept food aid from the United States and the European Union. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990802.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 03:10:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cuban Defects at Pan Am Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WINNIPEG, Manitoba (AP) -- Three more Cuban athletes sought  
asylum in Canada this weekend, bringing to seven the number of 
Cubans to leave the delegation during the Pan American Games. 
</P>
<P>
	Royal Canadian Mounted Police authorities confirmed Sunday that  
an athlete walked into their downtown office Saturday and said he 
wanted to defect. 
</P>
<P>
	The athlete, whom sources close to the Cuban delegation said was  
a member of men's 4 x 100 relay team, was turned over to 
immigration officials. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither the RCMP nor the sources, speaking to The Associated  
Press on condition of anonymity, would reveal the name of the 
athlete. Track and field concluded Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Late Sunday, the same sources told the AP a female artistic  
gymnast and a men's soccer goalkeeper sought asylum, as well. The 
two goalies for the soccer team are Rene Castro, who played every 
minute in the games, and Rodney Valdes. 
</P>
<P>
	Before the games began, pistol shooter Abel Juncosa Reyes asked  
for asylum. Reporter Lisette Cepero of Radio Rebelde also has 
sought to defect, as did a softball coach. 
</P>
<P>
	Another shooter, whom the Cubans say did not accompany the team  
-- sources say he did, indeed, come to Canada -- disappeared last 
week. The sources said he, too, was seeking to defect. 
</P>
<P>
	This latest episodes came hours after the heads of the 42  
delegations to the games denounced agents they claimed were 
inciting Cuban athletes to defect. They condemned ``the negative 
actions that have affected not only Cuba, but all of the Americas, 
and have interfered with the Olympic movement and the spirit of 
equality and good sportsmanship.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last Monday, Cuban President Fidel Castro said: ``We have never  
seen so many tricks, so much filth in the Pan American Games. We 
are competing in enemy territory.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jose Ramon Fernandez, president of the Cuban Olympic Committee,  
said sports agents have been seen near the athletes village trying 
to contact Cubans and encourage them ``to desert.'' He said these 
agents are plying the athletes with offers of million-dollar 
contracts. 
</P>
<P>
	Fernandez also has criticized media coverage of the defections,  
claiming the media had worsened the situation with its reporting. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
