<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> EPA To Review Pesticides for Dangers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- EPA Administrator Carol Browner on Monday said  
the agency within 18 months will complete studies and decide 
whether to ban or sharply curtail the use of more than 40 high-risk 
pesticides that may pose a threat to children. 
</P>
<P>
	As an immediate step, Browner announced agreements with  
manufacturers to stop the sale for most uses of one of the 
high-risk pesticides, methyl parathion, and to sharply curtail the 
use of another because of the health risks they pose to infants and 
children. 
</P>
<P>
	The dozens of pesticides, including a class of organophosphates  
used for decades on most fruits and vegetables, have been a focus 
of controversy because of concern that the residue levels the 
government deems acceptable pose risks to infants and children who, 
when compared with their weight, eat large amounts of these foods. 
</P>
<P>
	Allowable residue levels for many pesticides were set decades  
ago when the potential health impacts on infants and children were 
not taken into account. 
</P>
<P>
	Browner told a news conference that fruits and vegetables are  
safe and that children and adults alike should not stop eating 
them. 
</P>
<P>
	``The benefits of a diet that includes fruits and vegetables far  
outweigh the risks of pesticides,'' said Browner. However, she 
said, ``It is becoming increasingly clear that foods can be made 
even safer, especially for children,'' adding that ``today's 
technologies allow our farmers to use safer alternatives and safer 
approaches.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The EPA's intention to end the use of methyl parathion on fruits  
and vegetables and curtail the use of azinphos methyl was reported 
last week. The pesticides are widely used nationwide on such crops 
as apples, peaches, pears, grapes, carrots and certain beans. 
</P>
<P>
	Several environmental groups -- angered by EPA's pace in  
confronting the issue -- said Monday they planned to sue the agency 
Tuesday, accusing it of failing to meet a series of deadlines 
directed by Congress in 1996 to address pesticide dangers to 
children in the food supply. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is ample evidence that infants and children are being  
exposed to unacceptable levels of pesticides,'' said Jacqueline 
Hamilton, an attorney for the Natural Resources Defense Council, 
one of the groups filing the lawsuit. ``Yet the government is 
dragging its feet and caving to pressure from the pesticide 
industry.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Browner dismissed the criticism even as she acknowledged that  
the EPA had not met its own deadlines in completing the pesticide 
reviews demanded by Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	The EPA a year ago said it would complete reviews of the  
riskiest pesticides -- the organophosphate family of chemicals -- 
within 12 months. That deadline would have been Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Dealing with these pesticides ``has proven to be more difficult  
than we thought,'' Browner said. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics contend the EPA delayed taking action because of  
pressure from agriculture interests. Earlier this year, a number of 
environmentalists quit a pesticide review task force, created at 
the urging of Vice President Al Gore, claiming the agriculture and 
chemical industry participants had taken over the process. 
</P>
<P>
	Browner, nevertheless, said she is determined to push  
aggressively for the reviews and for new scientific studies to 
examine the health effects of pesticides on children. 
</P>
<P>
	She said her schedule will leave the EPA ``ready to take action  
by the end of next year to ensure our children are protected. In 
addition to the organophosphate class of pesticides, the EPA will 
review whether such widely used agricultural pesticides as 
atrazine, aldicarb and carbofuran should be curtailed or taken out 
of use entirely, she said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
