<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Woods Vs. Duval: Rivalry Can't Wait  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	THOUSAND OAKS, Calif. (AP) -- Tiger Woods against David Duval is  
one rivalry that may not have to wait until they meet on the back 
nine of a major championship for it to develop. 
</P>
<P>
	When Jack Nicklaus explained the ground rules for the making of  
a rivalry, he also disclosed a key component that explains Monday 
night's ``Showdown at Sherwood,'' the made-for-television event 
between the game's top two players. 
</P>
<P>
	``These two guys have been way above everybody else in the past  
few months, in the last year or so,'' Nicklaus said at the Masters. 
``They certainly are the two that you're going to talk about.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A major championship rarely goes by without some clamoring for  
Woods and Duval, the only players to hold the No. 1 position in the 
world rankings the past year, to trade shots down the stretch. 
</P>
<P>
	They have been the most talked about players in the game, a  
rivalry played out more in the imagination than between the ropes, 
driven by the vast differences in their style and background. 
</P>
<P>
	Duval is the ruthless robot in wraparound sunglasses, the son of  
a head pro from Jacksonville, Fla., who became the first player in 
25 years to win four times before the Masters. He also owns the 
only Sunday 59 in PGA Tour history. 
</P>
<P>
	Woods is a showman, the first Masters champion of color with a  
penchant for shotmaking and a personality that transcends golf. He 
has been part of every rivalry discussion that has cropped up since 
his record victory in the Masters -- Phil Mickleson, two-time U.S. 
Open champion Ernie Els, and even Justin Leonard after he won the 
British Open the same year Woods won the Masters. 
</P>
<P>
	A new prospect was thrown his way at Carnoustie.  
</P>
<P>
	``Oh, it's Sergio now?'' Woods said, shaking his head at the  
reference to 19-year-old Sergio Garcia of Spain. 
</P>
<P>
	Considering the mass of talent in today's game, rivalries are  
rare because of the sheer chance that two players can continually 
emerge in the final round of a major. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's difficult to say David and I are the best players in the  
world and that we're going to see each other heading down the 
stretch on Sunday in major championships,'' Woods said. ``It's 
possible, but it's difficult in this sport. It's more difficult now 
because of the competition and depth of field.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, any talk about Duval usually involves comparisons to  
Woods, and vice versa. 
</P>
<P>
	All they need now is to compete each other -- not at Sherwood  
Country Club, but at Medinah for the PGA Championship next week. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would say that a rivalry is a product of it being written  
about and talked about for a length of time,'' Duval said. ``It's 
hard to make a case for a rivalry when you haven't faced off in an 
event, much less a major. Our event at Sherwood isn't even a 
tournament, so I don't think it can really be considered a fuel for 
a rivalry.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That much is true.  
</P>
<P>
	No one really talked about Gene Sarazen and Walter Hagen until  
they began winning all the majors in the 1920s, particularly after 
the Squire beat Hagen on the 38th hole of the 1923 PGA 
Championship. Sam Snead and Ben Hogan didn't become rivals until 
they won five of six Masters from 1949 to 1954 -- the last year 
featured Snead's one-stroke victory over Hogan in an 18-hole 
playoff. 
</P>
<P>
	Nicklaus and Tom Watson became rivals after the 36-hole duel in  
Turnberry, followed by Watson's chip-in on the 17th to steal the 
U.S. Open from Nicklaus at Pebble Beach in 1982. 
</P>
<P>
	Golf hasn't had a good rivalry since.  
</P>
<P>
	The closest has been Nick Faldo and Greg Norman. Faldo dusted  
Norman in the third round of the 1990 British Open, but Norman 
dropped off the map after that until he won his second British Open 
in 1993, holding off a strong charge at Royal St. George. 
</P>
<P>
	Faldo also took advantage of the Shark's greatest collapse,  
winning the 1996 Masters with a 67 to Norman's 78. Still, they 
rarely met any time else, and Norman is linked more to failure and 
bad luck than any one player. 
</P>
<P>
	The greatest prospect is Woods and Duval, but the first step  
won't be Monday night. While Nicklaus admits they are the best two 
players in the game, he also unlocked another key component to the 
making of a rivalry. 
</P>
<P>
	``They've got to be winning majors to compete for that  
rivalry,'' Nicklaus said. ``That's where you guys are going to get 
the excitement from it, and that's where the people are going to 
get the excitement from it.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
