<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 4 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Christian Coalition Charges Tossed  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A federal judge today threw out most of the  
charges in a government lawsuit accusing the Christian Coalition of 
illegally aiding Republican candidates. U.S. District Judge Joyce 
Green rejected arguments by the Federal Election Commission that 
the coalition's contact with campaigns and its distribution of 
voters guide to churches on the Sunday before Election Days should 
be counted as excessive campaign contributions. Green ruled that 
the group must pay a civil penalty to the FEC for advocating the 
election of Rep. Newt Gingrich during the Georgia Republican's 
successful 1994 bid to gain GOP control of the House. 

</P>
<P>
	Heat Breaks but Deaths Rise  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Cooler temperatures eased conditions in the  
Midwest and most of the East today, but the nationwide death toll 
from the mid-summer heat wave rose to 197. A cold front that pushed 
across the Midwest during the weekend brought relief to many 
people. Temperatures were in the 70s across most of the Ohio Valley 
into parts of the Northeast. The Oklahoma Medical Examiner's Office 
reported that the state's heat-related death toll had reached 
eight. Officials in Chicago said they were sure the number of 
deaths in the city would increase. 

</P>
<P>
	India Train Crash Kills Nearly 200  
</P>
<P>
	GAUHATI, India (AP) -- Two high-speed trains collided in a remote  
section of eastern India, killing nearly 200 hundred people and 
injuring more than 300. The impact flipped coaches on top of each 
other and hurled sleeping passengers though flaming compartments. 
Railway officials said the death toll was likely to climb to 250, 
and news agencies said it could reach 400 or more. Rail officials 
blamed a signal failure for the crash. 

</P>
<P>
	Political Tensions Rise in Mideast  
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak was entangled  
in his first major crisis today with Palestinian leader Yasser 
Arafat. Infuriated by Barak's insistence on skipping one of two 
promised West Bank troop pullbacks, Arafat accused him of trying to 
break peace agreements. Barak said Arafat was being too rigid. 
Russian President Boris Yeltsin, seeking a greater role for Russia 
in the Middle East, told Barak during talks in Moscow that the 
peace process was moving too slowly and that Russia was ready to 
help negotiate a settlement. 

</P>
<P>
	Dole Puts Emphasis on Values  
</P>
<P>
	MARSHALLTOWN, Iowa (AP) -- With a new emphasis on values,  
Elizabeth Dole said today that a president should use the White 
House as a ``bully pulpit'' to show the difference between right 
and wrong. ``I don't think President Clinton has been the leader 
that he should be,'' she said. The Republican presidential 
candidate said: ``I'm speaking of things like integrity, honesty, 
respect for your fellow man, personal responsibility.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Barton Children Are Mourned  
</P>
<P>
	LITHIA SPRINGS, Ga. (AP) -- Relatives and friends gathered today  
to mourn the youngest victims of Mark Barton's deadly rampage -- his 
two children. Matthew Barton, 11, and his sister, Mychelle, 7, were 
bludgeoned by their father on Wednesday, the day after Barton, 
apparently distraught over large losses in the stock market, killed 
his wife. Barton the next day killed nine people in a shooting 
spree at two Atlanta brokerages before killing himself. The 
children's mother and maternal grandmother were hacked to death in 
Alabama in 1993, and police said Barton was a suspect but never 
charged. 

</P>
<P>
	Internet Shopping Slips  
</P>
<P>
	WESTPORT, Conn. (AP) -- The percentage of Internet users making a  
purchase online decreased slightly in the second quarter, the first 
drop in a year, according to a survey. The percentage of people 
with online access who said they purchased something from a Web 
site fell to 71 percent in the second quarter, down from 74 percent 
in the first quarter, according to Greenfield Online, an Internet 
marketing research firm. Greenfield said the decline could be 
attributed to there being no specific reason to shop. The 90-day 
period covered by the March tracking study included post-Christmas 
shopping. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Is Up 0.95  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed today, recovering from some of  
last week's big losses, after a new report suggested the economy 
has not expanded quite as fast as market watchers had feared. Just 
before the close, the Dow industrials were at 10,656.10, up 0.95. 
On the NYSE, losers led gainers 1,718-1,214. The Nasdaq was at 
2624.75, down 13.74. 

</P>
<P>
	Packers' Robert Brooks Retires  
</P>
<P>
	GREEN BAY, Wis. (AP) -- Wide receiver Robert Brooks of the Green  
Bay Packers announced his retirement today, hampered by a painful 
back injury. Brooks, 29, was a fan favorite who used to jump into 
the Lambeau Field stands to celebrate touchdown catches. He 
underwent surgery during training camp last year to repair a 
herniated disc. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by HOWARD SINER  
  	   	
</P>
