<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Finishing $12.6B Aid Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Many House Democrats are supporting a $12.6  
billion foreign aid bill in hopes that spending can be increased 
and anti-abortion language deleted to avoid a presidential veto. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate already has approved a similar measure but without  
the one amendment sure to bring a veto: a ban on any U.S. funding 
for groups working to liberalize abortion laws. 
</P>
<P>
	The House scheduled final debate on its version of the bill  
Monday. Several Democrats on the Appropriations' foreign operations 
subcommittee said they would support it if can be modified before 
it goes to President Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	In an unusual move, lawmakers last week approved a parallel  
provision that is more palatable to family planning groups that 
view the abortion language as a prohibition on free speech and an 
effort to stop family planning, not just abortions. 
</P>
<P>
	The second amendment, approved 221-208, reflects the contention  
that family planning prevents abortions. It would require that 
groups receiving aid certify only that they work to reduce the 
number of abortions. 
</P>
<P>
	The original amendment, a version of which has doomed several  
foreign affairs bills in the past five years, passed 228-220. It 
would ban aid to any group lobbying for changes in abortion laws 
even if the group uses privately raised funds. Family planning 
groups hope that language can be removed during the House-Senate 
conference committee that will shape the final bill. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration says the legislation's cuts of $1.9 billion  
from Clinton's requests would harm a wide range of foreign policy 
efforts, hurting the poorest countries and diminishing the ability 
to respond to foreign crises, to prevent nuclear smuggling, to deal 
with the Asian crisis, to expand the Peace Corps and to help 
refugees. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill's funding is $715 million below that of last year's  
bill and $20.7 billion below this year's actual spending on foreign 
assistance, including emergency appropriations. 
</P>
<P>
	A Clinton administration statement said senior advisers would  
recommend a veto if foreign operations funding is not increased. 
</P>
<P>
	``Funding at this level would seriously impair the president's  
ability to conduct an effective foreign policy,'' the statement 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	It said the bill would cut funding to international lending  
institutions by $493 million from amounts needed to meet U.S. 
commitments. 
</P>
<P>
	Other major provisions of the foreign operations bill include:  
</P>
<P>
	--$2.88 billion for Israel, representing a $120 million reduction  
in economic and a $60 million increase in military aid. 
</P>
<P>
	--$2 billion for Egypt, a $40 million reduction in economic aid  
but no change in military aid. 
</P>
<P>
	--$725 million for former Soviet states, $307 million below  
Clinton's request. It would withhold 50 percent of aid to Russia 
unless it ends missile cooperation with Iran. 
</P>
<P>
	--$680 million for child survival programs.  
</P>
<P>
	Among hotly contested provisions, the bill includes the first  
cut in funding for a military school in Fort Benning, Ga., which 
has been criticized for human rights abuses committed in Latin 
American by some of its graduates. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	The bill is H.R. 2606.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
