<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Montgomery Ward Attempts Comeback </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Venerable retailer Montgomery Ward emerged Monday  
from bankruptcy protection, hoping a new store format will help it 
succeed in a crowded retail marketplace. 
</P>
<P>
	The closely-held retailer, the nation's ninth-largest department  
store chain, is relying on a remodeled format for 43 of its 252 
full-line stores to bring in price-conscious consumers. 
</P>
<P>
	Company executives say sales have increased sharply at stores  
that have been converted to the new format, which includes more 
trendy clothes, home furnishings and electronics in easy-to-see 
settings. 
</P>
<P>
	But while the 127-year-old retailer has narrowed its losses, it  
continues to bleed red ink. The Chicago-based company lost $971 
million dollars in 1998 on sales of $3.6 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Retail analysts also remain skeptical about the company's  
chances for survival. They note powerhouses such as Sears, Roebuck 
and Co. and J.C. Penney presently are struggling to find their 
place with consumers who either shop at higher-end stores such as 
Bloomingdale's or discounters such as Wal-Mart and Target. 
</P>
<P>
	Wards in 1997 sought Chapter 11 bankruptcy reorganization  
protection and has since moved to slash costs by closing more than 
100 money-losing stores and selling off much of the real estate at 
its sprawling corporate campus here. 
</P>
<P>
	Under terms of its reorganization, the company sold its  
Signature Group direct marketing unit to GE Capital Inc. -- its 
largest creditor -- for more than $650 million. That subsidiary had 
been the company's only profitable enterprise. GE Capital also owns 
Wards' credit card operations. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
