<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bradley Moves Ahead of Bush in N.Y. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Former Sen. Bill Bradley is gaining on  
Democratic front-runner Al Gore in head-to-head polling in New York 
and actually outdoes the vice president when matched against 
Republican George W. Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	In a potential Democratic primary matchup, Vice President Gore  
led Bradley, 47 percent to 38 percent, in the latest survey by the 
Quinnipiac College Polling Institute. That's just half the margin 
of the institute's poll released in early July, 52 percent to 34 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	As for a possible November contest, Bradley led Bush, 46 percent  
to 39 percent, in the poll released Monday, up from a statistical 
dead heat in the earlier survey that had Bush at 44 percent and 
Bradley at 43 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The new poll had Gore at 45 percent to Bush's 43 percent. In  
early July, Bush was favored by 45 percent of voters while Gore was 
the choice of 44 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley has strong ties to New York. In addition to having  
represented neighboring New Jersey in the Senate, he was a star on 
the New York Knicks basketball team before entering politics. 
</P>
<P>
	While Gore was stronger than Bradley among Democrats in the  
survey, Bradley pulled more support from Republican voters, 15 
percent vs. 9 percent, and independents, 50 percent vs. 40 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The telephone poll of 1,241 registered voters was conducted July  
20-27 and had a margin of error of plus or minus 3 percentage 
points. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're trying to get a good start in New York and we think  
we're doing that,'' Bradley spokesman Eric Hauser said after the 
new poll came out. ``The shrinking gap (between Gore and Bradley) 
is a reflection of our ability to compete pretty hard in New 
York.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Roger Salazar, a spokesman for Gore, said, ``The bottom line is  
the V.P. is leading among Democrats in New York. We have a long 
campaign ahead of us and we're going to have a lot of these 
snapshots where numbers will be up and down.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Maurice Carroll, director of the Quinnipiac College  
institute, noted that Gore remained basically in a tie with Bush 
among New York voters ``and that's not a good place for a 
Democratic presidential candidate to be.'' 
</P>
<P>
	New York, where Democrats outnumber Republicans by a 5-3 margin,  
is considered a must-win state for Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton's approval rating among New York voters  
remains high, at 67 percent, and his wife is eyeing a run for the 
Senate seat from New York being vacated next year by fellow 
Democrat Daniel Patrick Moynihan. The Clintons are both backing 
Gore's candidacy. 
</P>
<P>
	While Gore is also backed by most of the state's top elected  
Democratic officials, there have been signs of Bradley inroads. 
Gore advisers in the state have said they expect Moynihan to back 
Bradley, and David Alpert, the influential Democratic chairman in 
suburban Westchester County, recently called Gore a ``stuffed 
shirt'' and said Bradley was ``more electable.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
