<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Virginia Shipyard Strike Ends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEWPORT NEWS, Va. (AP) -- Workers began returning to their jobs  
Monday after a four-month strike at the shipyard that is the 
nation's only builder of aircraft carriers. 
</P>
<P>
	The first workers filed through the gates at Newport News  
Shipbuilding at 7 a.m. and others will follow over the next four 
weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're going to be coming back in waves,'' said Arnold  
Outlaw, president of Steelworkers Local 8888, which conducted the 
strike that began April 5 and ended with a contract ratification 
vote Friday. The union represents 9,200 production and maintenance 
workers, about half the work force for the shipyard. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the shipyard gave workers return dates based on their  
qualifications and seniority. 
</P>
<P>
	Mike Hatfield, a company spokesman, said some workers have to be  
retrained and others need updated physicals before they can resume 
work. 
</P>
<P>
	The new contract provides a pay raise averaging $3.10 an hour  
over 58 months and improves the pension plan for workers who retire 
at 62 with at least 30 years experience. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
