<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 03:20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Baseball's Trade Deadline Passes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	The Oakland Athletics and New York Mets were busy. Chuck Finley  
and Andy Pettitte stayed put. And the Cleveland Indians once again 
entered baseball's stretch run without an ace pitcher. 
</P>
<P>
	This year's baseball trade deadline, which passed Saturday at  
midnight EDT, was most notable for the trades that didn't happen. 
Without a true No. 1 pitcher on the trade market, many teams 
decided they were better off standing pat than paying a hefty price 
for an also-ran pitcher. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the right guy was out there for us, we would have done  
something, believe me,'' Cleveland GM John Hart said. ``We kept 
looking for that top line pitcher.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But there was no Randy Johnson available this July 31, or even a  
Curt Schilling or David Wells. And the price for Chuck Finley, 
perhaps the top starter on the market despite a 5-10 record and 
5.76 ERA, was too high for Cleveland to pay. 
</P>
<P>
	``I will say that in some of the deals we have made the last  
couple of years, other clubs have gotten some good talent, but we 
look for the best players to be coming back our way in any deal,'' 
Hart said. ``Quite frankly, Finley's high ERA and lack of success 
this season were a concern to us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cleveland ended up doing nothing to bolster a pitching staff  
that is seventh-best in the AL. Despite efforts by Indians GM John 
Hart, Cleveland enters the stretch run without a starter whose ERA 
is under 4.00. 
</P>
<P>
	That pitcher wasn't out there. Kansas City's Kevin Appier, who  
went to Oakland, and Baltimore's Juan Guzman, who went to 
Cincinnati, were the top starters to change teams. 
</P>
<P>
	The A's completed an overhaul of their pitching staff, getting  
Appier and sending closer Billy Taylor to the Mets for pitchers 
Jason Isringhausen and Greg McMichael. 
</P>
<P>
	Those two deals came after trades that sent ace Kenny Rogers to  
the Mets and brought in starter Omar Olivares and infielder Randy 
Velarde from Anaheim. 
</P>
<P>
	``We weren't supposed to be here in July,'' A's general manager  
Billy Beane said. ``Now we're trying to make our mark in this 
race.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Mets were the busiest team. Besides acquiring Taylor from  
Oakland, they got outfielder Darryl Hamilton and left-hander Chuck 
McElroy from Colorado and infielder Shawon Dunston from St. Louis 
for outfielder Brian McRae and three minor leaguers. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going for it,'' GM Steve Phillips said. ``Now's the  
time. You don't know how many times the opportunity will present 
itself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Yankees reacquired postseason hero Jim Leyritz from the San  
Diego Padres for a minor league pitcher. But they didn't deal 
Pettitte, who has struggled for most of the past year and drawn ire 
from owner George Steinbrenner for not being aggressive on the 
mound. 
</P>
<P>
	The Phillies were hoping to add Pettitte to their pitching  
staff. But the Yankees apparently cooled at the idea late Saturday 
when they couldn't acquire Tampa Bay reliever Roberto Hernandez 
despite talks into the final hour. 
</P>
<P>
	The Devil Rays, who also couldn't deal Rolando Arrojo or Fred  
McGriff, insisted on top prospect Alfonso Soriano being included in 
any deal with New York. Tampa Bay has made only three deals in more 
than 20 months since the expansion draft. 
</P>
<P>
	Trades still can be made, but players must first pass through  
waivers. That means any club can step in and block a potential 
deal. Teams might be a bit more wary to block a deal this year 
after watching San Diego get stuck with Randy Myers' hefty 
contract. 
</P>
<P>
	Three division leaders -- Cleveland, Texas and Houston -- made no  
moves heading into the deadline. That's not always a bad thing. 
Last year's pennant winners, the Yankees and Padres, both stood pat 
a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The Atlanta Braves, beset by injuries, did make a last-minute  
deal, acquiring left-hander Terry Mulholland and infielder Jose 
Hernandez from the Cubs for three minor leaguers. 
</P>
<P>
	The Braves, facing their first pennant race in six years,  
learned last week that they lost catcher Javy Lopez and starter 
Odalis Perez for the season. That comes on top of earlier injuries 
to first baseman Andres Galarraga and closer Kerry Ligtenberg. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you lose offensive production like we have with Galarraga  
and Lopez, it's hurtful,'' GM John Schuerholz said. ``I don't mean 
to suggest that Hernandez will replace that. But it will give us 
another weapon offensively.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
