<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Internet Shopping Slips </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WESTPORT, Conn. (AP) -- The percentage of Internet users making a  
purchase online decreased slightly in the second quarter, the first 
drop in a year, according to a survey. 
</P>
<P>
	The percentage of people with online access who said they  
purchased something from a Web site fell to 71 percent in the 
second quarter, down from 74 percent in the first quarter, 
according to Greenfield Online, a Westport, Conn.-based Internet 
marketing research firm. 
</P>
<P>
	The decline followed four straight quarters of increases in  
online purchasing, according to Greenfield. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenfield said the decline could be attributed to there being  
no specific reason to shop. The 90-day period covered by the March 
tracking study included post-Christmas shopping. 
</P>
<P>
	Online auctions, however, were an exception, rising from 40 to  
43 percent from March to May, according to the survey. 
</P>
<P>
	The survey found a growing percentage of online consumers are  
making multiple purchases and 95 percent said they plan to buy the 
same amount or even more online in the future. And for the first 
time, CDs outranked books as the top online purchase, followed by 
computer software, computer hardware and airline tickets. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenfield findings were based on 2,598 respondents selected  
randomly from a pool of more than a million individuals who have 
agreed to participate in online research. Greenfield said the 
respondents are likely to be more experienced than typical Internet 
users, though all levels of users are represented in the survey. 
Greenfield says the findings were weighted to represent the total 
Internet population in terms of age, gender and region. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
