<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Purdue's Tiffany Young Dies in Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GARY, Ind. (AP) -- Purdue women's basketball player Tiffany Young  
was killed when her car was hit by a drunken driver. 
</P>
<P>
	The 21-year-old guard, a member of Purdue's 1999 NCAA national  
championship team, would have been a senior for the Boilermakers 
this season. 
</P>
<P>
	Young was pronounced dead at the scene of the accident Saturday  
night. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Purdue women's basketball family is shocked and deeply  
saddened by this tragedy,'' coach Kristy Curry said Sunday night. 
``Words cannot express how dearly we will miss Tiffany. She was 
more than special and she stood for everything that was right in 
this world.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Young was with her boyfriend, also a Purdue student, who was  
visiting his family in Gary, the university said. Young was 
apparently returning to West Lafayette with her boyfriend and an 
unidentified third passenger. 
</P>
<P>
	Young's boyfriend and the third passenger remained hospitalized  
late Sunday, the school said. 
</P>
<P>
	The driver of the vehicle that hit Young's car had a  
blood-alcohol content of .30 and was taken into custody by Gary 
Police, the school said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Gary Police would not release any further information about the  
accident or any charges pending. 
</P>
<P>
	``Tiffany, from day one, was the epitome of a Purdue  
student-athlete,'' Purdue athletic director Morgan Burke said. 
``She was bright, articulate, compassionate and competitive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 5-foot-11 Young averaged 3.3 points and 1.5 rebounds in her  
three-year career and started all 33 games during the 1997-98 
season. Her career highs were 16 points and seven rebounds. 
</P>
<P>
	A physical therapy major, Young was named Academic All-Big Ten  
last season. 
</P>
<P>
	She was a native of Hillsboro, Ala., and was a standout at East  
Lawrence High School. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
