<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fittipaldi Knocked Out in Accident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MADISON, Ill. (AP) -- Christian Fittipaldi, fourth in the CART  
season point standings, was knocked unconscious Monday during a 
test session at Gateway International Raceway and was to be 
hospitalized overnight for tests and observation. 
</P>
<P>
	The 28-year-old Brazilian hit the wall in turn one on the  
1.27-mile oval and was unconscious for between five and 10 minutes, 
according to witnesses. He regained consciousness while being 
transported to a local hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	Fittipaldi, the nephew of former CART FedEx Series and Formula  
One star Emerson Fittipaldi, was then airlifted to St. Louis 
University Hospital and admitted to the neurological intensive care 
unit for testing and observation. He was to remain hospitalized at 
least overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	According to CART rules, a driver who is knocked unconscious  
cannot compete for a minimum of seven days, effectively keeping him 
out of Sunday's Tenneco Automotive Grand Prix of Detroit. 
</P>
<P>
	He missed seven races in 1997 after breaking his leg in a crash  
during a race in Australia, then missed the Milwaukee race in 1998 
after suffering a concussion in a crash during the opening 
practice. 
</P>
<P>
	Missing Sunday's race could prove more expensive, since  
Fittipaldi is in the midst of the best season of his five-year CART 
career. He won his first pole at Rio de Janeiro in May and earned 
his first CART victory on July 11 in Elkhart Lake, Wis. 
</P>
<P>
	He is 28 points behind leader Juan Montoya and is six behind  
Newman-Haas Racing teammate Michael Andretti, who is third. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
