<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sound Bites: Audio Reviews </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	``Here and Now'' (Tone-Cool) -- Rod Piazza and The Mighty Flyers  

</P>
<P>
	Harmonica ace Rod Piazza and his longtime Mighty Flyers band  
dish up a hearty serving of jump blues on ``Here and Now,'' second 
disc for Tone-Cool Records and follow-up to a very successful 1998. 
Piazza won a W.C. Handy Award and the Mighty Flyers won the BAM 
California Music Award for outstanding blues band. Piazza has been 
blowing the blues since 1965 and playing with wife/pianist Honey 
Piazza since the early 1970s. Piazza waxes as tender as a bluesman 
can toward his beloved on ``Brought Together by the Blues.'' The 
style throughout is California swing married with traditional 
electric blues. Guitarist Rick ``L.A. Holmes'' Holmstrom powers the 
quintet. 
</P>
<P>
	-- By James Reindl, Associated Press Writer.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	``Lone-Star Shootout'' (Alligator Records) -- Lonnie Brooks, Long  
John Hunter and Phillip Walker 

</P>
<P>
	One can only imagine the recording session for ``Lone-Star  
Shootout,'' featuring Gulf Coast blues veterans Lonnie Brooks, Long 
John Hunter and Phillip Walker. They probably picked up their 
guitars and didn't quit playing until the tape ran out, if then. 
All hail from Louisiana or Texas and an era in the 1950s and 1960s 
when playing loud, long and with style were the only ways to get a 
gig in the refinery and shipyard bars. This is a good-time record 
with plenty of hot playing and soul. 
</P>
<P>
	-- By James Reindl, Associated Press Writer.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	``I Like the Way You Work It'' (Black Top) -- Mike Morgan &AMP; The  
Crawl 

</P>
<P>
	Blues guitarist Mike Morgan is back with another scorcher from  
his native Texas. Sidekick and harpist-singer Lee McBee is back for 
the ride, which starts hot with ``Somebody Help Me'' and kicks 
through a dozen more Morgan and/or McBee originals. Young Texan 
talent Shawn Pittman helps out on guitar on three of the tracks. 
Can't make it to the club to see them? Slap this one in the disc 
player and you'll feel like you're there. 
</P>
<P>
	-- By James Reindl, Associated Press Writer.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	``Running With Scissors'' (Volcano) -- ``Weird Al'' Yankovic  

</P>
<P>
	Twenty years after spoofing ``My Sharona'' with ``My Bologna,''  
``Weird Al'' Yankovic is still getting laughs with novelty songs. 
Funny how they're sometimes more entertaining than the originals. 
</P>
<P>
	I'll take ``Pretty Fly for a Rabbi'' any day over The  
Offspring's ``Pretty Fly (For a White Guy).'' Sample refrain: ``How 
ya doin' Bernie? Oy vey, oy vey!'' Now that's chutzpah. 
</P>
<P>
	And Yankovic continues to mine yucks at the expense of the  
overweight (remember ``Fat''?), this time remaking ``Zoot Suit 
Riot'' into ``Grapefruit Diet.'' Also inspired is ``Jerry 
Springer,'' a dead-on parody of ``One Week'' by the Barenaked 
Ladies. 
</P>
<P>
	Of course, a little of this goes a long way and the original  
songs on ``Running With Scissors,'' Yankovic's 10th album, aren't 
nearly as clever. But his polka medley (sampling Marilyn Manson AND 
Hanson, among others) is first-rate kitsch. 
</P>
<P>
	-- By David Kligman, Associated Press Writer.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990802.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 12:30:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Webb Sets Sight on Even Bigger Game  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PRIDDIS, Alberta (AP) -- When she was 16, Karrie Webb won a  
junior tournament in Australia that earned her a trip to Florida. 
She spent a week there with Greg Norman learning what it takes to 
be a professional golfer. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't know I was going to be sitting here eight years  
later,'' Webb said. 
</P>
<P>
	In the foothills of the Canadian Rockies, Webb was floating in  
the clouds Sunday after winning the du Maurier Classic for her 
first major championship. 
</P>
<P>
	Already No. 1 in the women's rankings, Webb managed to reclaim  
some of the spotlight from double-major winner Juli Inkster. The du 
Maurier was Webb's sixth victory of the year and the 15th of an 
LPGA Tour career that began just 3 1/2 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Not included in her victory count is the Women's British Open,  
which Webb won in 1995 and which could be the next LPGA major if 
anti-tobacco legislation forces du Maurier to drop its sponsorship. 
</P>
<P>
	``She's a special talent, and we're lucky to have her on tour,''  
Dawn Coe-Jones said. ``This is her first major, and I think it is 
going to be the first of many.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Few can argue that point.  
</P>
<P>
	Webb has emerged as the dominant force in women's golf, and  
Sunday was only a sampling. 
</P>
<P>
	Five strokes behind Laura Davies when the final round began at  
Priddis Greens Golf and Country Club, Webb got within three strokes 
of the lead with six holes to play, then treated the Canadian 
gallery to a breathless display of irons and clutch putting. 
</P>
<P>
	She saved par from 20 feet on No. 13 to stay in the hunt, only  
three strokes behind. She birdied the next three holes, no putt 
longer than 8 feet. And needing a birdie on the par-5 18th to have 
a chance, she stroked a 5-wood that landed 15 feet behind the hole 
in the rough, setting up a 5-foot birdie putt. 
</P>
<P>
	``Just the best player on tour this year,'' said Davies, who  
three-putted the last two greens and finished two strokes back. 
``She proved it again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Webb has been proving it from the minute she joined the tour.  
</P>
<P>
	As a rookie, she won her second event and became the first  
player to surpass $1 million on the LPGA Tour. Webb has won at 
least twice in all four of her seasons, and her du Maurier victory 
enabled her to set the earnings record of $1,254,051 with three 
months left in the year. 
</P>
<P>
	And she's only 24.  
</P>
<P>
	Annika Sorenstam, who skipped the final major of the year to  
rest, has won 17 times -- including two U.S. Opens -- since joining 
the LPGA Tour in 1994. Webb figures to pass that mark, perhaps even 
this year. 
</P>
<P>
	She still doesn't compare to Nancy Lopez, who won nine times as  
a rookie in 1978 and had 23 victories after her fourth full season. 
But given the depth in women's golf, it is tantalizing to imagine 
what the future holds. 
</P>
<P>
	Her swing hasn't changed, but her confidence has grown without  
any signs Webb is satisfied with her success. 
</P>
<P>
	Sorenstam and Se Ri Pak last year have always won their  
tournaments in batches. Webb had at least a share of the lead in 10 
of her first 11 rounds this year. She has finished out of the top 
eight only once this year, when she missed the cut in the LPGA 
Championship. 
</P>
<P>
	``Somehow, I find something every week to put me into  
contention,'' Webb said. ``I don't really have an answer except 
that I work hard, and confidence is a big thing, too. I really 
believe in myself, and I know what my ability is. I'm not happy 
with anything less than the best.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That attitude is what has driven Norman to the most consistent,  
successful golf since the days of Jack Nicklaus -- a victory 
somewhere in the world every year but one since 1976. 
</P>
<P>
	Norman saw it coming. He remembers when Webb came to visit in  
1991, how she outworked the teen-aged boy who also spent a week in 
Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	``Karrie was right there the whole way,'' Norman once recalled.  
``It was obvious she had the game and the mental toughness to 
succeed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Johnny Miller, whose career was like a comet, once said he got  
to the top of the mountain and wondered what was next. Nicklaus 
reached the top and looked for the next mountain. 
</P>
<P>
	Where does that leave Webb?  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not even halfway up the mountain yet,'' Webb said. ``I've  
got a long way to go. For things to have happened so quickly, 
obviously it's hard to set goals. But I love being in the position 
I'm in. I love playing good golf, and I love having a chance to 
win. That's all I need to drive me.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990802.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 14:30:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nani Rose Wins Saratoga Feature </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. (AP) -- Nani Rose, trained by Patrick  
Byrne, registered a half-length victory over Perfect Sting, owned 
by Frank Stronach, in Saratoga's Monday feature, the $112,800, 
Grade III Lake George Stakes for 3-year-old fillies. 
</P>
<P>
	Intrigued, finished third in the field of eight, three-quarters  
of a length further back. 
</P>
<P>
	Byrne and Stronach are waging a battle in court over $384,000  
which the trainer claims is owed him in back pay dating to their 
association in 1997. Stronach claims that Byrne misinterpreted 
their agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	Nani Rose's frontrunning victory was decisive as she drew away  
early in the final straight and held on gamely in the final yards. 
</P>
<P>
	Nani Rose remained undefeated on turf in three starts covering 1  
1/16 miles in 1:40 to earn $67,680 for Stonerside Stable. 
</P>
<P>
	The winner returned $5.10, $3.20 and $2.80 as the favorite.  
Perfect Sting paid $3.40 and $2.60 and Intrigued was $3.80 to show. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990802.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 16:21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Andre Reed, Bills Work Out Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FREDONIA, N.Y. (AP) -- Andre Reed, Buffalo's leading career  
receiver and one of its few remaining links to the Bills' four 
straight Super Bowl appearances, added another team record: 
shortest holdout. 
</P>
<P>
	Reed, who threatened to quit if the Bills refused to renegotiate  
his contract, practiced for the first time Monday after working out 
a contract extension with team owner Ralph Wilson. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've always wanted to play football,'' said Reed, 35. ``That's  
what I was born to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reed, who missed two minicamps as well as the first two days of  
training camp at Fredonia State, was uncharacteristically jovial 
after starting his 15th season in Buffalo. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had a nice talk with Mr. Wilson about a week and a half ago,  
and we talked about a lot of things,'' Reed said. ``And he agreed 
with me about a lot of things.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One thing they agreed upon was more money for Reed, who this  
season will make $2.2 million, or $900,000 more than his contract 
was due to pay him. 
</P>
<P>
	``All I wanted was to be treated fairly,'' Reed said. ``I just  
wanted to be paid. That's all you deserve. Fortunately we got 
something accomplished, and I'm here to play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The new deal sweetened the pot considerably for Reed, who got a  
$1.8 million signing bonus and a three-year pact that includes a 
one-year extension. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was born to wear a red, white and blue helmet, and when Mr.  
Wilson heard that he said `OK, OK,''' Reed said. 
</P>
<P>
	Reed showed up for the morning practice, having joined the Bills  
for their team meeting on Sunday night. 
</P>
<P>
	The third leading receiver on the NFL's career list behind Jerry  
Rice and Art Monk, Reed is one of only three Buffalo players -- 
along with Bruce Smith and Thurman Thomas -- still around from the 
team's four straight Super Bowl losses of the early 1990s. 
</P>
<P>
	His teammates cheered as Reed took the field. He hugged Smith,  
stretched and pulled on his pads. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a little bit behind, which is funny,'' quarterback Doug  
Flutie said. ``He's got to catch up to some of the young guys, 
actually. But every time he runs a route he's open.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After chatting with Eric Moulds, the team's leading receiver  
last year who credits Reed with helping him, Reed caught a pass in 
front of No. 1 draft pick Antoine Winfield and spun away from 
defensive back Donovan Greer. 
</P>
<P>
	One teammate sang a mock hymn in praise as Reed faced the press.  
</P>
<P>
	Reed joked with a television reporter: ``You said I was speeding  
down the highway and that's not right,'' Reed said. ``I was going 
the speed limit. No cops, man.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last week Reed's agent had all of Buffalo wondering if his  
client would follow Sabres goaltender Dominik Hasek, who announced 
last week that he would retire after next season. However, Reed 
wouldn't have waited a year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hate to say it, but I was contemplating not coming back,''  
Reed said. 
</P>
<P>
	With 889 receptions, including 63 last year, Reed needs just 51  
catches to pass Monk as the second-leading receiver in NFL history. 
Rice is first with 1,139. 
</P>
<P>
	``I knew that was a milestone that was attainable this year,''  
Reed said. ``That would be a great thing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reed, not always the most approachable of the Bills, relapsed  
into sarcasm when someone asked him if had a timetable for 
retirement. ``Do you? When are you going to retire, in about 20 
years?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Then he got serious. ``No, there's no such thing as a  
timetable,'' Reed said. ``I'm just going to see how it goes this 
year, how I feel at the end of the season. If I can stay healthy, 
I'll play again.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990802.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 16:21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
