<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 14:00:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nate Newton Inches Closer to Action </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SPARTANBURG, S.C. (AP) -- Nate Newton's bid to extend his NFL  
career inched forward Monday when the Carolina Panthers decided he 
was fit enough to join his teammates for full-squad workouts. 
</P>
<P>
	While his teammates spent the first three days of training camp  
running plays and going through group drills, Newton was secluded 
in a different part of the complex for private workouts with 
strength and conditioning coach Jerry Simmons. 
</P>
<P>
	The goal was to build up the 13-year NFL veteran's endurance and  
flexibility so he could compete for a spot on the offensive line. 
</P>
<P>
	Even when he was cleared for team drills Monday, Newton still  
took it slow, participating in only selected drills for brief 
periods. 
</P>
<P>
	Outfitted in full pads for the first time, the 6-foot-3 Newton  
looked larger than his listed weight of 348 pounds. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just went through a few drills. I didn't do much, but it  
still felt good,'' Newton said. ``I'm trying to get used to the 
pads and try to get back and do a little bit of work.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Newton, 37, was signed to a one-year, $420,000 deal by the  
Panthers in June after he was deemed expendable by the Dallas 
Cowboys, for whom he played 13 seasons and made six Pro Bowl 
appearances. 
</P>
<P>
	Carolina coach George Seifert said there is no timetable for  
bringing along Newton, who will try to unseat Anthony Redmon as the 
Panthers' starting left guard. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not like we're looking to move him into the starting  
spot. I think Redmon's doing a good job, and we'll just see how the 
competition does go there,'' Seifert said. 
</P>
<P>
	To challenge for a roster spot and then for a starting job,  
Newton first wants to get down to 335 pounds. He said he is pleased 
with his progress and is closing in on that figure, but would not 
divulge his exact weight. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm doing fabulous. I'm the type of guy that once I hit it,  
I'm all about getting it going,'' he said. ``I'm close. That's all 
you need to know.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Newton laughed when asked to compare the food at the Cowboys'  
camp to the Panthers' training table cuisine. 
</P>
<P>
	``It doesn't stack up because I ain't been on it yet,'' he said.  
``I'm a fruit and potatoes guy, a fruit and salad guy.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990802.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 15:00:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans, Pork All Higher  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Grain and soybean futures rocketed higher Monday on the Chicago  
Board of Trade in the absence of stress-relieving rainfall in major 
growing regions, with the dry spell threatening to reduce crop 
production. 
</P>
<P>
	On other markets, pork futures moved sharply higher.  
</P>
<P>
	Corn and soybean prices continued their sharp gains made during  
last week's late rally even as temperatures in Midwest growing 
regions fell back to more-tolerable readings in the lower 80s from 
highs in the 90s and 100s late last week. 
</P>
<P>
	While the threat of heat stress no longer appears to be in the  
picture, vulnerable corn and soybean crops could suffer from a lack 
of rainfall. Forecasters currently say there is no chance for 
appreciable rainfall in the next week, which could affect crops 
that are seeing dangerously low moisture levels. 
</P>
<P>
	A lack of heavy rainfall in recent weeks has caused alarm bells  
to go off across farming regions. Parts of Maryland, Ohio, 
Pennsylvania, West Virginia and Virginia were declared drought 
disaster areas by U.S. Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman, with 
some farmers reporting their expected average yields had been 
reduced by half. 
</P>
<P>
	Fields in Illinois and Iowa, the two largest corn and soybean  
growing states, were expected to fare better, but dryness also 
persisted in those regions after farmers saw less rainfall that had 
been forecast. 
</P>
<P>
	Futures investors were expected to closely examine the USDA's  
latest crop development update, which could provide a more reliable 
indication of final production numbers. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency reported after trading had ended that soybeans  
nationwide in good to excellent condition tumbled to 57 percent 
from 65 percent a week earlier. In Illinois, conditions plunged to 
53 percent from 62 percent, while they fell to 43 percent from 58 
percent in Indiana. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn crops fared better nationwide, with the good-to-excellent  
condition falling to 63 percent from 70 percent. But corn crop 
conditions in Illinois and Indiana also fell sharply. 
</P>
<P>
	Meantime, the National Weather Service's latest 10-day forecast,  
released after trading ended, reported key growing areas will 
receive normal temperatures and above-normal rainfall. That could 
pressure prices when trading resumes Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for December delivery rose 19 cents to $2.98 3/4 a bushel;  
December corn rose the limit 12 cents to $2.26 1/2 a bushel; December 
oats jumped 6 1/2 cents to $1.18 1/4 a bushel; November soybeans rose the 
limit 30 cents to $4.63 1/4 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Pork futures jumped on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange amid  
market talk the USDA was set to announce details of donated pork to 
Russia. 
</P>
<P>
	The American donations to the economically challenged country  
could help reduce a persistent pork glut, analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices also rose on the rally in grain futures, which could lead  
to higher feed costs and force pork producers to eliminate more of 
their herds. 
</P>
<P>
	October lean hogs rose 2 cents to 45.35 cents a pound; August  
pork bellies rose the limit 3 cents to 55.12 cents a pound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
