<DOCNO> APW19990802.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 15:10:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 6 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Clinton Backs Wife's Candor  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton today endorsed first lady  
Hillary Rodham Clinton's candor about his infidelities. In an 
interview with Talk magazine, she called her husband's adultery the 
product of emotional scars -- ``abuse,'' she termed it -- left by his 
mother and grandmother when he was 4 years old. Speaking of 
Clinton, White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said: ``He told me from 
the reports he's gotten that it's a generally favorable article 
about the first lady, that he's comfortable with the views 
expressed in the article and the fact that she did the interview.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Christian Coalition Charges Tossed  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A federal judge today threw out most of the  
charges in a government lawsuit accusing the Christian Coalition of 
illegally aiding GOP candidates. U.S. District Judge Joyce Green 
rejected arguments by the Federal Election Commission that the 
coalition's contact with campaigns and its distribution of voter 
guides to churches on the Sunday before Election Days were 
excessive campaign contributions. 

</P>
<P>
	Heat Breaks, Deaths Rise  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Cooler temperatures prevailed in the Midwest and  
most of the East today, as the national death toll from the 
mid-summer heat wave rose to 197. A cold front pushed across the 
Midwest during the weekend bringing relief to many people. 
Temperatures were in the 70s across most of the Ohio Valley into 
parts of the Northeast. The Oklahoma Medical Examiner's Office 
reported that the state's heat-related death toll had reached 
eight. 

</P>
<P>
	India Train Crash Kills Nearly 200  
</P>
<P>
	GAUHATI, India (AP) -- Two high-speed trains collided in a remote  
section of eastern India near the border with Bangladesh, killing 
190 people and injuring 310. Railway officials said the toll was 
likely to climb to 250, and news agencies said it could reach 400 
or more. The impact flipped coaches on top of each other and hurled 
sleeping passengers though flaming compartments. Rail officials 
blamed a signal failure. 

</P>
<P>
	Robertson Favored for NATO Chief  
</P>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- British Defense Secretary George  
Robertson, who impressed NATO with his determined stance during the 
Kosovo conflict, is likely to get the alliance's top job. Robertson 
received the backing today of 16 NATO nations, and three more said 
they were still consulting on the matter. Javier Solana is ending 
his four-year NATO term a few months early to be the European 
Union's foreign policy coordinator. 

</P>
<P>
	Dole Puts Emphasis on Values  
</P>
<P>
	MARSHALLTOWN, Iowa (AP) -- With a new emphasis on values,  
Elizabeth Dole said today that a president should use the White 
House as a ``bully pulpit'' to show the difference between right 
and wrong. ``I don't think President Clinton has been the leader 
that he should be,'' she said. The Republican presidential 
candidate said: ``I'm speaking of things like integrity, honesty, 
respect for your fellow man, personal responsibility.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Good Cholesterol Gene Found  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Scientists have identified a gene that regulates  
the body's level of so-called good cholesterol, a breakthrough that 
could someday lead to a new way to treat one of the most common 
causes of heart disease. Flaws in the gene, known as ABC1, prevent 
the production of a protein that the body needs to rinse excess bad 
cholesterol and other fats out of cells and the bloodstream. ABC1 
was isolated in separate studies by scientists in Germany and in 
Canada. Their results appear in the August issue of Nature 
Genetics. 

</P>
<P>
	Airlines Cut Fares Systemwide  
</P>
<P>
	FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) -- The first full air fare sale of the  
fall is going into effect. Northwest Airlines, the nation's 
fourth-largest airline, kicked off the sale during the weekend, 
with some off-peak prices discounted by as much as 25 percent. 
Other airlines matching included American, U.S. Airways, America 
West, Continental, Trans World Airlines, United and Delta Air 
Lines. 

</P>
