<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Janzen, McCarron Hit Holes-In-One  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BARRINGTON, R.I. (AP) -- Lee Janzen and Scott McCarron defied  
astounding odds Monday by making consecutive holes-in-one on the 
first day of the CVS Charity Classic. 
</P>
<P>
	``After Lee's shot, I had a feeling I was going to make it,''  
McCarron said. ``It was one of those wild feelings.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The team of Stuart Appleby and Jeff Sluman birdied the first  
five holes and held the lead with a 12-under-par 59. In last place 
at 67 was the main draw, Jack and Gary Nicklaus. 
</P>
<P>
	The two-day, 10-team tournament at the Rhode Island Country Club  
uses a best-ball format, which encourages low scoring because each 
two-man team uses its low score on each hole. 
</P>
<P>
	At 145 yards, the par-3 17th hole seemed ideal for a  
hole-in-one. In fact, a tournament sponsor promised a car to the 
first player who could do it. Janzen got the car when his tee shot 
bounced three times and then spun left to right into the hole. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm watching the crowd for their reaction and they went  
berserk,'' Janzen said. ``It's amazing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McCarron then hit immediately after Janzen, sending his shot  
right at the flag. The ball bounced twice and plopped right into 
the hole. 
</P>
<P>
	After Janzen's hole-in-one, McCarron had yelled, ``You've got to  
get the ball out of the hole and make some room for mine.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Yeah, right,'' Janzen thought.  
</P>
<P>
	Fans screamed and high-fived one another. Another member of the  
foursome, Tim Herron, fell to the grass in amazement 
</P>
<P>
	Appleby and Sluman played a bogeyless round. Besides their  
initial burst, they birdied three additional holes and eagled the 
538th-yard, 11th hole. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're pretty aggressive players and we have aggressive  
games,'' Appleby said. ``And what's the point of playing safe in a 
two-day event?'' 
</P>
<P>
	The pair, who had never played the course before, hit the  
fairways on just about every hole, repeatedly giving themselves a 
chance for birdie. Sluman birdied six holes and Appleby birdied 
four holes and made the eagle. 
</P>
<P>
	The second-place team, hometown favorites Dana Quigley and  
nephew Brett, didn't have that kind of balance but still shot a 61. 
</P>
<P>
	Though Dana, a senior PGA, has had a better year, it was Brett,  
a fringe player on the PGA Tour who carried the team, recording 
nine birdies before Dana finally birdied the 18th. 
</P>
<P>
	Brett said he knew he had to play well because his uncle was  
tired from a late flight from Utah, where he lost a senior tour 
event in a playoff. 
</P>
<P>
	``That was probably the best I've seen him play and I've seen  
him play a lot of rounds,'' Dana Quigley said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
