<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> White House Touts Welfare Changes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The percentage of Americans on welfare has  
dropped to the lowest level since 1967, according to new figures 
made available as President Clinton prepares to prod the business 
community to hire more people off the rolls. 
</P>
<P>
	The president also will urge states on Tuesday to spend $4.2  
billion in unspent federal welfare money and warn Congress not to 
take it away as some Republicans have suggested, administration 
officials told The Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	``The president will make clear that the job of welfare reform  
isn't done until we've got everybody working,'' said Bruce Reed, 
Clinton's top domestic policy adviser. ``This is not the time for 
Congress to call it quits.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton will meet in Chicago with participants of a Welfare to  
Work Partnership conference that is part cheerleading and part 
training for businesses interested in hiring welfare recipients. 
</P>
<P>
	The president also will encourage businesses to invest in  
poverty-stricken parts of the nation left behind by the economic 
good times -- the theme of his tour of impoverished areas last 
month. 
</P>
<P>
	New figures provided to AP on Monday show that welfare rolls had  
dropped 49 percent from their all-time high in 1994. And 29 states 
have cut their rolls by more than half. 
</P>
<P>
	As of March, just 2.7 percent of the population -- or 7.3 million  
Americans -- was on welfare, the least since Lyndon B. Johnson was 
president. In 1967, the figure was 2.5 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	But the new figures also show the dramatic declines are  
beginning to slow in some states. After large drops, welfare 
caseloads remained relatively stable in Kansas, Louisiana, 
Minnesota, New Hampshire, North Dakota, Oklahoma and West Virginia. 
And they increased in New Mexico and Indiana. 
</P>
<P>
	The figures offer further evidence that the toughest work in  
welfare reform may be ahead, as states deal with people who face 
complex problems -- poor education, domestic violence and drug and 
alcohol addiction. 
</P>
<P>
	The event Tuesday is likely to include plenty of cheers for the  
gains already made, disturbing some who worry about studies that 
show many Americans who leave welfare aren't earning enough to 
escape poverty. 
</P>
<P>
	``The data that is conveniently left out by the White House and  
by too many people in the Congress is this: What are the wage 
levels, what are people making?'' Sen. Paul Wellstone, D-Minn., 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he is always disturbed by Clinton's declarations that  
welfare reform has succeeded. 
</P>
<P>
	``Don't you dare hype this -- these are people's lives,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	But Clinton will continue to emphasize that people are doing  
better now than they were before, Reed said. ``Nobody's going to 
escape poverty by staying on welfare,'' he said. ``Introducing them 
to the world of work gives them a much better chance over the long 
haul.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reed said Clinton also plans to issue a warning to Congress.  
</P>
<P>
	States get $16.5 billion in federal money each year to run their  
welfare programs, but they don't have to spend it immediately. With 
the five-year decline in welfare rolls, many states are saving 
their extra dollars to handle the toughest cases or as a safety 
measure if the economy turns sour. 
</P>
<P>
	But Congress has periodically eyed that money, and GOP budget  
writers are considering taking some of it back to use for other 
domestic programs. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton plans to tell Congress on Tuesday that it would be wrong  
to renege on its promise to give the states a fixed amount of 
welfare money. But he'll also urge states to act before Congress 
reclaims the money. 
</P>
<P>
	``The message to states is 'Spend it,''' Reed said.  
</P>
<P>
	Vice President Al Gore also released new figures Monday showing  
the federal government had hired 14,028 people off welfare, 
surpassing the original goal, set in March 1997, of 10,000 by 2000. 
Most of them are working at the Commerce and Defense departments. 
</P>
<P>
	As of last September, nearly 70 percent of them were still on  
the job after a year -- compared with 37 percent of other, similar 
federal workers. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
