<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 16:10:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Backs Wife's Candor on Sex </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Her husband gave it a ``generally favorable''  
review. Her critics called it a lunge for the sympathy vote. All 
part of the plan, said her strategists. 
</P>
<P>
	While Hillary Rodham Clinton talked, from the pages of a new  
magazine, about Bill Clinton's famous infidelities, Washington 
buzzed: Why dredge all that up now? 
</P>
<P>
	In her month-old campaign for New York's Senate seat, not a  
single voter -- and only one reporter -- has confronted Mrs. Clinton 
with questions about her marriage. Protesters and posters scream 
``Carpetbagger, go home!'' but not much about cheating husbands. 
</P>
<P>
	``Why do I have to talk about things no one else in politics  
does?'' the first lady plaintively asked her Talk magazine 
interviewer before baring her most extensive thoughts yet on 
matters she refused to address when Gennifer Flowers, Paula Jones 
and Monica Lewinsky made headlines. 
</P>
<P>
	Three of Mrs. Clinton's confidantes, one of whom spoke with her  
over the weekend as Talk hyped the interview in its debut edition, 
said the first lady made a political calculation to try and put 
personal questions to rest before they popped up in her campaign. 
She made the decision in May, one associate said on condition of 
anonymity, after being pressed in two TV interviews on CBS and CNN 
about her feelings toward her husband. 
</P>
<P>
	In statewide surveys by the Marist Institute for Public Opinion,  
New Yorkers who do not like Mrs. Clinton overwhelmingly cite 
distaste for her husband as the reason, said pollster Lee 
Miringoff. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is some kind of sense that there's a pothole in the road  
and you don't know how deep it is, so she's trying to pave it 
over,'' said Miringoff. 
</P>
<P>
	New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, Mrs. Clinton's potential  
GOP rival for the Senate, said his campaign would not exploit her 
family troubles. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't believe somebody's private life ... should be part of  
a political campaign,'' said Giuliani, who has faced questions 
about his own marriage. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton used in her interview the language of psychobabble  
that she has long professed to despise. She called her husband's 
adultery ``a sin of weakness,'' and the product of emotional scars 
-- ``abuse,'' she termed it -- left by battles between his mother and 
grandmother when he was 4 years old. 
</P>
<P>
	Bill Clinton was never physically abused, White House spokesman  
Joe Lockhart clarified. And, Clinton has ``stated openly, publicly, 
that he is responsible for all of his actions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton insisted she stayed with her husband out of love,  
not ambition. 
</P>
<P>
	To Republican strategist Rich Galen, Mrs. Clinton came off  
sounding like an apologist for the president's behavior. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not the vast right-wing conspiracy's fault anymore, it's  
the grandma's,'' Galen sniffed. 
</P>
<P>
	``She wants to maintain her status as America's 'wounded woman  
in chief.' That's the only reason she's been popular.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It took a months-long dance to get Mrs. Clinton's story told.  
Talk editor Tina Brown assigned a writer friendly with the first 
lady and plied her with the attentions of a Paris fashion 
photographer. While established news organizations such as Newsweek 
and Newsday were refused seats on Mrs. Clinton's plane during trips 
earlier this year to North Africa and Ireland, the White House gave 
Talk two coveted slots in her entourage. 
</P>
<P>
	Spokeswoman Marsha Berry and chief of staff Melanne Verveer, who  
usually do not discuss the Clintons' personal problems, allowed 
themselves to be quoted in Talk. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've slowly seen a physical passion come back into their  
lives,'' Verveer confided on the glossy pages. 
</P>
<P>
	By Monday morning, the article appeared to have raised more  
questions than it answered, consuming the first half of Lockhart's 
daily briefing. 
</P>
<P>
	For the record, Clinton didn't mind his wife's candor.  
</P>
<P>
	``He told me from the reports he's gotten that it's a generally  
favorable article about the first lady, that he's comfortable with 
the views expressed in the article and the fact that she did the 
interview,'' Lockhart said. 
</P>
<P>
	But the two associates of the first lady, who spoke on condition  
of anonymity, said they were concerned that she appeared to be 
making excuses for her husband at a time when many voters are weary 
of the president and his personal scandals. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton's spokesman, Howard Wolfson, said her campaign  
never discusses its polling. On the Talk article specifically, 
Wolfson said, ``The only reaction I've asked for is from my mother 
and she thought it was great.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
