<DOCNO> APW19990802.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 13:50:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AutoNation To Separate Rental Unit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- AutoNation Inc. plans to separate its lackluster  
rental-car business, including the big Alamo and National chains, 
from its growing auto sales operations in what could lead to its 
eventual spinoff or sale. 
</P>
<P>
	Separating the rental unit will allow investors ``to better  
recognize and evaluate the strengths and growth prospects of our 
automotive retail operations,'' Chairman H. Wayne Huizenga said in 
the company's second-quarter earnings report Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The company said its board was still looking at options for how  
the separation will take place. Analyst Efraim Levy of Standard and 
Poor's said a spinoff was the most likely option, either in whole 
or in parts. The company spun off its Republic Services trash 
hauling business earlier this year through a sale of stock. 
</P>
<P>
	The separation of the rental business is the latest effort by  
publicly owned AutoNation to boost its lagging stock price. Wall 
Street has been wary of AutoNation, in part because of the 
industry's cyclical nature, but also because of missteps the 
company has had in trying to devise a winning long-term strategy. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's the best of times for automotive retailing, yet they've  
repeatedly had disappointments,'' Levy said. 
</P>
<P>
	AutoNation was up 31 1/4 cents, or by 2 percent, at $15.25 a share  
Monday on the New York Stock Exchange, well below its 52-week high 
of $24.37 1/2. 
</P>
<P>
	The company also announced plans to buy back an additional $500  
million of its stock, for a total of $1 billion, under its ongoing 
repurchase program. Through June, $449 million worth of stock had 
been repurchased. 
</P>
<P>
	Company spokesman Jim Donahue said AutoNation hoped to complete  
the rental-unit separation as soon as possible. The unit includes 
National Car Rental System Inc. and Alamo Rent-A-Car Inc. -- which 
both operate internationally -- and CarTemps USA, formerly known as 
Spirit Rent-A-Car Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Huizenga bought National and Alamo in 1996, in part to provide a  
steady source of used cars to his AutoNation USA used-car lots. But 
the logistics proved impractical, and as Huizenga expanded into the 
new-car business, he turned to more traditional sources: auctions, 
trade-ins and formerly leased cars. 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview in late June, Huizenga's co-chief executive,  
Steven Berrard, acknowledged that the company was frustrated with 
its stock price. 
</P>
<P>
	``Clearly, there were early problems with AutoNation, which are  
behind us and solved,'' he said. ``We've had a few hiccups in the 
rental car business, and yet our auto retail business has performed 
above everyone's expectations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The rental-unit separation comes as AutoNation's executive ranks  
are being shuffled. The company is searching for a new CEO to 
replace Berrard, who announced a month ago that he was leaving to 
manage his own investment firm. 
</P>
<P>
	The company also announced Monday that John H. Costello,  
president and chief operating officer, had resigned and was being 
replaced by Michael Maroone, former president of AutoNation's 
automotive retail group. Costello, a veteran retailer who came from 
Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co. only eight months ago, resigned to pursue 
Internet business ventures. 
</P>
<P>
	Maroone joined AutoNation two years ago when the company, then  
called Republic Industries Inc., bought his dealer group in 
southern Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	AutoNation reported that second-quarter earnings from continuing  
operations rose 79 percent to $97.1 million, or 21 cents a share, 
from $54.2 million, or 11 cents a share, in the same period a year 
ago. Revenue rose 60 percent to $5.1 billion from $3.2 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Same-store revenue, measuring performance at outlets open at  
least a year, grew 5 percent, including an 8 percent gain in new 
vehicle sales. 
</P>
<P>
	AutoNation has 412 automotive franchises and 42 AutoNation USA  
stores in 24 states. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
