<DOCNO> APW19990802.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 10:40:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Man Who Placed Ad for Heir Inundated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PINE CITY, Minn. (AP) -- Clayton Goward had a problem -- he was  
looking for someone who could inherit his $375,000 estate. Now he 
has a bigger problem -- he can't get any peace and quiet. 
</P>
<P>
	Since the 79-year-old retired lathe operator placed an ad in the  
Star Tribune last month asking for advice on how to find a suitable 
heir, he's been besieged with 22,000 letters, postcards and 
packages. 
</P>
<P>
	He got so many phone calls -- some from as far away as Europe --  
that he had to change his number to an unpublished one. 
</P>
<P>
	``I sought only ideas and a solution for making my will, nothing  
more,'' Goward said. ``What followed is not what I wanted. 
Worldwide coverage resulted, and I am now swamped. About anything 
that you can think of has been written.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some responses are religious. Others suggest that Goward donate  
his estate to charity -- which he says is what he might end up 
doing. One college student from Idaho told Goward he should start a 
scholarship fund. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd even be willing to apply'' for such a scholarship, the  
student volunteered. ``Believe me, I could use some help!!'' 
</P>
<P>
	Goward got divorced long ago, and his relationship with his  
three sons is strained. 
</P>
<P>
	He said most of the responses have come from women. He's heard  
romantic proposals and plenty of stories of hardship. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of people want personal help, and I don't have the  
millions of dollars to help them,'' he said. ``You feel sorry about 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Now Goward has a new request -- he says he needs volunteers to  
help sort the mail and trinkets that have arrived at his door. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990802.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 22:30:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Owners To Sell Interest in Twins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) -- The owners of the Minnesota Twins said  
Monday night they have agreed to sell their entire interest in the 
team to a St. Paul group by Oct. 1, and the team would move from 
Minneapolis if a sales tax referendum to build a stadium passes. 
</P>
<P>
	Major League Baseball has also agreed to the deal, and the  
league has approved a move from the Metrodome in Minneapolis if St. 
Paul can build a new stadium. Mayor Norm Coleman wants voters to 
approve a half-cent increase in the city's sales tax in the Nov. 2 
election. Legislative approval is also needed. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the agreement, St. Paul and the Twins would each  
contribute $8.5 million a year to build a $325 million outdoor 
stadium along the Mississippi River, Coleman said. The state would 
be asked to pay about one-third of the total cost of the project. 
</P>
<P>
	If taxes collected on players' salaries don't equal the state's  
share, the Twins have guaranteed the difference, Coleman said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The net effect of this provision is that the team is committed  
to paying about one-third of the costs of construction, but is 
virtually guaranteeing two-thirds of the costs of construction,'' 
Coleman said. 
</P>
<P>
	The player payroll tax would be similar to that now existing in  
Pittsburgh. 
</P>
<P>
	The Twins also have agreed to pay any cost overruns for the  
construction of the ballpark. The Twins also would pay for 
operating costs of the team and cover maintenance of the facility. 
</P>
<P>
	``Finally, I firmly believe that in addition to Twins  
ballplayers, major market teams and players like Chuck Knoblauch 
and the New York Yankees should help build a new ballpark for 
Minnesota,'' Coleman said. ``We have agreed that a player's tax 
incorporating these principals will be imposed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coleman thanked Twins owner Carl Pohlad and his family for the  
deal. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today because of their agreement to sell 100 percent in the  
Minnesota Twins, they have given us the opportunity to save 
baseball in Minnesota for the new millennium,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	A statement from the Twins said the Pohlad family has agreed to  
a letter of intent with the city of St. Paul authorizing Coleman to 
seek buyers. The statement also said one condition is that the team 
must remain in Minnesota for the next 30 years. 
</P>
<P>
	The Twins and the city anticipate the completion of construction  
of a 38,000- to 40,000-seat ballpark in the spring of 2003. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990802.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 15:00:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> HSBC Holdings Profits Up 10 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- HSBC Holdings Plc, which owns Hong Kong's  
largest bank, said Monday that strong growth in the United States 
and Britain and a modest recovery in Asia drove its profits up 10 
percent in the first half of the year to $4.07 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	HSBC, which was rocked last year by the Asian crisis and bad  
debts, was able to lower its provisions for bad debts to $1.08 
billion from $1.15 billion in the first half of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	An HSBC affiliate, Hang Seng Bank Ltd., said its pretax profits  
rose 13 percent to $646 million. The bank also was able to lower 
its bad debt provisions 13 percent to $101 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've benefited from the continuing strength in the United  
States and United Kingdom economies and a degree of recovery in 
some emerging markets,'' said John Bond, HSBC group chairman. But 
he cautioned that the Asian recovery would be ``uneven.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Huge provisions for bad loans in Indonesia, Thailand and China  
contributed to a 21 percent plunge in the group's 1998 profit. 
</P>
<P>
	HSBC is based in London, but its presence is biggest in Hong  
Kong, which accounted for 34 percent of its profit in the first 
half. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the rise in the group's profit and a drop in overall  
provisions for bad loans, HSBC's Hongkong and Shanghai Banking 
Corp. Ltd. still set aside $218 million as loss provisions for its 
China-related bad loans in Hong Kong, mainland China and Macau. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of HSBC rose $2.37 1/2 to $62.62 1/2 in trading on the New York  
Stock Exchange. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990802.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 15:02:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Clinton, Gore Bid Friend Farewell </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton remembered Washington  
lobbyist Dan Dutko on Monday as an irreverent, funny man, a devoted 
Democrat and loyal friend who stuck by him during the toughest 
moments of his presidency. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton, joined by Vice President Al Gore and first lady Hillary  
Rodham Clinton, attended a packed memorial service at Washington's 
Temple Sinai for Dutko, 54, who died July 25 in a mountain bike 
accident. 
</P>
<P>
	Dutko, a member of the Democratic National Committee and a major  
Democratic fund-raiser, fell and struck his head while biking in 
Aspen, Colo., while participating in a weekend of fund-raising 
events for Democrats that Clinton also attended. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have laughed and I have cried, and still I miss him  
terribly,'' Clinton said. He said he first met Dutko 27 years ago 
when they both worked in Texas for George McGovern's unsuccessful 
presidential campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	``Dan insisted on leading the campaign in west Texas, where it  
was hard to find anyone who would mention Senator McGovern's 
name,'' Clinton said. ``All his life he loved big challenges. He 
stayed with me and I turned out to be a bigger one than he 
bargained for.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore remembered Dutko with an excerpt from the Talmud: ``His yes  
meant yes. His no meant no.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I was really honored to have him as my friend,'' Gore said.  
``No matter what the goal, he surpassed it; no matter what the 
task, he achieved it. Dan was just irreplaceable, and I'm going to 
miss everything about him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A leading fund-raiser for Clinton and Gore, Dutko was also  
co-chairman of Leadership 2000, the Democratic National Committee's 
top finance committee. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1980, he founded the Dutko Group that grew to encompass three  
entities. One lobbied for businesses such as oil and gas companies 
and telecommunications groups. Another did public policy public 
relations. A third focused on state governments. 
</P>
<P>
	Dutko's widow, Deborah Jospin, is director of AmeriCorps.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990802.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 15:02:57 </DATE_TIME>
