<HEADLINE> Asian Stock Markets Close Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Most Asian stock markets closed lower Monday on  
the back of another slump on Wall Street. 
</P>
<P>
	The Japanese benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average fell 36.16  
points, or 0.20 percent, to finish at 17,825.70. On Friday, the 
average closed down 8.06 points, or 0.05 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency trading, the U.S. dollar was quoted at 114.04 yen,  
down 1.22 yen from late Friday in Tokyo and below its late New York 
level of 114.48 yen Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders said the dollar's basic weakness remained unchanged amid  
concerns about inflation in the United States. Those fears had also 
driven the Dow Jones industrial average down for a second straight 
session Friday, losing 1.3 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The stronger yen also weighed on sentiment in the stock market.  
A weak dollar makes Japanese exports costlier abroad while reducing 
the yen value of foreign revenue. 
</P>
<P>
	Malaysia's key index plunged 4.4 percent on foreign selling amid  
caution ahead of a spate of corporate earnings releases in the next 
two weeks, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark's Composite Index of 100 blue-chip stocks fell  
33.75 points to 734.94. 
</P>
<P>
	Bucking the trend was the Hong Kong Stock Exchange, where share  
prices rose on expectations that banking giant HSBC Holdings would 
post strong half-year earnings. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hang Seng Index, the Hong Kong market's key indicator of  
blue chips, rose 248.57 points, or 1.9 percent, to close at 
13,435.43. On Friday, the index had gained 69.02 points, or 0.5 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Brokers said market sentiment improved on speculation that HSBC  
Holdings' half-year results could be better than expected. 
</P>
<P>
	The optimists were proven right after the market closed, when  
HSBC Holdings announced that its half-year pretax profits rose 10 
percent to U.S. $4.068 billion, beating most analysts forecasts. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere:  
</P>
<P>
	TAIPEI: Share prices closed lower on worries over continuing  
tensions between China and Taiwan. The market's key Weighted Stock 
Price Index fell 130.81 points, or 1.8 percent, to 7,195.94. 
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: New Zealand share prices closed lower in line with  
weaker global stock markets. The NZSE-40 Capital Index fell 32.49 
points, or 1.5 percent, to 2,163.29. 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Philippine shares closed higher, boosted by speculation  
of a possible merger between two of the country's largest banks. 
The Philippine Stock Exchange Index rose 13.32 points, or 0.6 
percent, to 2,356.13. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: Australian stocks closed lower on selling of financial  
stocks amid market talk that U.S. interest rates will rise later 
this month. The All Ordinaries Index fell 19.9 points, or 0.7 
percent, to 3,000. 
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL: Share prices closed lower as concerns about the Daewoo  
Group's financial trouble continued to weigh down the market. The 
Korea Composite Stock Price Index fell 9.91 points, or 1.0 percent, 
to 959.82. 
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE: Share prices closed lower. The Straits Times Index  
fell 17.12 points, or 0.7 percent, to 2,128.65. 
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA: Share prices closed slightly lower. The Composite Index  
fell 0.2 percent, or 1.361 points, to 596.513. 
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK: Thai share prices closed lower in thin trading. The  
Stock Exchange of Thailand or SET index fell 4.20 points, or 0.92 
percent, to 452.61. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
