<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Close Lower; Dow Down 9.19 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The continuing threat of higher interest rates  
demolished a rally on Wall Street Monday, sending stocks lower even 
after a new report suggested the economy might not be overheating 
after all. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average closed 9.19 lower at 10,645.96  
after rising as much as 136 points earlier in the session. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators also gave up early gains and finished  
lower. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 fell 0.67 to 1,328.05, and the 
Nasdaq composite index fell 14.86 to 2,623.63. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks initially rebounded from last week's steep losses after  
the National Association of Purchasing Management said the U.S. 
manufacturing sector grew in July for the sixth consecutive month 
but not as strongly as most analysts expected. 
</P>
<P>
	The market had anticipated that the report, which gauges  
manufacturing activity, would show continued economic expansion and 
raise the likelihood of the Federal Reserve hiking interest rates 
later this year. The report is the first reading on the U.S. 
economy's performance for July. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's the excuse for some buying today,'' said William  
Meehan, chief market analyst for Cantor Fitzgerald, who said 
investors were also lured by bargains after last week's steep 
market losses, when the Dow fell a total of 255.81 points, or 2.3 
percent, and the Nasdaq lost 53.91 points, or 2 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	But there was little conviction behind Monday's early gains --  
even as the Dow was up more than 100 points, the S&AMP;P and Nasdaq 
managed only modest gains. And by midafternoon, the Dow also began 
slipping, turning lower in the final hour of trading. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would appear that the worries about interest rates were not  
adequately assuaged by the NAPM report,'' said Richard A. Dickson, 
a technical analyst at Scott &AMP; Stringfellow Inc. in Richmond, Va. 
</P>
<P>
	Bond prices followed a similar pattern, rebounding in morning  
trading before trailing off late in the day. The yield on the 
30-year Treasury bond touched 6.17 percent in early trading, sank 
to 6.10 percent and then edged up to 6.12 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The high yields on bonds have been contributing to a difficult  
environment for stocks, presenting an attractive and less volatile 
investment vehicle. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial stocks, battered last week as the threat of higher  
interest rates rattled the market, followed the broader market, 
rising before turning mixed late in the day. Chase Manhattan rose 1 
3/16 to 78 1/4 and American Express, a component of the Dow, fell 1 
11/16 to 130 1/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors seeking bargains boosted Daimler Chrysler 2 5/8 to 74 3/4 on  
the New York Stock Exchange. The automaker's shares slid last week 
after the company reported flat operating earnings. 
</P>
<P>
	Sears rose 1 1/16 to 41 9/16 following reports the company will  
cut 10 percent of the work force at its headquarters. 
</P>
<P>
	On a dismal day for most stocks, bullish analyst Abby Joseph  
Cohen provided a note of optimism. Cohen, chief investment 
strategist at Goldman Sachs &AMP; Co., told clients she does not 
foresee a bear market, and that share prices will continue to move 
higher along with strong corporate profits. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 7-to-5 margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange. Composite volume totaled 783.75 million 
shares, compared with 875.77 million in the previous session. 
</P>
<P>
	Meehan said the low volume suggests that many investors are  
staying out of the market for now and looking ahead to the Aug. 24 
meeting of the Fed's Open Market Committee, which sets interest 
rates. 
</P>
<P>
	``Volume is sluggish and will remain so until Aug. 24 unless we  
get some really negative news,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index fell 0.73 to 625.34, and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index lost 4.59 to 783.64. The Russell 
2000 index of smaller companies fell 2.14 to 442.63. 
</P>
<P>
	Overseas markets were mixed. Japan's Nikkei stock average fell  
0.2 percent, but most European markets thrived on the early Wall 
Street rally. Germany's DAX index rose 0.5 percent, Britain's FT-SE 
100 gained 0.9 percent, and France's CAC-40 closed 0.1 percent 
lower. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
