<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Litton Acquires Avondale Industries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- Litton Industries Inc. on Monday completed  
its acquisition of Avondale Industries Inc., creating a 
shipbuilding business with annual revenue of $1.8 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Litton, based in Woodland Hills, Calif., combined Avondale with  
Ingalls Shipbuilding Inc. in Pascagoula, Miss., to form Litton Ship 
Systems, which will have 17,000 employees. 
</P>
<P>
	Avondale designs, builds and overhauls ships for the Navy, Coast  
Guard and commercial customers. Litton builds military and 
commercial ships. The two companies have competed for some 
contracts. 
</P>
<P>
	``The merger with Avondale significantly broadens Litton's  
market coverage in both military surface combatants and commercial 
ships,'' said Litton chairman Michael R. Brown. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal ended a long period of courting Avondale.  
</P>
<P>
	Newport News Shipbuilding had been the first to bid for  
Avondale, offering $470 million in stock. Litton then offered $529 
million in cash for Avondale, about $39.50 per share. Avondale gave 
Newport News more time to improve its bid, but the Virginia-based 
company declined to raise its offer. 
</P>
<P>
	Litton also pursued Newport News Shipbuilding, but withdrew its  
bid last month in the face of opposition from the Pentagon. A 
Litton-Newport News combination would have reduced the number of 
companies competing to build most classes of Navy warships from 
three to two. 
</P>
<P>
	Avondale officials said they expect no layoffs and believe the  
merger will open the way for more jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	Still unresolved is Avondale's six-year fight with the Metal  
Trade Council of the AFL-CIO, which has been trying to organize 
Avondale's 6,000 workers. Last month, a federal appeals court ruled 
that a 1993 union representation election was invalid. 
</P>
<P>
	Union officials have said they hope Litton will recognize the  
union since Litton already has an organized force of 11,000 
workers. 
</P>
<P>
	Litton Ship Systems will be headed by Gerald St. Pe, who until  
recently was chief at Ingalls. Avondale chairman Albert Bossier 
will continue to be in charge of the New Orleans yard, but will 
report to St. Pe. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
