<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Photographer's View of Nixon's Era </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- In one Watergate image, John Ehrlichman simply  
glares with every inch of clenched and jutting jaw and out-thrust 
lower lip. 
</P>
<P>
	In another, Bob Haldeman, also in the witness chair at the  
Senate Watergate hearings, burns in a sort of dark yet incandescent 
glow. 
</P>
<P>
	They had been Richard Nixon's gatekeepers, the controllers of  
the president's political environment -- Haldeman as White House 
chief of staff, Ehrlichman his other top aide. 
</P>
<P>
	Fred Maroon's photographs reflect the situation of all three in  
the summer of 1973: under siege but fiercely defiant. 
</P>
<P>
	In an earlier shot, taken in far more controlled circumstances,  
Nixon steps between two White House columns and begins to 
disappear. The photograph leaves just a trailing right leg, 
polished black shoe and right arm in view. 
</P>
<P>
	Maroon looked up from his camera lens and asked about Nixon's  
retreat. 
</P>
<P>
	``He deliberately avoids us,'' an aide replied, giving the  
photographer his caption. 
</P>
<P>
	A quarter-century ago this month -- Aug. 8, 1974 -- Nixon  
submitted a one-sentence letter of resignation to Secretary of 
State Henry Kissinger and ended the 37th American presidency. 
</P>
<P>
	Now the Smithsonian Institution's National Museum of American  
History is displaying an exhibit with 145 of Maroon's 
black-and-white images from the Nixon era -- many of them never 
published nor widely viewed, all stashed in a vault for the last 
two decades. 
</P>
<P>
	A large-format book, ``The Nixon Years,'' with photographs by  
Maroon and text by Tom Wicker, a retired New York Times Washington 
bureau chief, will be published by Abbeville Press in September. 
</P>
<P>
	``For 25 years I waited for the passions to cool in this  
American tragedy, but I ultimately realized I would not live long 
enough to see that happen,'' said Maroon, a freelance photographer 
who has recorded the people and monuments of official Washington 
for nearly 50 years. 
</P>
<P>
	For Maroon, the story began early in the Nixon administration,  
when he was given the opportunity to photograph the presidential 
workday, first at the White House and then at the Committee to 
Re-elect the President. 
</P>
<P>
	He continued to work on his own after the Watergate scandal  
broke, covering the Senate Watergate hearings, the House 
impeachment hearings and finally, Nixon's resignation. 
</P>
<P>
	``I simply had a sense I was witnessing a pivotal moment in  
American history, and that I should stay with it until the 
conclusion,'' Maroon said. 
</P>
<P>
	In all, he shot 576 rolls of film.  
</P>
<P>
	When he began in 1970, Maroon witnessed ``a staff in control of  
everything that happened.'' In the week before Nixon resigned, 
control had been replaced by ``uncertainty and apprehension.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Maroon visited Nixon's re-election committee just days after the  
arrest inside Democratic National Committee headquarters of a team 
of burglars with ties to committee officials. 
</P>
<P>
	``You guys will do anything to get a little publicity,'' Maroon  
cracked to Jeb Stuart Magruder, the deputy campaign director. 
</P>
<P>
	``It never occurred to me at the time that they had anything to  
do with it,'' Maroon said. 
</P>
<P>
	But the photographer gradually began to become aware of the  
committee's tight security, its general air of ``paranoia.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I started taking notice of things differently,'' Maroon wrote.  
``Surveillance cameras and rooms with a lot of electronic devices 
took on a new meaning. I thought I should photograph them and the 
shredding machine ....'' 
</P>
<P>
	When the Senate Watergate hearings opened, many of the people  
Maroon had met earlier at the White House and the re-election 
committee were summoned to testify and the photographer saw ``the 
anguish of the situation etched on their faces.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Maroon said John Mitchell, Nixon's former campaign chairman,  
spotted him in the Senate Caucus Room and asked what he was doing. 
</P>
<P>
	``I told him I was continuing my photographic record of the  
Nixon era and asked whether he did not agree that what was 
happening was of some moment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope it's a fleeting moment,'' Mitchell replied.  
</P>
<P>
	Finally, it was August 1974. The Republican leaders of Congress  
had told Nixon he didn't have the votes to stave off impeachment. 
Maroon photographed the growing crowds at the White House fence; 
the prayer vigil for the president at the Northwest gate; the man 
with the hand-lettered sign reading, ``Don't resign.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Nixon did resign, and in a long, rambling speech said  
goodbye to the White House staff. 
</P>
<P>
	``The speech went on for quite a long time,'' Maroon wrote. ``It  
became heart-wrenching. You were glad for him when he finished 
because you felt such grief for the country and for what was going 
on inside of him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE: Lawrence L. Knutson, has reported on Congress,  
the White House and Washington's history for more than 30 years. He 
covered the Senate Watergate hearings. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990802.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 14:00:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> O's Johnson Not Slowed by Diabetes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- Most pitchers put on a warmup jacket and sit in  
the dugout between innings. Jason Johnson of the Baltimore Orioles 
slips into a back room and pricks one of his fingers with a lancet. 
</P>
<P>
	He then places the blood sample on a strip and slides it into a  
pocket-sized machine that tells him how much sugar is in his blood. 
If the level is too low, he sips a sports drink before returning to 
the mound. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson, a right-hander, has Type 1 diabetes. That means his  
pancreas can't make insulin, a protein that helps control the 
body's conversion of sugar into energy. Without careful monitoring, 
diabetes can lead to heart and kidney problems and blindness. 
</P>
<P>
	But because Johnson carefully controls the disease, he insists  
it doesn't make him a novelty in the Baltimore clubhouse or hinder 
his performance. 
</P>
<P>
	``They know about it and I know about it. I'm just like anybody  
else,'' Johnson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson, 25, was obtained in a March 29 trade with the Tampa Bay  
Devil Rays. He started the season in the minors, but was called up 
in May and has since become a fixture in the starting rotation. 
</P>
<P>
	About 1.2 million people in the United States have Type 1  
diabetes, according to Centers for Disease Control and Prevention 
figures. Few of those people are major league baseball players, but 
Johnson is not alone in managing the disease as a professional 
athlete. 
</P>
<P>
	New York Knicks center Chris Dudley has diabetes, as does Jay  
Leeuwenberg of the Indianapolis Colts, who appears on a promotional 
poster for the International Diabetic Athletes Association. The 
3,500-member group includes marathon runners, mountain climbers and 
cyclists training for the Olympics, according to director Linda 
McClure. 
</P>
<P>
	Like other athletes with diabetes, Johnson follows a strict  
regimen to keep his blood sugar steady. In addition to checking his 
blood sugar level between every inning when he is pitching, he must 
inject himself with insulin three times a day. 
</P>
<P>
	When traveling for games in different time zones, Johnson  
adjusts his injection schedule. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson learned he had diabetes at age 11, and in the years  
after several coaches and teachers unfamiliar with the disease were 
uncertain about his chances of excelling in sports. 
</P>
<P>
	``My way of showing them, 'Listen, I'm not different from  
anybody else,' was by performing and doing what any other kid could 
do,'' Johnson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Now he wants to help doctors convince young children with  
diabetes that they can succeed in professional baseball. 
</P>
<P>
	``Jason wants to prove to everybody that you can live normally  
with what he has to live with,'' Orioles manager Ray Miller said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990802.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 00:00:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Politicians Fight Back With Laws </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MONTCALM TOWNSHIP, Mich. (AP) -- Hardy and sociable, township  
Supervisor Bob Lewis is a straight talker who prides himself on 
running township meetings efficiently. 
</P>
<P>
	And with long days of tending to his hay field and business, the  
former fire chief likes to relax with a drink. 
</P>
<P>
	``Do I like a beer? Sure. I love hot dogs and beer. Popcorn and  
beer is great. But last time I checked, temperate drinking was not 
a crime,'' Lewis says. 
</P>
<P>
	It's not a crime, but Lewis' fondness for alcohol and his  
outspoken style have become a public issue. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, residents of this farming community 150 miles  
northwest of Detroit will vote in a special recall election, with 
the top complaints being that Lewis ``conducted regular township 
meetings while visibly under the influence of alcohol'' and 
denounced township officials at meetings. 
</P>
<P>
	It's one of dozens of recall elections that will take place  
around the state this year -- and state Rep. Charles LaSata says 
that's too many. While backers of the recalls say they have good 
reasons, LaSata says there is a culture of ``recall rage'' and is 
sponsoring legislation to limit them. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need to root out the bad apples, but not at the expense of  
driving good people out of elected office,'' he says. ``That's what 
is happening today.'' 
</P>
<P>
	LaSata, a Republican from St. Joseph, points to his home county  
as an example. From December 1996 to March 1999, 50 recall 
petitions were filed for approval in Berrien County, according to 
the clerk's records. That compares with 101 petitions filed during 
the last 16 years. 
</P>
<P>
	LaSata says elected officials shouldn't have to worry about  
whether they will face recall over a controversial decision or 
personality conflict. If they have that constant fear, ``everybody 
will run toward the middle,'' he says. 
</P>
<P>
	His bill would allow recalls only if the official had done  
something illegal or improper or did not fulfill the duties of the 
office. 
</P>
<P>
	The plan also would call for significant judicial oversight of  
the recall process: The county election commissions would determine 
if there was sufficient reason for the recall, and the decision 
would be subject to review by a circuit court judge. 
</P>
<P>
	The recall option is not available for members of Congress. The  
U.S. Constitution allows removal only through resignation or 
expulsion by the U.S. House or Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	Michigan is one of 20 states that have recall provisions for  
state or local officials, while the rest use an impeachment process 
for removal. Restrictions such as those in LaSata's bill are law in 
Alaska, Florida, Kansas, Montana, Washington and Georgia. 
</P>
<P>
	``The ballot in Georgia is heavily weighted to when you elect  
somebody, you keep them in office, unless there is some egregious 
violation,'' says Chris Riggall, spokesman for the Georgia 
Secretary of State. 
</P>
<P>
	Under current Michigan law, recalls can be held for just about  
any reason, as long as the petitioner gets enough signatures to 
place it on the ballot and the petition language is deemed clear 
enough for voters to understand. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of those who have pushed for recalls say that gathering  
signatures, getting the language approved and encouraging people to 
vote against their leaders requires an organized and motivated 
campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Mike Wiecek is a Warren City Council member who was involved in  
an 1989 effort to recall the mayor and six council members for 
presiding over a tax increase. 
</P>
<P>
	He says the mayor had political allies among the elections  
commissioners. It took 10 tries over 10 months to get the language 
approved and by that time, he says, many of the people behind the 
effort had become discouraged and never collected the signatures 
needed to put the issue to a vote. 
</P>
<P>
	``The ability to frustrate the citizens' right to recall is just  
unbelievable,'' Wiecek says. ``It's a powerful tool that the 
incumbents have.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But some officials who have faced a recall say they also have to  
spend significant effort to keep their job. Genesee Township 
Supervisor Fred Muhl beat a recall last November after spending 
more than $2,000 on legal bills to fight the petition language. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Michigan's House Republican leadership appears to agree  
with the intent of LaSata's legislation, its future is unclear 
because of concerns about whether it violates the state 
constitution. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Montcalm Township residents are gearing up for Lewis'  
recall question. Neither side is willing to predict how it will 
turn out, saying it is going to be close. 
</P>
<P>
	Although nobody disputes that Lewis likes to drink -- including  
Lewis himself -- he denies that he is ``visibly under the 
influence'' at board meetings and claims the recall is a 
politically motivated attack. 
</P>
<P>
	Township Treasurer Diane Fountain supports Lewis but prefers not  
to speak out ``because I could be next on the list.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I do think in the future it will deter people from running,''  
she says. ``You don't want such negative things said about you all 
over the newspapers in front of your family.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
