<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ethnic Albanians Return to Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Postal workers and university  
professors returned to their jobs in Kosovo's capital today, nine 
years after they were drummed out by a Serb purge of ethnic 
Albanian workers. 
</P>
<P>
	Bernard Kouchner, who heads the U.N. mission in Kosovo,  
accompanied hundreds of ethnic Albanian postal and 
telecommunications workers back to their jobs at the main 
headquarters building in downtown Pristina. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is an important day in the rebuilding of Kosovo,''  
Kouchner told the workers. ``It is a very important day because the 
workers are going back to their work.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The move is part of U.N. efforts to return to ethnic Albanians,  
who form the vast majority in the Serbian province, much of the 
power they lost in 1989-1990 when Belgrade revoked Kosovo's 
autonomy. 
</P>
<P>
	At the time, some 600 ethnic Albanian postal workers lost their  
jobs. Today they took up their old jobs alongside the Serbs who 
remained in their positions. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ever since September 1990, I dreamed about this day, because  
when I was expelled I never thought I would be back here again,'' 
said 50-year-old Emine Rexhepi. ``But hey, dreams do come true.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kouchner promised money and equipment to help rebuild the  
damaged and outdated telecommunications network in the province. 
The United Nations estimates improvements to the system will cost 
$1.5 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Ethnic Albanian professors and students also returned today to  
Pristina's main university campus, which they were forced to leave 
in 1989. 
</P>
<P>
	Rebel leader Hashim Thaci joined a ceremony marking the return  
of around 5,000 students, who will spend the month making up missed 
classes and exams to be ready for the official start of classes in 
September. All classes will be held in Albanian. 
</P>
<P>
	``A ghost once said that we will never step onto this university  
again,'' university rector Zenel Kelmendi said at the ceremony, 
referring to the Serbs who drove them out. ``But we are here now 
and we are here to stay.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The employee returns were a step forward after a weekend plagued  
by more violence between ethnic Albanians and Kosovo's minority 
Serbs. A Serb Orthodox church was bombed Sunday in Pristina, 
causing no casualties. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, a British team detonated a hand grenade and a suspicious  
package found in the yard of a Serb house in Pristina. The blasts 
caused no damage or injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Sunday, a U.S. soldier -- identified as Pfc. Benjamin A.  
McGill, 20 -- was electrocuted while on patrol in the eastern sector 
of Kosovo, when the antenna on his M2 Bradley Fighting Vehicle 
struck a powerline, a statement from the U.S. military said. 
</P>
<P>
	The statement, out of the U.S. press office in Urosevac, Kosovo,  
did not specify McGill's hometown, but said his father and mother 
live in Florida. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
