Nasdaq Composite Index        2,623.63  - 14.86
Gold(final) -    $256.20    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Mon.
Silver(final) -   $5.400  troy oz., NY Comex spot month Mon.

</P>
<P>
	Manufacturing Sector Grows in July  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The nation's manufacturers reported a slowing of  
growth in July with only modest increases in prices of raw 
materials. A survey released today by the National Association of 
Purchasing Management indicated that the U.S. manufacturing sector 
grew in July for the sixth straight month, but less than in the 
previous month and below analysts' predictions. Price increases 
also were below expectations. The figures suggest that a 
second-quarter slowing of the overall economy's growth is 
continuing into the third quarter. ``The report put a damper on any 
plan by the Fed to immediately raise interest rates,'' said 
economist Sung Won Sohn at Wells Fargo. Meanwhile, the Commerce 
Department reported construction spending rebounded slightly in 
June, rising 0.5 percent, after falling for two straight months. 

</P>
<P>
	Airlines Cut Fares for Fall  
</P>
<P>
	FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) -- Travelers are seeing the first full air  
fare sale of the fall. Northwest Airlines, the nation's 
fourth-largest, kicked off the fare sale during the weekend, with 
its computer system posting some off-peak prices discounted by as 
much as 25 percent. United Airlines, the nation's largest carrier, 
and No. 2 American Airlines were among those matching the sale, 
which includes most of the continental U.S., Hawaii, and Canada. 
Other airlines matching included U.S. Airways, America West, 
Continental, Trans World Airlines and Delta Air Lines. 

</P>
<P>
	Warner Bros. Exec Meyer Named CEO  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Longtime Warner Bros. executive Barry Meyer  
was named chairman and chief executive officer of the studio today, 
while Castle Rock Entertainment chairman Alan Horn was appointed 
president and chief operating officer. Meyer will take over from 
departing chiefs Terry Semel and Bob Daly, who had worked together 
running studio operations since 1980. Semel and Daly announced 
their resignations last month. Meyer will head film and television 
operations but will not inherit Semel and Daly's duties overseeing 
Warner Music Group. A new leader at the music division will be 
named soon. Shares of Time Warner were at 70 1/8, down 1 7/8. 

</P>
<P>
	Sun Microsystems Designs Java Chip  
</P>
<P>
	PALO ALTO, Calif. (AP) -- Sun Microsystems is designing a new  
computer chip geared toward its Java programming language, setting 
up a possible faceoff with Intel. The new MAJC -- pronounced 
``magic'' -- semiconductor is ``intended for the rapidly emerging 
market of applications that blend communications, exciting visual 
images, sound and compute functionality,'' according to a draft 
press release from Sun. The new chips are expected to compete with 
the market-dominating Pentiums and other microprocessors made by 
Intel. Sun plans to present an overview of the MAJC architecture at 
a technical conference in mid-August and unveil the chip in 
October. Shares of Sun were at 69 7/16, up 1 9/16. 

</P>
<P>
	Most Financial Firms Set for Y2k  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal regulators said today that 99 percent  
of the nation's banks, thrifts and credit unions have completed 
testing for the Year 2000 bug in their computer systems. They added 
without giving specific numbers that most financial institutionsare 
already using computer systems that are Year 2000 compliant every 
day without problems. Among the nation's 10,335 banks and thrifts, 
10,246 received the highest possible rating for readiness, 78 were 
told they needed to improve and 11 drew unsatisfactory ratings, 
according to the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. A similar 
breakdown among the 10,807 credit unions included in the overall 
assessment wasn't immediately available. 

</P>
<P>
	Celebrex Beats Viagra in Sales  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- It didn't create a national sensation like  
Viagra, but the new arthritis pill Celebrex has surpassed the 
impotence medicine as the nation's fastest-selling new drug ever. 
Celebrex promises pain relief with fewer stomach problems than 
other drugs. Unlike Viagra, patients take it every day and it's 
usually covered by insurance. Celebrex, which was introduced in 
January, sold 6.86 million prescriptions during its first six 
months on the market, compared with 6.05 million for Viagra during 
its first six months, according to IMS Health, a research company. 

</P>
<P>
	CBS Earnings Rise Sharply  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- CBS Corp. credited strong growth in its  
television and radio businesses for a large jump in second-quarter 
earnings. CBS reported today it earned $95 million, or 13 cents a 
share, compared with $4 million, or 1 cent a share, in the same 
period a year ago. The earnings matched Wall Street expectations. 
CBS president Mel Karmazin singled out a strong showing at the 
company's TV network business as an engine behind the profit surge. 
CBS was the top-rated network last season, taking the No. 1 spot 
for the first time in five years. Shares of CBS were at 44 7/8, up 
15/16. 

</P>
<P>
	AutoNation Separating Rental Units  
</P>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- AutoNation Inc. plans to separate its lackluster  
rental-car business, including the big Alamo and National chains, 
from its growing auto sales operations in what could lead to its 
eventual spinoff or sale. Separating the rental unit will allow 
investors ``to better recognize and evaluate the strengths and 
growth prospects of our automotive retail operations,'' Chairman H. 
Wayne Huizenga said in the company's second-quarter earnings report 
today. The company said its board was still looking at options for 
how the separation will take place. 

</P>
<P>
	Cooper Industries Buys 2 Companies  
</P>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- Tool and electrical product maker Cooper  
Industries today announced the acquisition of two electrical 
products companies, JSB Electrical of England and Corelite of 
Denver. No financial terms were disclosed. JSB is a maker of 
emergency lighting, fire detection and security systems. Corelite 
is a privately-held manufacturer of indirect lighting fixtures. 
Last year, the companies had combined revenues of more than $50 
million. 

</P>
<P>
	British Beef Export Gets OK  
</P>
<P>
	PROBUS, England (AP) -- A government minister today slapped an  
official approval stamp on the first British beef carcass destined 
for foreign consumers since exports were banned three years ago. 
Yesterday, European regulators lifted the ban imposed after an 
outbreak of mad cow disease. The carcass was brought into a 
slaughterhouse in Probus, Cornwall. And the meat will be sent to 
France in mid-August as centerpiece of a marketing drive to 
persuade the French to buy British beef again. 

</P>
