<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea Floods Create Shortages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DONGDUCHON, South Korea (AP) -- Shortages of food, water and  
blankets slowed efforts Monday to help thousands of people left 
homeless by deadly flooding in South Korea. Victims accused the 
government of being poorly prepared for the disaster. 
</P>
<P>
	Three days of torrential rains have left at least 20 dead and 24  
missing. Another powerful storm approached the Korean peninsula 
from the South Pacific, raising fears of more flooding. 
</P>
<P>
	Many residents whose homes were flooded complained that the  
government had failed to raise embankments and take other 
preventive measures after similar flooding in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	``The same thing happened last year and our entire house was  
under water for days. I don't understand why the authorities didn't 
do anything,'' said Kim Jum-ae, a 57-year-old housewife. 
</P>
<P>
	She had taken shelter with two dozen other people in the  
basement of a Roman Catholic church in Dongduchon, 26 miles north 
of the South Korean capital of Seoul. 
</P>
<P>
	They were among more than 19,000 people who fled their homes in  
an area between Seoul and the border with North Korea, 35 miles 
from the capital. 
</P>
<P>
	Monsoon rains also wracked other Asian countries, causing deadly  
floods and landslides. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Philippines, two days of rain left at least 16 people  
dead, including a family of seven whose house was hit by landslide. 
Ten others were missing. In Vietnam, 16 people were dead and 11 
missing after flash floods. And four people died and in flooding in 
eastern Thailand. 
</P>
<P>
	In South Korea, aid workers were frustrated by limited  
resources. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are short of everything here. Volunteers, foods, blankets,  
especially clean water,'' said Chung Moon-suk of South Korea's Red 
Cross. The water supply for Dongduchon had been cut off since 
Sunday, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	In Yonchon, another hard-hit town, a section of a reservoir  
collapsed and unleashed cascades of water. The same section caved 
in last year and some villagers complained of a sloppy repair job. 
</P>
<P>
	In a statement, President Kim Dae-jung said government measures  
since last year had prevented damage on a much greater scale, but 
he acknowledged shortcomings. 
</P>
<P>
	``We still have problems to solve,'' he said. ``The same  
disaster erupted in some towns that took precious lives. That calls 
for our grave reflection.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Opposition leaders wanted more.  
</P>
<P>
	``The government should apologize to the people of Korea for not  
having set up any lasting plan to prevent such disasters,'' said 
Ahn Taek-soo, a spokesman for the Grand National Party, the main 
opposition party. 
</P>
<P>
	Several bridges and many roads were blocked and police ordered  
drivers to make detours. Heavy machinery cleared roads littered 
with rocks that had slid off hills. 
</P>
<P>
	The government said 20 people were killed and 24 missing. Those  
missing included 10 vacationers from Seoul who were buried in a 
landslide in Hwachon near the North Korean border early Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Up to 23 inches of rain fell in some locations, and more than  
47,000 acres of rice paddies were washed out. Nearly 7,000 houses 
in dozens of towns and villages were swamped. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, three weeks of rain that began in August killed at  
least 271 South Koreans. 
</P>
<P>
	North Korea also reported heavy damage to crops from storms that  
unleashed up to 16 inches of rain over the weekend. Buildings and 
roads were submerged and some railway and telephone lines were cut, 
North Korean radio reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Huge floods hit the reclusive communist country in 1995, forcing  
it to plead for outside food aid. Flooding and drought that ensued 
caused famine in the North, killing 220,000 people, by the 
Pyongyang government's own figures. U.S. congressional officials 
said more than 2 million North Koreans may have died. 
</P>
<P>
	The South's official Yonhap news agency said 25,000 soldiers  
near the border with North Korea were ordered to higher ground. 
U.S. soldiers built walls of sandbags to protect their bases. About 
37,000 American troops are stationed in South Korea. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
