<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Daewoo To Submit New Debt Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- Under pressure from creditor banks,  
South Korea's troubled Daewoo group will submit new plans this week 
on how to pay off billions of dollars in debt, bank and Daewoo 
officials said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Korea First Bank, the principal domestic creditor of Daewoo,  
said the group is required to submit a revised restructuring plan 
by Thursday on how to speed up its repayment of bank loans. 
</P>
<P>
	Based on Daewoo's revised plan, creditors will announce a final  
restructuring scenario for the conglomerate by Aug. 11, bank 
officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Daewoo's restructuring plan announced last month lacks  
credibility, so the group is being asked to submit new plans that 
can accelerate the breakup of its bloated operations,'' Korea First 
Bank spokesman Min Young-shik said. 
</P>
<P>
	Daewoo, South Korea's second-largest conglomerate, narrowly  
escaped becoming South Korea's largest-ever bankruptcy when 
creditors agreed last week to delay repayment of $8.3 billion in 
short-term debt for six months and extend $3.3 billion in new 
loans. 
</P>
<P>
	In return, Daewoo put up $8.42 billion of stock and real estate  
as collateral. 
</P>
<P>
	But doubts persisted over Daewoo's commitment -- or its ability --  
to sell off dozens of affiliates within six months. 
</P>
<P>
	The government then ordered creditor banks to intervene to  
accelerate the conglomerate's restructuring and breakup. Most of 
the banks are controlled either directly or indirectly by the 
government. 
</P>
<P>
	The government is suggesting that the creditor banks sell  
Daewoo's collateral and turn their loans into equity so that they 
can lower the group's debt and make its subsidiaries more 
attractive to buyers. 
</P>
<P>
	It wants Daewoo to concentrate on its two main businesses -- the  
flagship trading arm Daewoo Corp. and Daewoo Motors, the nation's 
second-largest carmaker. 
</P>
<P>
	Daewoo said it has $49 billion in debts, of which $9.94 billion  
is owed to foreign creditors. 
</P>
<P>
	Daewoo officials said they were considering whether to ask  
foreign creditors to continue to roll over maturing loans. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
