<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Feds Boast of Exposing Tax Cheats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- Federal officials boasted Monday that they  
have finally breached Cayman Islands bank secrecy with the aid of a 
former bank owner who provided records that exposed hundreds of 
U.S. citizens as tax cheats. 
</P>
<P>
	The one-time banker, John M. Mathewson, 71, was sentenced Monday  
in federal court here on conspiracy and money laundering charges. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. authorities claim the case demonstrates that the  
approximately 500 banks in the tiny British colony exist only to 
serve as illegal tax shelters for a mainly American clientele. 
</P>
<P>
	As a result of Mathewson's help, the U.S. government has  
recouped $50 million in back taxes and penalties, and can expect to 
get a total of $300 million, said his lawyer. Authorities could not 
confirm those figures. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Cayman Islands are no longer the safe haven they once  
were,'' said a ranking FBI agent, Robert J. Jordan. ``This case 
enabled us to get on the inside.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The FBI, working with the Internal Revenue Service, is pursuing  
1,500 potential cases around the nation, Jordan said. 
</P>
<P>
	The bank had about 2,000 depositors, and Mathewson dealt  
personally with each and prepared fake documents for shell 
corporations, invoices and other items to help conceal the true 
account holder and the extent of their business, said Paul L. 
Machalek, chief criminal investigator for the IRS in New Jersey. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities stumbled on the case by accident while pursuing a  
nationwide investigation into a cable piracy operation, according 
to court papers. 
</P>
<P>
	When FBI agents arrested Mathewson in 1996, they found over a  
year's worth of computer records from the now-defunct Guardian Bank 
&AMP; Trust Limited of Grand Cayman, the papers show. 
</P>
<P>
	Mathewson immediately offered the records, leading to a  
continuing investigation that has so far brought cases in about 20 
states, Assistant U.S. Attorney John J. Carney said in court 
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Carney urged U.S. District Judge Alfred J. Lechner to give  
Mathewson a lenient sentence to acknowledge his cooperation, which 
included testifying to grand juries and obtaining computer software 
to decode the bank's computer tapes, which were encrypted. 
</P>
<P>
	Saying his cooperation ``has been unparalleled,'' Lechner  
sentenced Mathewson to five years' probation, with six months to be 
served under house arrest, a $30,000 fine and 500 hours of 
community service. He could have faced nearly five years in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	Mathewson pleaded guilty in March 1997 to federal charges  
including conspiracy, money laundering and aiding income tax 
evasions as part of plea bargains with federal prosecutors in 
Florida, New Jersey and New York. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990802.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 13:50:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> APME Names 15 Awards Finalists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Fifteen newspapers have been named finalists in  
the Associated Press Managing Editors association's 29th annual 
Public Service Awards competition. 
</P>
<P>
	Ten finalists were chosen from newspapers of 50,000 or more  
circulation, and five were selected from newspapers under 50,000 
circulation. 
</P>
<P>
	One winner in each category will be announced during APME's  
national conference Oct. 13-16 in Memphis, Tenn. 
</P>
<P>
	``The 78 entries demonstrated that small and large newspapers  
are vigorously performing the work of educator and watchdog,'' 
Robert G. McGruder, former APME president and chairman of the 
judging committee, said Monday. ``These newspapers showed a 
willingness to explore and expose tough issues in their hometowns 
and across the country.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Finalists in the 50,000 and over circulation category are:  
</P>
<P>
	--Detroit Free Press, for ``Grading the Groceries,'' a four-month  
investigation of food handling in Michigan's 2,000 grocery stores 
that found wide disparities in sanitation practices. 
</P>
<P>
	--Sun-Sentinel, Fort Lauderdale, Fla., for ``Cosmetic Surgery:  
The Hidden Dangers,'' a comprehensive effort to assess the safety 
of cosmetic surgery in the state and the adequacy of laws designed 
to protect the public from ill-trained or incompetent physicians. 
</P>
<P>
	--The Hartford (Conn.) Courant, for a five-month investigation  
that uncovered preventable deaths of mentally ill people across the 
country and led to federal regulations designed to protect mental 
patients from abusive restraints. 
</P>
<P>
	--Los Angeles Times, for reports that documented the woeful  
performance of the Los Angeles district attorney's bureau of child 
support. 
</P>
<P>
	--The Star-Ledger, Newark, N.J., for an in-depth examination of  
the New Jersey State Police and racial profiling. 
</P>
<P>
	--Pittsburgh Post-Gazette, for documentation of incidents of  
discovery violations by federal prosecutors; coercion of witnesses 
and suspects by federal agents and prosecutors; a growing reliance 
on convicted criminals and known liars for key testimony; and 
numerous examples of desperate measures taken by federal 
prosecutors to justify the cost of elaborate sting operations. 
</P>
<P>
	--Saint Paul (Minn.) Pioneer Press, for its stories about  
academic fraud at the University of Minnesota that cost the jobs of 
a popular basketball coach and the team's academic counselor. 
</P>
<P>
	--The Salt Lake Tribune, Salt Lake City, for a 12-month series of  
stories that overcame a barrier of secrecy, intimidation and a 
collective out-of-sight, out-of-mind attitude by local law 
enforcement authorities to penetrate several polygamous clans in 
Utah. 
</P>
<P>
	--San Francisco Examiner, for revealing the existence of an  
infection outbreak, its extent and its apparent cause in an 
investigation of a subsidiary of Johnson &AMP; Johnson Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	--Waterbury (Conn.) Republican American, for uncovering an  
insular hiring system in the city's schools that allowed City Hall 
to dole out dozens of teaching jobs to a network of relatives, 
friends and campaign contributors. 
</P>
<P>
	Finalists in the under-50,000 circulation category are:  
</P>
<P>
	--The Courier-News, Bridgewater, N.J., for a two-month  
investigation that exposed an apparent conflict of interest between 
two key planning officials and a developer. 
</P>
<P>
	--Southeast Missourian, Cape Girardeau, Mo., for ``Life or  
Meth,'' a six-week project that opened the eyes of staff members, 
the region and state and federal lawmakers to the dangers and 
extensive reach of the drug methamphetamine. 
</P>
<P>
	--The Recorder, Greenfield, Mass., for an in-depth look at rural  
poverty and near-poverty in the poorest and most rural county in 
the state. 
</P>
<P>
	--Hattiesburg (Miss.) American, for six months of research and  
reporting that led to strengthening a state law that had been 
unenforced and had led to the deaths of three law enforcement 
officers in two years. 
</P>
<P>
	--The Wenatchee (Wash.) World, for an investigation that found  
that although the percentage of minorities had increased 
dramatically in the area over 15 years, employment of minorities in 
local government had been minimal, even while affirmative action 
programs were in place. 
</P>
<P>
	Judges were McGruder, executive editor of the Detroit Free  
Press; William E. Ahearn, vice president and executive editor of 
The Associated Press; Pam Johnson, president of APME and vice 
president news and executive editor, The Arizona Republic, Phoenix; 
and former APME presidents Reid MacCluggage, editor and publisher, 
The Day, New London, Conn., and David Hawpe, vice president and 
editorial director of the Courier-Journal of Louisville, Ky. 
</P>
<P>
	Judges did not participate in discussion or votes concerning  
their own newspapers. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
