<DOCNO> APW19990802.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 16:20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bond Prices Slip / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Treasury prices slipped on Monday, as pessimism  
among bond investors overshadowed a fresh suggestion that inflation 
pressures remained in check last month. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond dropped 1/4  
point, or $2.50 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, a key 
influence on borrowing costs, rose to 6.12 percent from late 
Friday's 6.10 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The nation's manufacturers reported a slowing of growth in July,  
with only modest increases in prices of raw materials. The survey 
by the National Association of Purchasing Management indicated that 
the U.S. manufacturing sector grew but not as strongly as in the 
previous month and below analysts' predictions. Price increases 
also were below expectations. 
</P>
<P>
	The figures helped bond prices rebound somewhat off early lows.  
But prices stayed depressed as the day wore on, hurt by continued 
concern by investors that interest rates will rise, hurting the 
value of their existing fixed-rate securities. 
</P>
<P>
	Many investors are convinced that the Federal Reserve will push  
its key lending rates higher again to keep inflation in check, 
particularly after the Labor Department reported Friday that 
employment costs rose 1.1 percent from April through June. That was 
the biggest quarterly change since the second-quarter of 1991, when 
wages and benefits increased 1.2 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In the broader market, prices of short-term Treasury securities  
fell by 1/32 point, while intermediate-term Treasurys fell by 1/32 
point to 3/32 point, reported Bridge Telerate, a financial 
information service. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields on newly auctioned three-month Treasury bills rose to  
4.83 percent while the discount rate rose to 4.70 percent. Yield on 
newly auctioned six-month yields rose to 4.97 percent and the 
discount increased to 4.78 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	One-year yields rose to 5.13 percent as the discount increased  
to 4.87 percent, up 0.03 percentage point. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, rose to 5.19 percent from Friday's 5.13 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds fell 9/32 point to 117 15/32. The average 
yield to maturity was unchanged from 5.59 percent Friday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
