<DOCNO> APW19990802.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 16:10:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Driver in New Orleans Bus Crash Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- The driver of the charter bus that crashed on  
Mother's Day, killing 22 people on their way to a Mississippi 
casino, died of heart failure over the weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	The death of Frank Bedell, who had a history of heart disease  
and kidney problems, means no criminal charges will be filed in the 
case. 
</P>
<P>
	Because Bedell was never interviewed by investigators,  
authorities may never know whether his health problems or history 
of illegal drug use contributed to the crash. 
</P>
<P>
	Bedell, 46, collapsed Sunday at his home in Algiers. He was  
taken by ambulance to the hospital where he was pronounced dead. 
</P>
<P>
	Bedell never spoke to investigators about the crash but told his  
lawyer he was trying to avoid a car that cut in front of him when 
he lost control of the bus. 
</P>
<P>
	Bedell had a heart condition that should have prevented him from  
keeping his commercial driver's license, officials said. About 12 
hours before the crash, Bedell received treatment in a hospital 
emergency room for dehydration and extremely low blood pressure 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities said Bedell had congestive heart disease, had lost  
two bus-driving jobs because he used marijuana, had failed a test 
for cocaine and was undergoing dialysis. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, tests found traces of marijuana in Bedell's blood  
after the crash. 
</P>
<P>
	Information about Bedell's medical history never made it to  
federal and state authorities who could have prevented him from 
driving. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990802.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 21:30:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Warner Bros. Exec Meyer Named CEO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Time Warner's choice of one of the company's  
top insiders, Barry Meyer, to head its studio operations will 
provide a stable successor after the departure of one of 
Hollywood's best management teams, analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	Meyer was named Monday as chairman and chief executive officer  
of Warner Bros., replacing the duo of Terry Semel and Bob Daly. Now 
executive vice president and chief operating officer, Meyer has 
been at Warner since 1971. 
</P>
<P>
	Time Warner named Alan Horn, chairman and CEO of its Castle Rock  
division, as president and chief operating officer for Warner Bros. 
</P>
<P>
	Choosing in-house successors made sense to maintain continuity,  
said Jessica Reif Cohen, a Time Warner analyst for Merrill Lynch. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not surprising. They had a very deep bench,'' Reif Cohen  
said. ``Barry Meyer is a phenomenal executive, one of the best in 
the industry. He's been there almost 30 years. He applies 
stability.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meyer and Horn will take over Oct. 4, after Semel and Daly  
leave. Semel and Daly, who have worked together since 1980 running 
Warner's studio operations, announced their resignations last 
month. 
</P>
<P>
	Meyer will not inherit Semel and Daly's duties overseeing Warner  
Music Group, which they took on in 1995. A new leader for music 
operations will be named soon, said Gerald Levin, chairman and 
chief executive officer of Time Warner. 
</P>
<P>
	Splitting the businesses was a good move, said David Davis, an  
entertainment industry analyst with investment banker Houlihan 
Lokey Howard &AMP; Zukin. Semel and Daly had been stretched thin when 
the music division was added, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The music division was the one area that lagged under Semel and  
Daly, Davis said. Overall, Warner has been one of Hollywood's most 
successful studios, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of it has to do with the stability in management. Not  
just Semel and Daly. It's tentacles throughout the company,'' Davis 
said. ``It makes sense logically to promote from within.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meyer, 56, has been executive vice president since 1984 and  
chief operating officer of the Burbank-based studio since 1994. He 
came to work for Warner television in 1971. 
</P>
<P>
	Horn co-founded Castle Rock in 1987. The production company's  
films include ``When Harry Met Sally,'' ``City Slickers'' and ``A 
Few Good Men.'' 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990802.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 14:50:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Andre Reed, Bills Work Out Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FREDONIA, N.Y. (AP) -- Andre Reed, Buffalo's leading career  
receiver and one of its few remaining links to the Bills' four 
straight Super Bowl appearances, added another team record: 
shortest holdout. 
</P>
<P>
	Reed, who threatened to quit if the Bills refused to renegotiate  
his contract, practiced for the first time Monday after working out 
a contract extension with team owner Ralph Wilson. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've always wanted to play football,'' said Reed, 35. ``That's  
what I was born to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reed, who missed two minicamps as well as the first two days of  
training camp at Fredonia State, was uncharacteristically jovial 
after starting his 15th season in Buffalo. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had a nice talk with Mr. Wilson about a week and a half ago,  
and we talked about a lot of things,'' Reed said. ``And he agreed 
with me about a lot of things.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One thing they agreed upon was more money for Reed, who this  
season will make $2.2 million, or $900,000 more than his contract 
was due to pay him. 
</P>
<P>
	``All I wanted was to be treated fairly,'' Reed said. ``I just  
wanted to be paid. That's all you deserve. Fortunately we got 
something accomplished, and I'm here to play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The new deal sweetened the pot considerably for Reed, who got a  
$1.8 million signing bonus and a three-year pact that includes a 
one-year extension. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was born to wear a red, white and blue helmet, and when Mr.  
Wilson heard that he said `OK, OK,''' Reed said. 
</P>
<P>
	Reed showed up for the morning practice, having joined the Bills  
for their team meeting on Sunday night. 
</P>
<P>
	The third leading receiver on the NFL's career list behind Jerry  
Rice and Art Monk, Reed is one of only three Buffalo players -- 
along with Bruce Smith and Thurman Thomas -- still around from the 
team's four straight Super Bowl losses of the early 1990s. 
</P>
<P>
	His teammates cheered as Reed took the field. He hugged Smith,  
stretched and pulled on his pads. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a little bit behind, which is funny,'' quarterback Doug  
Flutie said. ``He's got to catch up to some of the young guys, 
actually. But every time he runs a route he's open.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After chatting with Eric Moulds, the team's leading receiver  
last year who credits Reed with helping him, Reed caught a pass in 
front of No. 1 draft pick Antoine Winfield and spun away from 
defensive back Donovan Greer. 
</P>
<P>
	One teammate sang a mock hymn in praise as Reed faced the press.  
</P>
<P>
	Reed joked with a television reporter: ``You said I was speeding  
down the highway and that's not right,'' Reed said. ``I was going 
the speed limit. No cops, man.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last week Reed's agent had all of Buffalo wondering if his  
client would follow Sabres goaltender Dominik Hasek, who announced 
last week that he would retire after next season. However, Reed 
wouldn't have waited a year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hate to say it, but I was contemplating not coming back,''  
Reed said. 
</P>
<P>
	With 889 receptions, including 63 last year, Reed needs just 51  
catches to pass Monk as the second-leading receiver in NFL history. 
Rice is first with 1,139. 
</P>
<P>
	``I knew that was a milestone that was attainable this year,''  
Reed said. ``That would be a great thing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reed, not always the most approachable of the Bills, relapsed  
into sarcasm when someone asked him if had a timetable for 
retirement. ``Do you? When are you going to retire, in about 20 
years?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Then he got serious. ``No, there's no such thing as a  
timetable,'' Reed said. ``I'm just going to see how it goes this 
year, how I feel at the end of the season. If I can stay healthy, 
I'll play again.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
