<DOCNO> APW19990802.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 16:40:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Boilermakers Mourn Tiffany Young </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Her ankle badly sprained and Purdue clinging to a narrow lead  
over Duke, Stephanie White-McCarty sat nervously on the bench and 
held hands with teammate Tiffany Young as the Boilermakers won the 
national championship. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, White-McCarty was speechless at news of her former  
teammate's death in a traffic accident over the weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was overwhelmed when I heard the tragic news of Tiffany's  
death, and I am still at a loss for words to describe how I feel 
about her being gone,'' said White-McCarty, now with the WNBA's 
Charlotte Sting. ``She was such a good person with nothing but love 
in her heart for everybody, and she cannot be replaced.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Members of Purdue's national championship team were reeling  
Monday from Young's death over the weekend when the car she was in 
was struck by a drunk driver. The 5-foot-11 guard played a reserve 
role on Purdue's national championship team, and players and 
coaches remembered her as a special presence. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are a very tight Purdue family, and this is a devastating  
loss,'' said her former coach Carolyn Peck, now with the WNBA's 
Orlando Miracle. ``Tiffany's smile could brighten up a room and she 
will be physically missed, but she will always be a part of me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Young started all 33 of Purdue's games during her sophomore  
season but was relegated to reserve duty this past year with the 
emergence of Katie Douglas in a three-guard lineup that included 
White-McCarty and Ukari Figgs. The senior averaged 3.3 points and 
1.5 rebounds in her career with the Boilermakers, including 2.1 
points last season when she played sparingly. 
</P>
<P>
	But teammates remembered her for more than just the way she  
played. 
</P>
<P>
	``Tiffany was an extremely integral member of our team and will  
be dearly missed,'' Douglas said. ``She will be missed as a 
teammate, but more so as a friend who was always there to give love 
and support.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Young died Saturday night after visiting the family of her  
boyfriend, Neil Sinclair, in Gary, Ind. Sinclair, who was driving, 
was in the intensive care unit at a local hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	The other driver, Arnold D. Eaton, 33, of Great Lakes, Ill., had  
a blood-alcohol content of 0.30 and sustained minor injuries in the 
crash. He was being held on a $10,000 bond by the Lake County 
Sheriff's Department on a charge of operating while intoxicated 
resulting in death. His two passengers were hospitalized in stable 
condition with numerous broken bones. 
</P>
<P>
	Young is to be buried Thursday in her hometown of Hillsboro,  
Ala. 
</P>
<P>
	Purdue spokeswoman Kathleen Offer said the school was working on  
plans for a memorial. 
</P>
<P>
	``She was just happy to be there and happy to be on a team ...  
and to be able to contribute as much as she could,'' Offer said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990802.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 10:31:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  1st Lady Explains Husband's Actions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- First lady Hillary Rodham Clinton called her  
husband's infidelity ``a sin of weakness'' and insisted in a 
magazine interview that she has stayed with him out of love and not 
for her own benefit. 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview with Talk magazine, Mrs. Clinton emphasized that  
her husband's affair with Monica Lewinsky happened after the deaths 
of his mother and her father, and the 1993 suicide of their close 
friend Vincent Foster. 
</P>
<P>
	``You know in Christian theology there are sins of weakness and  
sins of malice, and this was a sin of weakness,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton was impeached by the House for lying about his  
affair with the former White House intern. The Senate acquitted him 
after a trial in February. 
</P>
<P>
	``He couldn't protect me, so he lied,'' Mrs. Clinton said, but  
added the reaction ``was harmful to the country. ... People are 
mean. I think it's a real disservice, the way we sort of strip away 
everybody's sense of dignity, of privacy. People need support, not 
disdain.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The interview with Mrs. Clinton, who is considering a run for  
the Senate from New York state, appears in Talk's first issue, on 
newsstands Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Its author, Lucinda Franks, told CNN today she believes Mrs.  
Clinton chose to talk now about her marriage and its problems to 
fight her public image, which ranges from ``cold, calculating 
political wife'' to a ``kind of soft thinker of romance and 
fantasy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``She has been stereotyped in a way that has been very painful  
to her. I think she feels that people don't understand her, don't 
get her,'' Franks said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton's spokeswoman, Marsha Berry, said today that Franks  
-- wife of Manhattan District Attorney Robert Morgenthau, a 
prominent Democrat -- is ``someone she (Mrs. Clinton) knew and felt 
comfortable with. She had a friendship with this reporter.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the article, Mrs. Clinton said she thought her husband's  
infidelity ``was resolved 10 years ago. ... I thought he had 
conquered it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton blamed her husband's infidelity on a desire to  
please women that can be traced to his childhood. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was so young, barely 4, when he was scarred by abuse. There  
was a terrible conflict between his mother and grandmother,'' she 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``A psychologist once told me that for a boy being in the middle  
of a conflict between two women is the worst possible situation,'' 
Mrs. Clinton said. ``There is always a desire to please each one.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Franks said Clinton's mother, Virginia Kelley, wrote in her  
autobiography about a physical tussle with her son's grandmother 
over who would raise the boy. 
</P>
<P>
	``She describes the chaos. ... She describes an incident in  
which Bill's grandmother and she literally were pulling him 
apart,'' with one tugging on a shoe and the other on an arm, Franks 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	In her book ``Leading with My Heart,'' Kelley said her mother  
was outraged by her plan to marry Roger Clinton -- husband No. 2 -- 
and tried to get legal custody of young Bill. 
</P>
<P>
	``To her mind, Roger Clinton wasn't fit to be under the same  
roof with Bill, and she said she was going to stop the possibility 
of it if she could,'' Kelley wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	``She was actually announcing that she was willing to rip this  
family apart. ... I screamed that the only way she was going to get 
my child was over my dead body,'' Kelley said. ``I clutched Bill, 
who was four years old. I probably thought he was too young to be 
seriously affected by even such scenes as this, but I was dead 
wrong, of course. Forty-one years later, during the presidential 
campaign, I would be flabbergasted to hear some of what he 
remembered about his early life in Hope. I don't know whether or 
not he remembers this part.'' 
</P>
<P>
	White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said he wasn't sure if  
Clinton knew prior to the interview that Mrs. Clinton would discuss 
the incident. 
</P>
<P>
	``He knew some time ago that she'd done this interview and the  
story was coming out,'' Lockhart said. 
</P>
<P>
	Lockhart said Clinton ``believes that like many young people, he  
had difficult times within his family, but he feels he has been 
blessed with love and a wonderful life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He also said Clinton has ``stated openly, publicly, that he is  
responsible for all of his actions, and he's working hard to make 
right some mistakes he's made within his family.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the story, Mrs. Clinton said her husband is a good man, but  
said: ``Yes, he has weaknesses, yes he needs to be more 
responsible, more disciplined.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She told Franks that, since the Lewinsky scandal, her husband  
``has been working on himself very hard. ... He has become more 
aware of his past and what was causing this behavior.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She denied sticking with the president for her own benefit,  
saying his infidelities caused her pain, but did not outweigh the 
relationship the two have built. 
</P>
<P>
	``Is he ashamed? Yes. Is he sorry? Yes. But does this negate  
everything he has done as a husband, a father, a president?'' Mrs. 
Clinton asked. ``There has been enormous pain, enormous anger, but 
I have been with him half my life and he is a very, very good man. 
We just have a deep connection that transcends whatever happens.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She said she and her husband remain close.  
</P>
<P>
	``We talk. We talk in the solarium, in the bedroom, in the  
kitchen -- it's just constant conversation,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, Mrs. Clinton's potential  
GOP rival for the Senate, said today he had no intention of 
bringing up the Clintons' relationship during a campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't believe somebody's private life ... should be part of  
a political campaign,'' he said. ``I have no desire to probe Mrs. 
Clinton's private life.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990802.0167 </DOCNO>
