<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 16:30:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Butler Chides Annan on Arms Probes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Former U.N. weapons chief Richard Butler  
has accused U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan of trying to destroy 
the weapons inspection operation he headed because it was ``too 
independent.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview in the debut issue of Talk magazine, Butler said  
Annan repeatedly confused Iraqi President Saddam Hussein's 
``superficial cooperation'' with U.N. weapons inspectors ``with 
substantive compliance'' on Baghdad's disarmament obligations. 
</P>
<P>
	The secretary-general and his staff reacted to systematic  
cheating by Iraq in destroying and accounting for its banned 
weapons by ``papering over'' problems with diplomacy, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Talk magazine issued a press release with excerpts from the  
interview, to be published Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked Monday to comment on Butler's accusations, Annan said: ``I  
don't think I have to comment. Everybody knows what happened. ... 
It's not relevant in the scheme of things.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After two stormy years, Butler left his job as executive  
director of the U.N. Special Commission, known as UNSCOM, when his 
contract expired on June 30. He is now a diplomat-in-residence at 
the Council on Foreign Relations and is writing a book. 
</P>
<P>
	In the article, Butler said he decided against seeking another  
term because ``the situation within the U.N. had become 
untenable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Butler, an Australian diplomat, pulled UNSCOM inspectors out of  
Iraq in mid-December on the eve of U.S. and British airstrikes, and 
Baghdad has banned them from returning. The Security Council is 
debating a new Iraq policy that will likely include a successor 
organization to UNSCOM. 
</P>
<P>
	``Iraq possesses the knowledge required to make a sophisticated  
atomic bomb, has long-range missiles and has been hard at work on 
extending their range, (and) possesses the means to make both 
chemical and biological weapons,'' Butler said. 
</P>
<P>
	He described UNSCOM as a ``thorn in the side'' of both Saddam  
and Annan and said the secretary-general wanted the ``destruction'' 
of UNSCOM because it was ``too independent to work within the 
mainstream of the U.N.'' 
</P>
<P>
	UNSCOM was created by the Security Council after the 1991  
Persian Gulf War to ensure the elimination of Iraq's nuclear, 
chemical and biological weapons and the long-range missiles to 
deliver them. 
</P>
<P>
	But he said its tough inspection provisions were weakened, and  
Annan at one point asked him to exclude American inspectors as Iraq 
demanded. He refused. 
</P>
<P>
	Butler denied allegations by former UNSCOM inspector Scott  
Ritter, an American, that the CIA was directing the organization's 
activities. 
</P>
<P>
	Ritter ``misrepresented facts and reconstructed events,  
conversations, and decisions in which he played no part'' and his 
assertions hurt UNSCOM's credibility, Butler said. 
</P>
<P>
	Butler also said former Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov  
told him Moscow was motivated to act as Iraq's ``most aggressive 
advocate'' because it hopes to recoup $7 billion in war debts if 
sanctions against Baghdad are lifted. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990802.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 15:30:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> State Food Stamp Rules Found Unfair </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Poor families who are eligible for food stamps  
aren't getting them because of unfair rules imposed by states and 
local governments, congressional investigators said. 
</P>
<P>
	A report released Monday by the General Accounting Office also  
faulted the Agriculture Department for failing to monitor the 
food-stamp program adequately and being too slow in writing new 
regulations. 
</P>
<P>
	Food stamp participation has dropped by 27 percent over the past  
3 1/2 years to 18.5 million people. 
</P>
<P>
	The drop is largely due to the strong economy and changes in  
eligibility requirements, but the report said that demand for food 
assistance from other programs and nonprofit organizations has 
grown, indicating that families who need food stamps aren't getting 
them. 
</P>
<P>
	The number of children who get federally subsidized free lunches  
increased 6 percent from 1994 through 1997, while the number of 
children on food stamps dropped by 18 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	``There has to be a major educational campaign, and the states  
have to actively inform people of available programs,'' said Rep. 
Sander Levin, D-Mich. ``Everyone has to understand the purpose of 
welfare is to help people move from welfare to work.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A federal judge this year barred New York City from requiring  
people to look for a job before applying for food stamps. Michigan 
was illegally denying food stamps to whole households when one 
member of the family violated welfare regulations, said the GAO, 
Congress' investigative and auditing arm. 
</P>
<P>
	Other states and local governments have not been publicizing the  
difference in eligibility requirements for welfare and food stamps, 
the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	USDA, meanwhile, has not written regulations to implement  
changes in the food-stamp program that Congress enacted three years 
ago and has yet to review application procedures in 10 states, the 
investigators said. 
</P>
<P>
	USDA officials say they will finish the food-stamp regulations  
by the end of the year and are working on the state reviews. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is a great deal of confusion among working families  
simply because they have gone to work and they don't know what 
their eligibility status is anymore,'' said Shirley Watkins, USDA's 
undersecretary for food, nutrition and consumer services. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, President Clinton announced that the administration  
would streamline reporting rules for food stamp recipients and 
launch an educational campaign aimed at getting the working poor to 
sign up for the program. 
</P>
<P>
	Nationwide, two of five working families eligible for food  
stamps actually apply for the assistance, according to USDA. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990802.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 03:30:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Eagles Fans Cheer McNabb at Camp </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BETHLEHEM, Pa. (AP) -- Now that contract negotiations are over,  
Donovan McNabb has some catching up to do. He wasted no time during 
his first day on the field at Eagles training camp. 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Andy Reid gave the team's top draft pick plenty of  
practice reps Sunday as McNabb begins the process of learning 
Philadelphia's new West Coast offense. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't feel like it's going to take me long to catch up,''  
said McNabb, who worked primarily with the second unit. ``I think 
the timing is pretty low right now. The receivers I worked out with 
(when he was unsigned) didn't have the speed or the route running 
that these guys have. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just an adjustment period that you go through when you  
report to camp. I'm patient and I'm just going to continue working 
on my conditioning,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	McNabb, taken with the second overall pick in the April draft,  
completed a hectic first weekend with the team. McNabb and the 
Eagles agreed to terms Friday on a seven-year contract worth $54 
million, including an $11.3 million signing bonus, but it wasn't 
until late Saturday that the 32-page contract was approved by the 
league offices and signed by McNabb. 
</P>
<P>
	With that behind him, McNabb stepped onto the field for the  
first time in training camp Sunday, intent on showing he was worth 
the high selection and big money. 
</P>
<P>
	He even heard his first cheers from Philadelphia fans after his  
selection was booed on draft day. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was rewarding to hear the fans cheer and clap for every  
completion that I had,'' McNabb said. ``They seemed to get excited 
about it. That helps out all the players.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reid is just glad McNabb is finally in camp.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm glad he's working,'' Reid said. ``We're catching him up on  
this thing. We're just working him right into the rotation. There 
were a lot of throws he had a chance to complete and they were 
either off the receiver's body or in a position where that receiver 
couldn't catch the football. 
</P>
<P>
	``The thing that I liked was, he finished strong. He came out  
and he was tired and that arm was tired and he worked that last 
series there and finished with some completions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McNabb goes into camp as the backup to Doug Pederson, already  
familiar with the Eagles offense after working with Reid in Green 
Bay. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
