<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 16:21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Nate Newton Inches Closer to Action </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SPARTANBURG, S.C. (AP) -- Nate Newton's bid to extend his NFL  
career inched forward Monday when the Carolina Panthers decided he 
was fit enough to join his teammates for full-squad workouts. 
</P>
<P>
	While his teammates spent the first three days of training camp  
running plays and going through group drills, Newton was secluded 
in a different part of the complex for private workouts with 
strength and conditioning coach Jerry Simmons. 
</P>
<P>
	The goal was to build up the 13-year NFL veteran's endurance and  
flexibility so he could compete for a spot on the offensive line. 
</P>
<P>
	Even when he was cleared for team drills Monday, Newton still  
took it slow, participating in only selected drills for brief 
periods. 
</P>
<P>
	Outfitted in full pads for the first time, the 6-foot-3 Newton  
looked larger than his listed weight of 348 pounds. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just went through a few drills. I didn't do much, but it  
still felt good,'' Newton said. ``I'm trying to get used to the 
pads and try to get back and do a little bit of work.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Newton, 37, was signed to a one-year, $420,000 deal by the  
Panthers in June after he was deemed expendable by the Dallas 
Cowboys, for whom he played 13 seasons and made six Pro Bowl 
appearances. 
</P>
<P>
	Carolina coach George Seifert said there is no timetable for  
bringing along Newton, who will try to unseat Anthony Redmon as the 
Panthers' starting left guard. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not like we're looking to move him into the starting  
spot. I think Redmon's doing a good job, and we'll just see how the 
competition does go there,'' Seifert said. 
</P>
<P>
	To challenge for a roster spot and then for a starting job,  
Newton first wants to get down to 335 pounds. He said he is pleased 
with his progress and is closing in on that figure, but would not 
divulge his exact weight. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm doing fabulous. I'm the type of guy that once I hit it,  
I'm all about getting it going,'' he said. ``I'm close. That's all 
you need to know.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Newton laughed when asked to compare the food at the Cowboys'  
camp to the Panthers' training table cuisine. 
</P>
<P>
	``It doesn't stack up because I ain't been on it yet,'' he said.  
``I'm a fruit and potatoes guy, a fruit and salad guy.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990802.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 16:21:01 </DATE_TIME>
