<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 16:50:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP, Democrats $4B Apart on Farm Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate opened debate Monday over a bailout  
of the nation's farm economy with Democrats and Republicans 
offering rival proposals more than $4 billion apart. 
</P>
<P>
	``Silently and quietly, American farmers and ranchers are losing  
their businesses. They are at the end of their rope,'' Sen. Tom 
Harkin, D-Iowa, said. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats proposed $10.8 billion in aid, while Republicans  
countered with a $6.7 billion plan. The money would be added to an 
annual spending bill for the Agriculture Department. 
</P>
<P>
	The first vote was expected Tuesday afternoon.  
</P>
<P>
	A worldwide glut of grain has kept commodity prices low for a  
second consecutive year, and USDA projects that net farm income 
will dip to $43.8 billion this year. That's about 4 percent off the 
decade's average. 
</P>
<P>
	The Democratic plan includes almost $6 billion in extra crop  
subsidies, $2.3 billion in disaster aid and $1.4 billion in 
emergency trade provisions. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the GOP package would go toward doubling the annual  
``market transition'' payments that farmers receive from the 
government under the 1996 farm bill. That way the money will go 
directly to farmers instead of toward USDA programs, said Sen. Thad 
Cochran, R-Miss. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats say their plan is a better way of helping farmers who  
need it most. 
</P>
<P>
	That the Republicans even offered a proposal of their own this  
week was a recognition of how potent a political issue the farm 
economy has become. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican leaders had argued it was too early to know how much  
help farmers will need this fall. They had pressed the Clinton 
administration without success to offer its own proposal. 
</P>
<P>
	But several farm-state GOP senators have argued the importance  
of Senate action before lawmakers start their long summer recess 
next week. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the chairman of the Senate Agriculture Committee, Dick  
Lugar, R-Ind., suggested Monday that $2 billion to $3 billion in 
aid would be sufficient. Crop subsidies already give farmers a 
``pretty strong safety net,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate leaders put off until Wednesday a debate over the way the  
government regulates dairy prices. A proposal by New England 
lawmakers would bar USDA from going forward with an overhaul of the 
pricing system and allow their states to continue fixing milk 
prices for another year. 
</P>
<P>
	Senators from the upper Midwest have threatened to filibuster  
the spending bill over milk prices. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990802.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 18:40:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bears Sign QB Cade McNown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAKE FOREST, Ill. (AP) -- After missing the first 10 days of  
training camp, Cade McNown didn't want to waste any more time. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chicago Bears' quarterback of the future headed for training  
camp at at Platteville, Wis., on Monday after signing a contract 
that could be worth $22 million over five years. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm fired up to get to Platteville and get started on trying  
to make an impact this year,'' he said at a news conference at the 
team's practice facility. ``Once I get up there, I'm just going to 
have to jump in wherever they are and just spend some time in the 
film room and with the coaches just kind of getting to where I need 
to be.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McNown, the 12th overall pick in the draft out of UCLA, signed a  
seven-year, $15 million deal that includes a $6.1 million signing 
bonus. But McNown can void the last two years of the deal if he 
meets performance-based incentives, such as taking 35 percent of 
the snaps as a rookie or 45 percent of the snaps in his second or 
third year. 
</P>
<P>
	He also can make an additional $7 million if he meets other  
performance-based incentives, agent Tom Condon said. Those 
``escalator clauses'' take the place of the ``buyback'' that's 
usually included in voidable year deals, Condon said. In most 
voidable year deals, teams ``buy back'' the remaining years of the 
long-term contract. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's an exciting place for Cade,'' Condon said. ``There was  
never a time when we didn't think this thing would get done, or 
whether it was going to turn into any kind of an acrimonious 
situation. At the same time, it's complicated -- it was uncharted 
waters, and we're happy that it's over with and both sides got what 
they needed out of the contract.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Bears have made it plain since drafting McNown that he's  
their quarterback of the future. But they appeared to give him 
additional leverage in the contract negotiations when they cut 
veteran Erik Kramer two days before camp started. 
</P>
<P>
	Chicago does have four other quarterbacks in camp -- Shane  
Matthews, Jim Miller, Moses Moreno and Doug Nussmeier -- but they 
have four NFL starts among them. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know. That's a decision for the coaches to make, but  
my job is to be as ready as possible to allow them to make a good 
decision,'' McNown said when asked if he could start in the Bears' 
first game, Sept. 12 against Kansas City. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are no expectations,'' he added. ``From all indications,  
they just want me to be able to step in and play, whatever that 
means.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Bears are installing a new, more wide open offense this  
season, and McNown has gotten some exposure to it at the team's 
minicamps. He's also been studying his play book and working out 
with a trainer, but he said there's no comparison to being at camp. 
</P>
<P>
	``Whether we started camp a month ago or we started it today, I  
need all the preparation I can possibly get,'' he said. ``It 
doesn't matter whether it's one week or two weeks away, so the more 
the better. With that, I just want to tell you how excited I am to 
finally get up to camp and get started.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990802.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 03:10:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> US Baseball Qualifies for Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WINNIPEG, Manitoba (AP) -- The assignment for an assortment of  
American minor league baseball players was demanding: come together 
in two weeks, mesh as a team and qualify their country for the 
Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, the reservations for Sydney and the 2000 Games can be made.  
</P>
<P>
	Long-time minor leaguer Mike Neill had a pinch-hit single in the  
10th inning Sunday night and the Americans struggled before edging 
Mexico 2-1 in the semifinals of the Pan American Games. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States will now play Cuba, which beat Canada in the  
other semifinal, for the Pan Ams gold Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	But the most important mission for this hastily formed team --  
qualifying for the Olympics -- has been accomplished. 
</P>
<P>
	``What an experience, I'll tell you,'' said U.S. manager Buddy  
Bell, his voice cracking with emotion. ``If anybody asks me if they 
should do this, I'd tell them they couldn't pass it up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With one out in top of 10th, Marcus Jensen, America's top hitter  
in the tournament, doubled off the first-base bag. After a 
strikeout, Neill, who got into six games with Oakland last season, 
hit a 3-2 pitch for a run-scoring single off former major league 
pitcher Vicente Palacios. 
</P>
<P>
	``Last year I had a major arm injury and made it to the big  
leagues. That was a long road back and finally getting there was an 
individual thing,'' Neill said. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is by far better as a team member, representing your  
country and trying to get USA baseball into the Olympics. I think 
we were a little tight. But it's awesome playing for your country 
and then getting the big hit to help the team win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dan Wheeler, who pitched well in a 10-5 win over Cuba in the  
preliminary round, got the victory. The right-hander from Triple-A 
Durham pitched a perfect four innings in relief. 
</P>
<P>
	``Wow,'' he said after the Americans swarmed the mound in  
celebration after Wheeler got the final out. ``This is one of the 
things that we needed to do. But I want a gold medal and now we 
have that chance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Americans had a run cut down at the plate in the second when  
Craig Paquette tried to score from first on a double by Milton 
Bradley. Then Mexico took a 1-0 lead in the fourth on an RBI double 
by Ray Martinez. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. team, comprised of players not on the 40-man roster of  
major league clubs, struggled all night against former major 
leaguer Cesar Alvarez. But the Americans finally scored in the 
sixth. A walk, a bunt and a two-out single by Adam Kennedy got the 
run. 
</P>
<P>
	Alvarez allowed only three hits in 7 2-3 innings and had 10  
strikeouts. 
</P>
<P>
	Cuba, the two-time defending Olympic champion, overcame the  
distraction of a ninth-inning protester. It was sweet revenge for 
the Cubans, who were rocked by preliminary-round losses to Canada, 
8-1, and the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Omar Linares, regarded as his nation's best player, hit a  
two-out, three-run homer in the third inning. Jose Ibar pitched 5 
1-3 innings of strong relief before he lost concentration after 
retiring the first batter in the ninth. 
</P>
<P>
	That's when a man carrying a ``Human Right First'' sign came  
onto the field in front of the mound. Cuba's Yobal Duenas rushed 
out of the dugout with his country's flag and tried to wrap up the 
protester. 
</P>
<P>
	The man, wearing a shirt with ``Freedom'' written on the front,  
then ran behind home plate. Cuban catcher Ariel Pestano tried to 
stop the protester with his mask before the man ran in front of the 
Canadian dugout, where he was apparently knocked down by Cuban 
second baseman Juan Padilla. Authorities then took the man away. 
</P>
<P>
	Late Sunday night, police said four members of the Cuban  
delegation were involved in a fight with the protester. The fight 
occurred at 10:30 p.m. in the center of the city outside the 
offices of the Canadian Broadcasting Corporation, acting duty 
inspector Paul Ingram of the Winnipeg City Police said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ibar gave up a single to Todd Betts, threw a wild pitch and  
walked Ryan Radmanovich before Luis Lazo came on to strike out the 
final two hitters. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this year when the Cubans beat the Baltimore Orioles in  
an exhibition at Camden Yards, a protester ran onto the field 
before he was tackled by a Cuban umpire. 
</P>
<P>
	Canadian left fielder Aaron Guiel, who struck out to end the  
game, was in front of the dugout when the protester was trying to 
get away. 
</P>
<P>
	``The guy made us all look bad,'' Guiel said. ``But what is  
great about the U.S. and Canada is that you have the freedom to do 
that. I don't agree with what he did and I also don't agree with 
Cuba's politics, either.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the opening round, Guiel twice ran over Pestano at the plate.  
On Sunday, he was nearly in the middle of another physical 
confrontation. 
</P>
<P>
	``One of their coaches tried to throw a punch and another player  
tried to throw his mask at him. I had my bat in my hand and another 
guy was beside me,'' Guiel said. ``We just stood in between. It's a 
good thing for them they didn't show any aggression toward us. Then 
there would have been some real trouble.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``In a way I understand it. But basically those guys are  
brainwashed into thinking the way their country runs is the way it 
should be run. ...Unfortunately it was a little blemish on the 
game, a great game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Canada had won all five of its games entering the semifinals.  
</P>
<P>
	``Probably the toughest loss I've ever had to take,'' Guiel  
said. ``We were one run, one blooper, one error away from 
qualifying for the Olympics.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Canadians took a 2-0 lead on a run-scoring wild pitch in the  
second and a third-inning solo homer from Stubby Clapp. 
</P>
<P>
	Canadian starter Mike Meyers retired the first two batters in  
the third before Luis Ulacia and Isacc Martinez singled. Linares 
then drove a long homer to left. 
</P>
<P>
	Ibar relieved in the fourth and allowed only one hit into the  
ninth. 
</P>
<P>
	After Lazo got the final two outs, the Cubans, winners of seven  
straight Pan Ams golds, swarmed their hefty relief pitcher. Several 
players ran out of the dugout with their flag. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cubans did not comment after the game, but their actions  
made it clear how relieved they were to qualify for the gold medal 
game -- and for the Olympics. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
