<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 22:40:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> `Good' Cholesterol Gene Discovered </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Researchers have identified a gene that regulates the level of  
so-called good cholesterol in the body, a key step in the drive to 
find new treatments for one of the most common causes of heart 
disease, the nation's No. 1 killer. 
</P>
<P>
	Flaws in the gene, known as ABC1, prevent the production of a  
protein that the body needs to rinse excess bad cholesterol and 
other fats out of cells and the bloodstream. 
</P>
<P>
	The gene was discovered by researchers looking for the cause of  
Tangier disease, an extremely rare inherited illness in which the 
body produces virtually none of the good cholesterol, HDL. Without 
it, the level of the bad cholesterol, LDL, and other fats that 
contribute to heart attacks and clogged arteries rise unchecked. 
</P>
<P>
	Scientists not involved in the studies said the discovery was a  
significant advance in heart disease research because millions of 
people with cardiovascular problems have lower-than-normal HDL 
levels. 
</P>
<P>
	``Patients can have a normal LDL level, but still have  
cardiovascular disease because their HDL is so low,'' said Sonia 
Skarlatos, genetics research leader at the National Heart, Lung and 
Blood Institute in Bethesda, Md. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't have any drugs right now that raise HDL  
significantly. Now we know where to look for the gene and its 
mutations, and how we might enhance the gene's expression to make 
more HDL.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Heart disease is the country's No. 1 killer, and as many as 10  
labs were looking for ABC1. It was isolated in separate studies by 
two sets of scientists in Germany and one in Canada. Their results 
appear in the August issue of Nature Genetics. 
</P>
<P>
	A group headed by Michael Hayden of the University of British  
Columbia, lead author of one of the studies, determined that ABC1 
is responsible for making a protein essential to both HDL formation 
and the process of unloading fats from cells and the blood. 
</P>
<P>
	Stephen Young of the University of California, San Francisco,  
who reviewed the studies independently, said they did not determine 
where the gene works within cells, or the precise biochemical steps 
involved. 
</P>
<P>
	But if the ABC1 discovery does lead to new cholesterol drugs,  
they may work in opposite ways from statins, a class of cholesterol 
busters that have revolutionized heart care. About 8 million 
Americans take statins, though many experts say perhaps as many as 
30 million should be taking them. 
</P>
<P>
	Statins lower the level of LDLs in the bloodstream. For people  
at high risk, the drugs can reduce the risk of a heart attack by 
half. 
</P>
<P>
	Drugs that would boost HDL might offer more protection, doctors  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	HDL, or high-density lipoprotein, is called the good cholesterol  
because LDL, low-density lipoproteins and other fats attach 
themselves to HDL particles and are eventually discarded together 
by the liver. 
</P>
<P>
	``This genetic discovery allows us to ask the question of, `How  
would you impact vascular disease if you were to specifically 
change HDL?''' said Dr. Dennis Sprecher of the Cleveland Clinic. 
``It's a significant piece of the puzzle. But we're not at the 
point where we would start experimentation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Understanding ABC1 also may lead to treatments or gene therapies  
for Tangier disease -- which afflicts only about 40 people worldwide 
-- and less severe illnesses caused by other mutations of the gene. 
</P>
<P>
	Tangier disease is named after tiny Tangier Island in Chesapeake  
Bay. Discovered in 1608 by Capt. John Smith, today it's home to 
about 700 people. Most are descendants of the island's original 
English settlers. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal scientists identified Tangier Disease in two island  
children -- a brother and sister -- in 1963. Their tonsils were 
orange, a sign their cells were overloaded with cholesterol. Tests 
showed they lacked HDL, and researchers launched the first of many 
hunts for the genetic culprit. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990802.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 00:30:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Internet Pornography Sites Thriving </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- When Internet pornographers allegedly tried to use  
Nancy Kerrigan's fame to sell pictures on their Web site, all they 
needed was the correct spelling of her name. 
</P>
<P>
	By inserting it 32 times in a block of text called a ``metatag''  
used by Internet search engines, they were able to fool the search 
engines into believing the site was about the medal-winning Olympic 
skater. 
</P>
<P>
	Some fans curious about Kerrigan found themselves directed to  
pornographic pictures on the site -- although Kerrigan's name was 
never seen there, and there certainly were no nude pictures of the 
skater. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, Kerrigan, 29, sued the site's operators and it has  
since disappeared from the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	It wasn't the first court victory for Kerrigan -- she was awarded  
an undisclosed amount of money in 1998 by an Internet company that 
allegedly displayed images of her online that had been doctored to 
make them pornographic. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, her success has hardly had a chilling effect on the  
thriving Internet pornography industry, where even small sites can 
make up to $10,000 per month. 
</P>
<P>
	In an ever-expanding electronic terrain there are seemingly  
limitless avenues for pornographers to exploit famous women. 
</P>
<P>
	``You don't have to have taken your clothes off,'' said  
Kerrigan's attorney, Victor Polk. ``If you're a famous woman in 
this country, your name is going to be used to sell pornography.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Internet's combination of cheap access and worldwide reach  
make it almost impossible to regulate tightly, experts say. The law 
gives celebrities some ammunition to fight for their names, but 
high costs and potentially low returns have discouraged many from 
using it. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's the wild, wild West with just a couple of marshals,''  
said Mitchell Kamarck, who represented TV star Alyssa Milano in a 
lawsuit against online firms. ``We have the tools. It's a matter of 
applying the tools.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Legal issues involving the Internet are relatively new, but one  
Internet law specialist says protecting names and images likely 
will boil down to adjusting existing law to fit the new medium. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's really a case of adjusting fairly well-established  
principles to new facts,'' said Houston lawyer D.C. Toedt. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Kerrigan case, Polk says copyright law could apply  
because indiscriminate use of Kerrigan's name absent any context is 
not ``fair use'' of her name. 
</P>
<P>
	Other legal principles that have been effectively used include a  
``right of publicity,'' which gives a person the right to control 
and profit from the commercial use of their name, as well as 
trademark, privacy and defamation statutes. 
</P>
<P>
	But even if the law evolves to favor celebrities, practical  
considerations make it virtually impossible to shut down every 
illegal site, according to Mitchell Zimmerman, a Palo Alto, Calif., 
attorney who works in Internet law. 
</P>
<P>
	First, simply finding the offenders is a major chore. At the  
first sign of trouble, site owners can shut down and begin again 
for relatively little money. Some smaller sites aren't worth 
pursuing because operators have no money. And because the Internet 
is worldwide, figuring out whose laws apply when material is 
produced in one country but seen in another is an unresolved issue. 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest reason there will always be illegal celebrity porno  
sites, Zimmerman said, is the decentralized nature of the Internet, 
a major part of its appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Internet and World Wide Web are inherently  
uncontrollable,'' he said. ``There's nobody in charge, and there 
can't be anybody in charge.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While stopping the misuse of celebrities' images may or may not  
be a realistic hope, model Alley Baggett said she'll fight to shut 
down those sites she can. Baggett, 26, Playboy's 1998 lingerie 
model of the year, has seen her name and image on the hard-core 
Internet sites, and wants them gone. 
</P>
<P>
	``I love the Internet. I love what its done for me,'' she said.  
``At the same time, you definitely have to try to have control or 
everyone's going to walk all over you.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990802.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 15:50:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Strawberry Suspension Cut by Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- After 10 months of waiting, Darryl Strawberry  
can finally focus on returning to the New York Yankees. 
</P>
<P>
	Strawberry's 120-day suspension for his arrest on solicitation  
and drug charges April 14 was cut short one week by commissioner 
Bud Selig on Monday, making the New York Yankees outfielder 
eligible to play Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm starting to get into the frame of mind of playing,''  
Strawberry said in Tampa, Fla. ``I'm looking forward to it. I'm 
ready to get going.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Strawberry's penalty was originally scheduled to run through  
Aug. 11. Selig decided to shorten the suspension after reviewing 
medical records and speaking to Strawberry twice. 
</P>
<P>
	``The good thing out of this for me was, it allowed the time off  
to really take care of myself physically and mentally,'' said 
Strawberry, who hasn't played since learning last Oct. 1 that he 
had colon cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	Strawberry will report Wednesday to Triple-A Columbus of the  
International League and is expected to play that night against 
Norfolk. Manager Joe Torre said Strawberry will need at least one 
week, probably more, before he will be ready to return to the 
majors. 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest problem facing Strawberry now is an injured left  
knee, that has limited his running and makes it difficult to play 
outfield. With Chili Davis entrenched at designated hitter, 
Strawberry will have to be able to play left field to get into the 
lineup consistently. 
</P>
<P>
	``If he can't play every day, a week only means three or four  
games, which isn't very much for a guy who hasn't played since 
September,'' Torre said. ``We know what he brings to the table as a 
threat with the bat. We need to find out if he can play outfield.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Strawberry has been working out at the Yankees' minor league  
complex in Tampa since July 9. His batting practice performances 
have shown that the majestic left-handed swing that has hit 332 
career homers hasn't deserted him. 
</P>
<P>
	Now he gets the chance to do it in the minors. After waiting for  
a ruling from Selig since July 22, Strawberry isn't concerned about 
how long it will take to return to the Yankees. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's too far ahead,'' Strawberry said. ``I really haven't  
thought about that. I'm just taking it day by day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Strawberry, who was suspended 60 days for testing positive for  
cocaine in 1995, admitted last month that an alcohol relapse 
contributed to his arrest. He has been attending Alcoholics 
Anonymous meetings in Tampa, while working out. 
</P>
<P>
	He hasn't played in a game since the final week of the 1998  
season, before surgery for colon cancer forced him to miss the 
playoffs and the World Series. 
</P>
<P>
	``With all of the negatives that he's been through, it's good to  
see something positive happen for him,'' Davis said. ``He can see 
the light at the end of the tunnel. He wants to come back to New 
York and that's what we want for him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Strawberry was one of the most popular Yankees in the clubhouse  
before the cancer and suspension. And his teammates aren't worried 
that his return could disrupt the team. 
</P>
<P>
	``He is a positive influence,'' Derek Jeter said. ``I don't see  
how Darryl could be a distraction. He's all about the team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Strawberry's availability has been a recurring theme around the  
Yankees for the past five seasons. He joined the Yankees on Aug. 4, 
1995, after spending four weeks in the minors following his first 
drug suspension. 
</P>
<P>
	He played sporadically and was not brought back at the start of  
1996. After a stint in the independent Northern League, Strawberry 
was brought back to New York in July 1996 and played a major role 
in helping the Yankees win the World Series. 
</P>
<P>
	He played only 11 games in an injury-plagued 1997. He made his  
biggest contributions last season, hitting 24 homers in 295 at-bats 
before being diagnosed with colon cancer during last year's 
playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	His expected return this season was delayed by chemotherapy  
treatments and then the arrest. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a unique organization,'' Torre said. ``Billy Martin  
came back five times. ... Distractions are always there. It's how 
you handle them that matters.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
