<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Caddies Told Not To Wear Shorts  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	THOUSAND OAKS, Calif. (AP) -- Before the showdown between Tiger  
Woods and David Duval came a standoff between their caddies and the 
PGA Tour over what has become a sticky issues: shorts. 
</P>
<P>
	Both arrived at Sherwood Country Club wearing shorts, and PGA  
Tour official Vaughn Moise told them to wear pants because the heat 
index was not 100 degrees. The high Monday was 94. 
</P>
<P>
	Mitch Knox, the caddie for Duval, scrambled to find a nice pair  
of trousers -- so stylish that they came without a hem, and he had 
to roll them up four times so they wouldn't drag on the ground. 
</P>
<P>
	When Moise approached Steve Williams, Woods stepped in and told  
his caddie not to change. During a telephone call from PGA Tour 
chief legal officer Ed Moorhouse, Moise suggested that Williams 
could face disciplinary action after the match. 
</P>
<P>
	Knox didn't want to talk about it, saying he was too mad.  
</P>
<P>
	Moise also declined comment other than to say, ``It's over,'' as  
the players headed to the first tee -- Williams in shorts, Knox in 
pants too long. 
</P>
<P>
	The PGA Tour is in the final week of a trial period in which  
caddies will be allowed to wear shorts when the heat index is 100 
degrees. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
