<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 3:10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Monday, Aug. 2, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Manufacturing Sector Grows in July  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- `A survey of purchasing managers said today that  
the U.S. manufacturing sector grew in July for the sixth 
consecutive month, but not as strongly as most analysts expected. 
The National Association of Purchasing Management said its monthly 
index of manufacturing activity registered 53.4 percent in July, 
compared with 57 percent in June. Figures above 50 percent indicate 
growth. The purchasing managers group also reported a slightly 
stronger rise in July raw-material prices than in June. The 
managers' report eased fears on Financial markets that there might 
be another hike in interest rates soon. 

</P>
<P>
	Construction Spending Rebounds  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Construction spending rose 0.5 percent in June  
after falling in two straight months. The Commerce Department said 
today that spending rose to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 
$699.4 billion, following drops of 1.4 percent in both May and 
April. The increases were fairly widespread with gains reported in 
office buildings, industrial buildings, hotels and motels and big 
government projects. However, spending on all residential 
construction fell 0.3 percent. The overall increase in construction 
spending was in line with many analysts' expectations. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Up 90.23; Nasdaq Up 12.54  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rose sharply today after a new report  
suggested the economy has not expanded quite as fast as market 
watchers had feared. Just before 3 p.m. EDT, the Dow Jones 
industrial average was up 90.23 at 10,745.38. The index had risen 
as much as 136 points earlier in the session. Broader stock 
indicators also posted solid gains, with the Nasdaq composite index 
up 12.54 at 2,651.03. 

</P>
<P>
	Financial Figures  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Financial figures just before 3 p.m. EDT:  
