</P>
<P>
	Most Financial Firms Set for Y2K  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal regulators reported today that 99  
percent of the nation's banks, thrifts and credit unions have 
completed testing for the Year 2000 bug in their computer systems. 
Among the nation's 10,335 banks and thrifts, 10,246 received the 
highest possible rating for readiness, 78 were told they needed to 
improve and 11 drew unsatisfactory ratings, according to the 
Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. A similar breakdown among the 
10,807 credit unions included in the overall assessment wasn't 
immediately available. The regulators said most financial 
institutions, a number they did not specify, already are using 
computer systems that are Year 2000 compliant every day without 
problems. 

</P>
<P>
	Internet Shopping Slips  
</P>
<P>
	WESTPORT, Conn. (AP) -- The percentage of Internet users making a  
purchase online decreased slightly in the second quarter, the first 
drop in a year, according to a survey. The percentage of people 
with online access who said they purchased something from a Web 
site fell to 71 percent in the second quarter, down from 74 percent 
in the first quarter, according to Greenfield Online, a Westport, 
Conn.-based Internet marketing research firm. The decline followed 
four straight quarters of increases in online purchasing, according 
to Greenfield. 

</P>
<P>
	CBS Earnings Rise Sharply  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- CBS Corp. credited strong growth in its  
television and radio businesses for a large jump in second-quarter 
earnings. CBS reported today it earned $95 million, or 13 cents a 
share, compared with $4 million, or 1 cent a share, in the same 
period a year ago. The earnings matched Wall Street expectations. 
CBS president Mel Karmazin singled out a strong showing at the 
company's TV network business as an engine behind the profit surge. 
CBS was the top-rated network last season, taking the No. 1 spot 
for the first time in five years. CBS stock was up 13/16 at 44 3/4 in 
afternoon trading. 

</P>
<P>
	AutoNation Separating Rental Units  
</P>
<P>
	FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) -- AutoNation Inc. announced plans  
today to separate its rental-car business, including the Alamo and 
National chains, so the rest of the company can focus on auto 
sales. The Fort Lauderdale-based company disclosed the plans in 
issuing its quarterly earnings report. The rental division includes 
National Car Rental, Alamo Rent-A-Car and CarTemps USA. The board, 
which voted to separate the unit last week, has yet to decide how 
the rental companies will be separated, said AutoNation spokesman 
Jim Donahue. AutoNation reported earnings from its continuing 
operations rose to $97.1 million, or 21 cents a share, in the 
second quarter from $54.2 million, or 11 cents a share, in the same 
period a year ago. AutoNation shares were up 3/16 at 15 1/8. 

</P>
<P>
	Cooper Industries Buys 2 Companies  
</P>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- Tool and electrical product maker Cooper  
Industries today announced the acquisition of two electrical 
products companies, JSB Electrical of England and Corelite of 
Denver. No financial terms were disclosed. JSB is a maker of 
emergency lighting, fire detection and security systems. Corelite 
is a privately-held manufacturer of indirect lighting fixtures. 
Last year, the companies had combined revenues of more than $50 
million. 

</P>
<P>
	Japan Vehicle Sales Fall in July  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Sales of cars, trucks and buses fell 13.9 percent  
in July from the same month last year, marking Japan's 28th 
straight month of declines of vehicle sales. Sales totaled 372,334 
vehicles in July, the Japan Automobile Dealers' Association said 
today. The monthly figures also included sales of imported 
vehicles, which fell 5.9 percent to 23,656. 

</P>
<P>
	Russian Grain Harvest Doing Better  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Russian farms will harvest 66 million tons of  
grain this year, according to Ministry of Agriculture estimates 
released today, the Interfax news agency reported. The figure is 
higher than previous estimates. It suggests that a drought and 
locusts in the south, where most of the country's grain grows, have 
not cut into output as severely as originally feared. Estimates for 
1999 have fluctuated nearly every week, dipping as low as 55 
million tons. But Minister of Agriculture and Food Vladimir 
Shcherbak said yields per acre were up about 20 percent compared 
with last year. 

</P>
<P>
	Brazilians Turn To Informal Economy  
</P>
<P>
	RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- Recession and rising unemployment  
have swelled the ranks of the underground economy, a huge but 
shadowy sector that dodges taxes and defies measuring. With the 
government predicting zero growth at best for this year, more and 
more Brazilians are JOINING IT. ``You wouldn't believe what goes on 
behind people's doors,'' says the cheerfully indiscreet doorman in 
one apartment house. ``We've got a hairdresser, a takeout meal 
service, two clothes makers, a manicurist, a natural products 
saleswoman and a coconut vendor.'' The government-run Brazilian 
Institute for Geography and Statistics, reporting recently on a 
1997 study of the informal economy, said that at that time one in 
four of Brazil's 52 million economically active people were in the 
informal economy. Of those, 55 percent worked at home or at their 
clients' homes. 

</P>
