<DOCNO> APW19990802.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 18:01:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Gwynn Enjoys Chase to 3,000 Hits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- As Mark McGwire and Tony Gwynn close in on  
milestones, it's easy to see which player appears to be enjoying 
the chase more. 
</P>
<P>
	Gwynn, who entered Monday night's game against McGwire's St.  
Louis Cardinals six hits shy of 3,000, affably dealt with wave 
after wave of media in the hours before the game. 
</P>
<P>
	``The pursuit has been fun,'' Gwynn said. ``The end of the  
pursuit has been a little bit more than even I thought it would be, 
but still, it's been fun.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gwynn said McGwire told him that holding mass news conferences  
during his 70-homer season allowed him to stay focused on the Roger 
Maris chase and the Sammy Sosa duel. 
</P>
<P>
	That's not Gwynn's way. The eight-time batting champion doesn't  
mind answering the same questions over and over to every individual 
reporter, always with a smile. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd rather sit down and talk to guys individually or in  
smaller groups because, to me, you get more out of it and both guys 
get more out of it,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gwynn has another reason for instant availability: He tried it  
McGwire's way and it was a bust. 
</P>
<P>
	``McGwire told me in San Diego he thought it saved him last year  
because he only had to discuss it one time,'' Gwynn said. ``So I 
took that advice to heart and went to Los Angeles and decided, I'll 
call a 3:30 press conference, and like, two guys showed up. If I 
get to first base, I'll have to let him know.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gwynn was McGwire's locker neighbor at the All-Star Game at  
Boston, and he can sympathize if McGwire isn't Mr. Sunshine after 
seeing the demands placed upon him just from within. 
</P>
<P>
	``You talk about major league baseball leaning on somebody,''  
Gwynn said. ``The demands they make on guys like him and Griffey 
and Bonds, the icons of the game, the guys that carry the major 
league logo, is amazing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McGwire, who entered the game three homers shy of 500 and with  
13 homers in 17 games, has steadfastly avoided the topic. After he 
hit No. 497 and drove in four runs in a 5-4 loss to Colorado on 
Sunday, he was particularly surly. 
</P>
<P>
	``You guys always ask me about numbers and I keep saying winning  
is what I care about,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gwynn said St. Louis is the next-best place to reach 3,000 if he  
can't do it at home. He's flown in a rather large entourage of 
family members, and they'll all head to Montreal if it doesn't 
happen in St. Louis. 
</P>
<P>
	Gwynn had been 9-for-43 before getting three hits and homering  
Sunday against Houston. He entered the night tied with Wade Boggs 
of Tampa Bay. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hopefully, I can get six hits and have it all work out,''  
Gwynn said. ``But the way I've been going, we may have to pack up 
and move on to the next stop.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gwynn was hoping he, McGwire and Boggs wouldn't steal each  
other's thunder by reaching their milestone on the same day. 
</P>
<P>
	``But it wouldn't surprise me at all if we all did it within 15  
minutes of each other.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990802.0196 </DOCNO>
