<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 16:20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Airlines Cut Fares for Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) -- Airlines are offering steep discounts  
for late summer and fall travel, a welcome respite in a year during 
which the base ticket price has gone up 11 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Northwest Airlines, the nation's fourth-largest airline, kicked  
off the fare sale during the weekend, with its computer system 
posting some off-peak prices discounted by as much as 25 percent. 
The fare changes were formally announced on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	United Airlines, the nation's largest carrier, and No. 2  
American Airlines were among those matching the sale, which 
includes most of the continental U.S., Hawaii, and Canada. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's pretty much systemwide,'' said American spokesman Tim  
Smith. 
</P>
<P>
	Other airlines offering the discounts include U.S. Airways,  
America West, Continental, Trans World Airlines and Delta Air 
Lines. 
</P>
<P>
	Northwest said the discounts would remain in effect for travel  
to most destinations through Dec. 17. Advance purchase is required, 
a 14-day maximum stay applies to most destinations and tickets must 
be purchased by Aug. 13. A Saturday night stay is required and 
tickets are nonrefundable. 
</P>
<P>
	Many international flights were announced as part of the sale as  
well, but those discounts have actually been available for more 
than a week, according to Tom Parsons, editor of www.bestfares.com, 
an Internet site that tracks travel costs. 
</P>
<P>
	``The only place I've seen any difference is to Asia,'' said  
Parsons. 
</P>
<P>
	Terms of the Asian discounts differ slightly from the domestic  
fare cuts. 
</P>
<P>
	Parsons cautioned consumers that they could get better fares  
through some spot sales rather than through the new systemwide 
offer. He suggested travelers contact a travel agent to search for 
the best price. 
</P>
<P>
	For instance, Southwest Airlines' occasional coast-to-coast fare  
sales can result in better prices for travelers. Southwest has had 
three of those sales so far this year. Also, America West last week 
reduced prices for flights in and out of Orange County, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is not one of those fare sales to write home to mom  
about,'' he said. ``But with this sale more people can participate. 
I think the cities that are probably enjoying this air sale are 
where there's no competition.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some fare examples include an off-peak fare of $354 roundtrip  
from New York to Dallas-Fort Worth with a 14-day advance purchase. 
That's compared to an everyday rate of $472, according to Smith. 
</P>
<P>
	A Chicago to San Francisco roundtrip, advance purchase, off-peak  
price would be $446, compared to an everyday price of $594, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Discounts of up to 25 percent mean some tickets are at the  
lowest level of this year. Airlines have been under pricing 
pressure in 1999 as they add planes to their fleets and additional 
seats become available. 
</P>
<P>
	Airline analyst Holly Hegeman with PlaneBusiness, an Internet  
site that focuses on the airline industry, attributes this sale to 
the additional space made available. 
</P>
<P>
	``Too much capacity is the culprit. Airlines are obviously  
looking ahead at bookings, seeing weak books in many cases, and so 
they are lowering the fares in an attempt to at least fill seats at 
some fare level,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	On the fare cut announcement, Northwest shares fell 37 1/2 cents to  
$31.75 on the Nasdaq Stock Market. 
</P>
<P>
	But many airline stocks rose, in part because American Airlines  
reported strong travel numbers for July. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're usually the bellwether,'' said Susan Donofrio at BT  
Alex. Brown Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	AMR, the parent of American, was up $1.18 3/4 at $66.06 1/4 a share on  
the New York Stock Exchange, where UAL, the parent of United, was 
up 43 3/4 cents at $63.87 1/2. U.S. Airways rose $2.87 1/2 to $38.50 on news 
that a major shareholder was pushing to improve the value of the 
company's shares, including exploring a possible sale or merger. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990802.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 15:10:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Softball Is Rolling Along </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WINNIPEG, Manitoba (AP) -- Unbeaten, virtually unscored upon and  
nearly unhittable. Nobody can touch the U.S. women's softball team. 
</P>
<P>
	In 37 games in the Pan American Games since 1987, the Americans  
never have lost. When they give up a run, it's a shock for this 
dream squad that has dominated the world. 
</P>
<P>
	This Pan Am squad, however, appears to be extra special.  
</P>
<P>
	``This team is probably the most powerful ever assembled,'' Dot  
Richardson, the peppery second baseman, said. 
</P>
<P>
	Richardson's evaluation has to be taken seriously. She played on  
the team that won the gold medal in the 1979 Pan Am Games. Except 
for a two-year break after the 1996 Olympics to work on her 
residency -- she now is an orthopedic surgeon -- has been a member of 
almost every major U.S. team in the past 20 years. 
</P>
<P>
	In the previous three Pan Ams, when the United States won the  
gold medal, the Americans outscored their opposition 194-5. In 
those 30 games, U.S. pitchers threw 26 shutouts. The only team to 
score more than one run against them was Canada, a 4-2 loser in 
1991. Nine times they won by at least 10 runs. Canada also was the 
last team to beat the Americans, 5-4 in the 1983 title game. 
</P>
<P>
	This year's team, bolstered by the addition of former pro Crystl  
Bustos, the shortstop and cleanup hitter, and other outstanding 
young talent, already is 7-0, all shutouts until Monday's 8-1 
victory over Colombia. The Americans have scored 56 runs. 
</P>
<P>
	The pitchers have allowed only 10 hits, with Danielle Henderson  
throwing a perfect game against Colombia and a one-hitter against 
the Bahamas. Lisa Fernandez tossed a no-hitter against Cuba, and 
Michele Smith, the most valuable player in the Japan League each of 
the past two years and three times overall, hurled a one-hitter 
against the Netherlands Antilles. They have struck out 97 in 47 
innings. 
</P>
<P>
	``The U.S. has dominated the sport because of our experience and  
the drive for each player to reach her full potential,'' said 
Richardson, 37. ``When you have athletes with that talent, you will 
see success.'' 
</P>
<P>
	First baseman Sheila Douty, also 37, with three children and a  
granddaughter on the way, has been around as long as Richardson. 
Like her teammate, she played on the first Olympic gold medalists 
in softball in 1996 and on three Pan Am winning teams. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have a huge player base to choose from,'' Douty said.  
``Some kids start playing T-ball at 4 or 5. They get into 
competitive ball between 8 and 10. Then they play in national 
tournaments against teams across the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	``Playing that long, having good coaching and developing their  
techniques makes them good players.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Ralph Raymond, who will guide the Americans in the 2000  
Olympics, agrees with Douty. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've had the opportunity to have a greater pick of the  
players,'' Raymond said, ``because about 200,000 are playing the 
(fast-pitch) game in the United States.'' 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. teams also have won five golds and one silver in six Pan Am  
Games, and won six golds, including the last four, and two silvers 
in the world championships. Their 89-11 record in the worlds is the 
best ever. 
</P>
<P>
	This 15-member team includes nine players from the Olympic team  
that lost only once to Australia, before beating China three 
straight times to win the gold. 
</P>
<P>
	By winning the world title last year in Fujinomiya, Japan, the  
Americans qualified for the Sydney Games and will be the top seed. 
The team trials for the Olympics will be Sept. 2-4 at Midland, 
Mich. Forty-eight players have been invited, with 15 to be selected 
by a seven-member committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the players invited who are not in Winnipeg are Michele  
Granger, the starting pitcher in the opener game and the gold medal 
game at the Olympics. She hasn't played since then because she had 
two children. 
</P>
<P>
	Pitcher Christa Williams, the youngest member of the Olympic  
team at 18, and second baseman Dani Tyler, another '96 Olympian, 
also were invited. 
</P>
<P>
	While Pan Ams opponents aren't as strong as those in the Canada  
Cup, which the United States recently won, the Americans aren't 
treating their opposition lightly. 
</P>
<P>
	``You're representing yourself and your country,'' Fernandez,  
who got the save in the Olympic gold medal game against China, 
said. ``There's a lot of pride on the line. Even though we've been 
traveling a lot lately, you can't walk out on the field and say 
you're tired. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would be terrible for someone to come out here and beat us.  
We couldn't live with a loss. Deep in our hearts, we feel if we 
play our game, we should come out on top.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
