<HEADLINE> Alaska Airlines Reaches Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- A tentative agreement on a new four-year contract  
was announced Monday by Alaska Airlines and the union representing 
its flight attendants. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal, which now must be approved by union members, would  
cover the nearly 2,000 attendants at the regional carrier who are 
represented by the Association of Flight Attendants, AFL-CIO. 
</P>
<P>
	Both sides said they would not announce details of the proposed  
agreement until union members have had a chance to review the 
offer, but it contains wage and benefit increases and an improved 
401(k) retirement savings plan. 
</P>
<P>
	``We worked hard to address the concerns of all flight  
attendants in this contract,'' said Thomas Lent, AFA Master 
Executive Council president at Alaska. ``I think the members will 
be pleased with the improvement we made in compensation, benefits, 
work rules and scheduling flexibility.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Today we have a tentative agreement that will help keep the  
airline in a strong competitive position, while offering our flight 
attendants an attractive package of pay and benefits,'' said John 
F. Kelly, Alaska's chairman and chief executive officer. 
</P>
<P>
	Alaska Airlines, part of Alaska Air Group, serves more than 40  
cities in Alaska, Canada, Mexico and five Western states. 


  	   	
