<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Congress Negotiates Final Tax Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Congressional Republicans, working with  
unusual urgency, labored Monday toward a compromise on tax cuts, 
intent on passing the measure through the House and Senate by 
week's end as part of a veto showdown with President Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	The chairmen of the two tax-writing committees, Texas Rep. Bill  
Archer of the House Ways and Means Committee and Delaware Sen. 
William Roth of the Finance Committee, met privately in a room in 
the Capitol as aides shuttled in and out. 
</P>
<P>
	The senior GOP leadership of both houses convened later in the  
day, and it appeared that Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., and 
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., were exercising firm 
control over the negotiations. 
</P>
<P>
	Both the House and Senate passed $792 billion tax cut measures  
in the past two weeks, but the two bills differ significantly in 
detail. The House bill calls for a 10 percent across-the-board tax 
cut, phased in over a decade, to achieve broad-based tax relief. 
The Senate measure, by contrast, would drop the current 15 percent 
tax bracket to 14 percent, and allow income that is currently taxed 
at 28 percent to be subject to the lower tax instead. 
</P>
<P>
	Both houses provide relief from the so-called marriage penalty  
and estate taxes and reduce taxes on capital gains, but with 
different provisions. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, the Senate measure includes numerous provisions to  
assist taxpayers who save for their retirement. There also are 
differences over tax breaks for health care and education, as well 
as special interests. 
</P>
<P>
	The issue spilled briefly into public when Democrats forced a  
roll call vote in the House on their demand that Republicans scale 
back the tax cut to extend the solvency of Social Security and 
Medicare and provide for a prescription drug benefit for recipients 
of the health care program for the elderly. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Bob Matsui, D-Calif., said that by their vote, Republicans  
were indicating whether they supported a cut in Social Security 
benefits. 
</P>
<P>
	And Rep. Charles Rangel, D-N.Y., said Republicans were ``begging  
for a veto'' and would get one. 
</P>
<P>
	Archer said Democrats made the same charges about spending cuts  
the last time Republicans pushed for tax cuts. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can save Social Security. We can save Medicare. We can give  
a prescription drug benefit and we can pay down the debt and we can 
give a small amount of tax relief,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Whatever the rhetoric on the House floor, the real decisions  
were being made in private, in meetings involving Lott, Hastert and 
other GOP leaders. 
</P>
<P>
	Customarily, both houses name numerous senior lawmakers to  
thrash out differences in legislation. In this case, though, the 
group was limited to two Republicans and one Democrat from the 
Senate and four Republicans and two Democrats from the House. To 
keep the closest possible control over the proceedings, Republicans 
tapped Lott and Roth from the Senate and Majority Leader Dick Armey 
and Archer from the House. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans labored under a schedule that called for House  
passage on Thursday and Senate passage on Friday. Rank-and-file GOP 
lawmakers intend to trumpet the benefits of their measure during 
Congress' long August recess, then send the bill to Clinton for his 
expected veto after Labor Day. 
</P>
<P>
	The drive for tax cuts stems from enormous surpluses projected  
to materialize over the next decade. Republicans say they will set 
aside more than $2 trillion to help ensure Social Security's 
solvency before turning to tax cuts. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats caution that the surpluses may never materialize and  
that in the decade beginning in 2009, the GOP tax cut will explode 
by an additional $3 trillion. As a result, they said, it would 
jeopardize the economy. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990802.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 14:40:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nearly All Banks Said OK for Y2K </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Ninety-nine percent of the nation's federally  
insured banks, thrifts and credit unions have successfully 
completed preparations for the Year 2000 computer bug, federal 
regulators reported Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the nation's 10,335 banks and thrifts, 10,246 received the  
highest possible rating for readiness, 78 were told they needed to 
improve and 11 drew unsatisfactory ratings, according to the 
Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, only 56 of the nation's 10,807 credit unions had not  
completed Year 2000 testing as of July 28, the National Credit 
Union Administration said in a report to Congress last week. 
</P>
<P>
	Most financial institutions already are using computer systems  
that are Year 2000 compliant, the regulators said, without offering 
specific numbers. The institutions had to meet a June 30 deadline 
for testing. 
</P>
<P>
	``The agencies are confident that, based on their reviews,  
financial institution customers will be able to conduct business as 
usual both before and after Jan. 1, 2000,'' the Federal Financial 
Institutions Examination Council, which issued Monday's report, 
said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Regulators are ``closely supervising'' the few institutions  
lagging in their readiness, said the council, which consists of the 
FDIC, the Federal Reserve, the Treasury Department's office of the 
comptroller of the currency, the Office of Thrift Supervision and 
the National Credit Union Administration. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Reserve recently approved a plan to make special  
loans to banks, thrifts and credit unions that might need emergency 
money because of consumer fears about system breakdowns caused by 
computers that can't handle the Year 2000 date change. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan said in congressional  
testimony that banks will be the safest place for people to keep 
their cash at the end of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Even so, many Americans are expected to withdraw extra cash on  
or before the New Year. 
</P>
<P>
	The House on Monday approved legislation that would expand the  
types of collateral a bank can offer when seeking credit from the 
Federal Reserve. The aim of the bill, passed by voice vote, is to 
help banks deal with an unusual demand for cash. The Senate has yet 
to consider it. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
