<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 13:00:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Son of Ex-NFL Star Slain in Atlanta </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- Though slain seemingly in his prime during last  
week's massacre in an Atlanta office building, Kevin Dial already 
had made his peace with death. 
</P>
<P>
	Dial, the 36-year-old son of former NFL star Buddy Dial, had an  
inoperable brain tumor. His family made the disclosure at his 
funeral Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it's worth seeing or hearing or doing, I want to see it or  
hear it or do it now,'' Dial wrote in a letter he faxed to his 
mother, Janice Marye, the day before Thursday's shooting rampage. 
</P>
<P>
	Dial's sister, Sherri, read the letter to some 500 mourners who  
filled the sanctuary at Second Baptist Church in Houston. She 
sobbed throughout the eulogy about her ``best friend.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She continued reading the letter: ``Every day, every breath,  
every thing in life really is a gift from God.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Buddy Dial starred at Rice University before going on to  
standout career as a receiver with the Pittsburgh Steelers and 
Dallas Cowboys. He attended the service despite a recent stroke and 
chronic injuries from his football days. 
</P>
<P>
	Kevin Dial visited his father in nearby Tomball during the July  
4 holiday weekend and told him he was prepared to die, relatives 
said. However, in his letter last week, Dial spoke of his 
frustration at being unable to grow old: 
</P>
<P>
	``It's those little things left undone that make me angry that  
my days are limited,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Dial was helping to establish a Momentum Securities day-trading  
office in Atlanta. Trader Mark Barton killed Dial and three others 
at the office Thursday, then killed five more at another firm. Nine 
shooting victims remained hospitalized Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Barton also fatally bludgeoned his wife and two children in the  
two days preceding the rampage. He committed suicide after the 
shootings as police closed in. 
</P>
<P>
	``What happened that day was not God's will,'' the Rev. Richard  
O'Brien said. ``It was the evil act of one man, no matter the 
provocation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dial's sister and other speakers recalled a natural leader with  
a magnetic personality. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm pretty sure you're with Elvis, having cocktails, trying to  
convince God to let (John) Belushi visit,'' she said, speaking to 
her brother and drawing laughter. ``And I think he'll probably do 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dial was buried at Forest Park Lawndale Cemetery in Houston.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
