<HEADLINE> Soybeans, Grains Continue Climb / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Soybean and grain futures prices soared in early  
dealings today on the Chicago Board of Trade after a dry weekend in 
the Midwest. 
</P>
<P>
	In some cases, soybeans jumped as much as a quarter a bushel.  
</P>
<P>
	Though temperatures dropped to the low 90s and 80s in much of  
the growing region, analysts say soybean and corn traders are 
particularly concerned about forecasts calling for little or no 
rain this week. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts say wheat prices also caught a ride upward on the fast  
market. 
</P>
<P>
	In early trading, wheat for December delivery rose 13 1/4 cents to  
$2.93 a bushel; December corn climbed 11 3/4 cents to $2.26 1/4 a bushel; 
December oats rose 5 1/4 cents to $1.17 a bushel; and November 
soybeans jumped 24 3/4 cents to $4.58 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Livestock and meat futures were mixed in early trading on the  
Chicago Mercantile Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	October live cattle rose .45 cent to 64.82 cents a pound;  
September feeder cattle fell .37 cent to 76.75 cents a pound; 
September lean hogs rose 2 cents to 45.35 cents a pound; and August 
pork bellies rose the limit 3 cents to 55.12 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
