<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GM Brake Problem Halts Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- An unresolved problem with brakes on some General  
Motors Corp. pickup trucks and sport utility vehicles forced the 
automaker to shut down assembly plants in Linden, N.J., and 
Shreveport, La., on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The plants produce the Chevrolet S-10, GMC Sonoma and Isuzu  
Hombre pickups. The New Jersey plant also makes the two-door 
Chevrolet Blazer and GMC Jimmy SUVs. 
</P>
<P>
	Workers assembling the light trucks discovered brake fluid was  
leaking, and the source of the problem could not be immediately 
determined, according to a GM source who spoke on condition of 
anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	The problem was found only on two-wheel-drive models and no  
defective trucks left the plant, the source said. 
</P>
<P>
	Production was slowed on Friday and halted Monday. GM said it  
could not estimate when production might resume. Production of the 
four-door Blazer and Jimmy at GM's plant in Moraine, Ohio, was 
unaffected. 
</P>
<P>
	Shreveport has about 2,200 hourly workers, while Linden employs  
about 2,400. Skilled trade and salaried workers remained on the 
job. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
