<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sega Says Dreamcast Orders Are Brisk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Sega Enterprises Ltd.'s future in the home  
video-game business may come down to one thing: Will its new 
Dreamcast video gaming system be a best seller? 
</P>
<P>
	Already, there are signs that consumer demand is there. The  
company was expected to announce today that it has taken more than 
200,000 pre-orders for the $199 new system, which will hit store 
shelves Sept. 9. 
</P>
<P>
	While the orders are coming in well ahead of expectations,  
analysts still warn that the initial hype over the new console 
doesn't guarantee a long-term hit for the company that once led the 
video game business. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think they will have a strong year and a very strong  
Christmas,'' said Sean McGowan, an analyst at the investment firm 
Gerard Klauer Mattison. ``But the question is: `Will they be able 
to continue the momentum after that?''' 
</P>
<P>
	For Tokyo-based Sega, which had a hit with its Genesis system in  
the early 1990s, much rests on Dreamcast's success. Its Saturn 
gaming console bombed five years ago, and the company now lags a 
distant third behind Sony and Nintendo. Saturn had fewer games than 
its rivals and was less powerful than Nintendo 64. 
</P>
<P>
	Sony currently accounts for about 60 percent of the U.S. market  
for video game machines with its PlayStation system, while Nintendo 
holds more than 30 percent; Sega has less than 5 percent, analysts 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	A big hit with Dreamcast could again make Sega a serious player  
in the video-game business. But a flop could wipe it out of the 
home gaming market for good. 
</P>
<P>
	``What Sega has to prove with Dreamcast is that we can have  
success in the U.S. market,'' said Charles Bellfield, director of 
marketing at Sega of America, based in Redwood City, Calif. ``The 
Saturn launch here was a failure, and now we need to show that 
we've learned from our past.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With so much riding on the Dreamcast, Sega is spending more than  
$100 million on marketing and advertising. Starting in mid-July, it 
took the unusual step of offering the public the opportunity to 
rent out the new system at 1,000 Hollywood Video stores. 
</P>
<P>
	Sega hopes to convince consumers that its next-generation  
128-bit system is far more advanced than anything currently on the 
market and will provide a more exciting gaming experience. 
</P>
<P>
	Dreamcast is the first to include Internet capabilities. With a  
modem in its base, consumers will be able to play games online, as 
well as e-mail, chat and browse the Web. It also features advanced 
3-D graphics and sophisticated sound. 
</P>
<P>
	So far, demand has been surprisingly strong. Retailers are  
shocked by the number of pre-orders they have received. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been in this business for 14 years and this is the  
biggest product that I have ever been involved in,'' said Peter 
Roithmayr, vice president of merchandise for video games at 
Electronics Boutique, which has more than 500 stores in North 
America. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is the largest pre-sell ever and we think that the day it  
launches will be the biggest day in sales in the history of the 
company,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Doreen McKenzie, who heads video games merchandising at the  
480-store Babbage's Etc. chain, said consumers are not only 
attracted to Dreamcast's technology but also by the 16 games that 
Sega will make available at the launch -- something serious gamers 
look for when buying a new system. 
</P>
<P>
	``That is more than I've ever seen before when a new system has  
been launched,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	While Sega is eager to tout its hefty pre-orders, analysts still  
question whether Dreamcast's sales momentum will can continue into 
2000. 
</P>
<P>
	In Japan, where Dreamcast hit stores almost a year ago, sales  
are well below expectations. That led Moody's Investors Service to 
downgrade Sega's debt rating last week, saying that ``Sega's 
earnings and cash flow remain under pressure.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, many analysts say Dreamcast's sales will come under  
pressure as new systems from Sony and Nintendo come to market. 
Sony's PlayStation II will be in U.S. stores by the fall of 2000, 
while Nintendo's next platform should be available in 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	Lastly, Sony and Nintendo are expected to drop the price of  
their existing systems -- Playstation and N64 -- from $129 to $99 at 
the end of August in an attempt to steal some sales from the 
Dreamcast launch. 
</P>
<P>
	``The buzz around Dreamcast is good and they've already locked  
in a good Christmas,'' said McGowan, the toy industry analyst. 
``They have a number of games that look much better than anything 
that is out there now. But new competition isn't far away.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
