<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                           *Leo V. Berger    	
</P>
<P>
	MIAMI BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- Leo V. Berger, one of the country's  
biggest shipping magnates, who helped revitalize the U.S. merchant 
marine fleet, died of a heart attack July 24. He was 78. 
</P>
<P>
	Berger began working to rebuild America's dying international  
shipping business in 1967 with the federally subsidized purchase of 
an oil tanker for $1.5 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Over the years, Berger built up his Apex Marine Corp. of Lake  
Success, N.Y., which had an estimated $100 million annual revenue 
and a fleet of 24 ships at its high point in the mid-1980s. 
</P>
<P>
	As the market soured in recent years, Berger began selling  
ships. He sold two to the U.S. Navy and helped transform them into 
1,100-bed hospitals serving American troops. The ships are still in 
service. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hungarian immigrant came to the United States with his  
family in 1928 and settled in New York City. He was inducted into 
the U.S. Merchant Marine's Hall of Distinguished Graduates last 
year. 

</P>
<P>
                         *Nirad C. Chaudhuri    	
</P>
<P>
	OXFORD, England (AP) -- Nirad C. Chaudhuri, the Indian-born  
author and scholar who was acclaimed abroad but scorned in the 
Subcontinent, died Sunday. He was 101. 
</P>
<P>
	Chaudhuri made his entry into the scene of scholarly literature  
in 1951 with the publication of ``The Autobiography of an Unknown 
Indian,'' a memoir of his childhood in colonial India, in what is 
now Bangladesh. The thick memoir included lively, insightful 
descriptions of Indian customs, castes and relations with the 
British. 
</P>
<P>
	As a barefoot boy, he read Shakespeare alongside Sanskrit  
classics, and the memoirs were somewhat sympathetic to the 
unpopular 200 years of British rule. Critics called him the last 
British imperialist. 
</P>
<P>
	At the age of 90 he wrote a second 1,000-page tome of  
autobiography, ``Thy Hand, Great Anarch.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His last book of essays, ``Three Horsemen of the New  
Apocalypse,'' was written when he was 99. It was an indictment of 
what he called India's failed leadership and a lament for the 
decline of the country. He also concluded after 30 years in Oxford 
that England did not deserve itself. 

</P>
<P>
                         *Porfirio Delgado    	
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Candelas Guitars co-founder Porfirio Delgado,  
whose firm made instruments for such musicians as Los Panchos, Los 
Diamantes, Los Lobos, Jose Feliciano and Andres Segovia, died 
Wednesday. He was 85 and had recently suffered a heart attack. 
</P>
<P>
	Delgado and older brother, Candelario, who died in 1983, opened  
Candelas Guitars in East Los Angeles in 1948. It is currently run 
by Delgado's grandsons, Tomas and Manuel. 

</P>
<P>
                       *Reginald E. Kavanaugh    	
</P>
<P>
	EAST BRUNSWICK, N.J. (AP) -- Reginald E. Kavanaugh, a longtime  
court reporter for The Home News, died Saturday of a pulmonary 
embolism. He was 72. 
</P>
<P>
	Kavanaugh was a reporter at the newspaper for 43 years, 35 of  
which were spent covering the Middlesex County Courthouse. 
</P>
<P>
	Born in New Hampshire, Kavanaugh lived in several places as a  
child. He served in the Army during World War II. After the war, he 
returned to East Orange and graduated from Rutgers University in 
1951. While at Rutgers, Kavanaugh began working at what was then 
The Daily Home News of New Brunswick. 
</P>
<P>
	Kavanaugh won a National Headliner award in 1965 for writing a  
series of articles on drug use among young people, and also 
received awards from the New Jersey Press Association and Sigma 
Delta Chi. 
</P>
<P>
	He retired from The Home News in 1993.  
</P>
<P>
	Survivors include his wife, a sister, a niece and four nephews.  

</P>
<P>
                        *Bastiaan J.D. Meeuse    	
</P>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Bastiaan J.D. Meeuse, a professor emeritus of  
botany at the University of Washington who researched a 
particularly malodorous type of lily for more than 50 years, died 
Tuesday of pneumonia. He was 83. 
</P>
<P>
	Meeuse wrote more than 200 articles on the voodoo lily, a  
relative of the ``corpse flower'' that came into rare bloom last 
month at the university, and other plants. 
</P>
<P>
	He discovered a moss enzyme that oxidizes oxalic acid. Now the  
enzyme helps monitor blood in people who produce excess oxalic 
acid, which can cause deadly crystals in their kidneys. 
</P>
<P>
	But his passion remained researching the heat-and-stench  
generating pollination phase of the voodoo lily. 
</P>
<P>
	He once said the negative part of his choice was that his work  
would leave him with ``an odor that would drive skunks away.'' 

</P>
<P>
                       *Gregory Charles Minor    	
</P>
<P>
	TELLURIDE, Colo. (AP) -- Gregory Charles Minor, an engineer who  
quit General Electric's reactor division in the 1970s to protest 
nuclear power, died July 20 of leukemia. He was 62. 
</P>
<P>
	Minor and two other middle-management engineers, Richard Hubbard  
and Dale Bridenbough, quit General Electric in 1976, saying they 
believed nuclear power presented a profound threat to mankind. 
</P>
<P>
	``My reason for leaving is a deep conviction that nuclear  
reactors and nuclear weapons now present a serious danger to the 
future of all life on this planet,'' Minor said at the time. 
</P>
<P>
	The three engineers, who spent most of their careers building  
reactors, testified before Congress that because they had become so 
specialized they could no longer see the big picture. As a result, 
no one was in control. 
</P>
<P>
	The three engineers, championed by the anti-nuclear movement,  
founded MHB Technical Associates in San Jose, Calif., where they 
spent the next two decades conducting studies and testifying on the 
safety, reliability, construction and economics of power plants. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Gilbert Mustin    	
</P>
<P>
	BRYN MAWR, Pa. (AP) -- Gilbert Barclay Mustin, the president of  
Fleer Corp., one of the largest baseball trading card companies in 
the country and creator of Dubble Bubble chewing gum, died July 28 
of pneumonia. He was 78. 
</P>
<P>
	Mustin was the grandson of Frank Fleer, who founded Fleer in  
Philadelphia in the 1880s. The company made confections including 
Chiclets gum. 
</P>
<P>
	Fleer is believed to have invented bubble gum in 1928. Company  
accountant Walter Diemer is often credited with accidentally 
inventing the product, which Fleer sold under the name Dubble 
Bubble. 
</P>
<P>
	Mustin started at Fleer in 1949 and became its president in  
1959. By then, the company was in stiff competition with Topps, 
makers of Bazooka bubble gum. Topps dominated the baseball trading 
card business because the Federal Trade Commission had upheld 
Topps' exclusive contracts with pro baseball players for the use of 
their pictures on cards packaged with the gum. 
</P>
<P>
	Fleer, which had long sold trading cards of movie stars and  
other personalities with its gum, began a long antitrust suit 
against Topps in 1975. In 1983, the companies reached an out of 
court settlement that allowed Fleer to sell baseball cards but not 
with gum. 
</P>
<P>
	Mustin retired in 1989, the year Fleer was sold to Marvel  
Entertainment. Fleer was sold again this year to a group of private 
investors and renamed Fleer Skybox of Mount Laurel, N.J. 

</P>
<P>
                         *Viktor Posuvalyuk    	
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Viktor Posuvalyuk, Russia's main envoy to the  
Middle East, died early Sunday. He was 59. 
</P>
<P>
	Posuvalyuk, a deputy foreign minister, died after a long  
illness, the ITAR-Tass news agency reported. 
</P>
<P>
	An expert in Middle Eastern affairs, Posuvalyuk joined the  
Russian diplomatic corps in 1964. He served in embassies in Yemen, 
Iraq and Syria before becoming Russia's ambassador to Oman in 1988 
and Iraq in 1990. 
</P>
<P>
	After returning to Moscow in 1992 to head the Foreign Ministry's  
Department of Africa and the Near East, he shuttled between Baghdad 
and Moscow in efforts to defuse several crises around Iraq, and 
took part in negotiations to advance the Mideast peace process. 

</P>
<P>
                            *Clint Youle    	
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Clint Youle, one of the first men to present the  
weather on television and a former Illinois legislator, died July 
23. He was 83. 
</P>
<P>
	Youle's television career began in 1948 when producers at NBC in  
Chicago decided to produce daily weather reports. He volunteered to 
use meteorology expertise he had gained during World War II and was 
first to present the weather on a national news program when he 
appeared on ``The Camel News Caravan'' with John Cameron Swayze in 
1949. 
</P>
<P>
	Youle, who became known as Mr. Weatherman, used a Rand McNally  
map covered with Plexiglas and marked weather systems using a black 
marker as he gave the forecast. He retired from television in 1959. 
</P>
<P>
	Youle was elected to the Illinois Legislature in 1964. He  
received the second largest number of votes on the Republican 
ticket because of his name recognition, said his son, John. 
</P>
<P>
	Youle also owned several newspapers and worked as an investment  
banker. 
</P>
<P>
	He retired in 1977 to his family's 200-acre homestead in Scales  
Mound in Jo Daviess County. 
</P>
<P>
	He is survived by his wife, a son, two daughters and a sister.  


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
