<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 09:00:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Texas Governor To Fight Subpoena </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- Gov. George W. Bush denies he played a role in the  
firing of a state worker who was investigating allegations of 
misconduct at funeral homes owned by a company whose chairman is a 
longtime Bush family supporter. 
</P>
<P>
	The Republican presidential candidate was subpoenaed to testify  
in a whistle-blower lawsuit filed by Eliza May, former executive 
director of the Funeral Service Commission, against Houston-based 
Service Corporation International. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush will file court documents by Friday asking a judge to  
reject demands that he testify, press secretary Linda Edwards said 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush's testimony is not needed because he knows nothing about  
the investigation or Ms. May's dismissal, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The governor has no personal knowledge of this situation,''  
Edwards said. ``The governor's office did not attempt to influence 
this investigation in any way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. May, who until last summer was treasurer of the Texas  
Democratic Party, was fired in February after leading her agency's 
investigation into embalming practices at 20 SCI funeral homes. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. May's lawsuit alleges that SCI, whose political action  
committee gave Bush $35,000 in 1996 and 1997, worked with Bush's 
staff to interfere with the investigation. The inquiry led to a 
recommended fine of $445,000 against the company, which owns 3,700 
funeral homes worldwide. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. May contends that Bush had her fired at the urging of Robert  
Waltrip, SCI chairman and longtime Bush family supporter. 
</P>
<P>
	A governor is granted broad immunity from such actions. But the  
lawsuit lists Bush as a conspirator while Waltrip, SCI and the 
Texas Funeral Service Commission are defendants. 
</P>
<P>
	Some legal experts said Bush could lose his battle to kill the  
subpoena because of precedents set in President Clinton's dispute 
with Paula Corbin Jones, The Dallas Morning News reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge handling the case will determine whether Bush  
``actually knows something or if the plaintiff's lawyers are simply 
trying to embarrass a presidential candidate,'' said Emory 
University law professor Frank Vandall, an expert on whistle-blower 
litigation. 
</P>
<P>
	``But if he testifies, he better make sure everything --  
absolutely everything -- he says is truthful, because people are 
going to examine every word and its meaning,'' said Vandall. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
