<HEADLINE> Man Convicted of 4 Murders Escapes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- A man serving a life sentence for killing four  
teen-agers opened the window in his cell, sneaked across a grassy 
yard and wriggled through a fence to escape from a maximum-security 
prison Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Police started searching for Norman Johnston on Monday morning  
after workers at the state prison in Huntingdon noticed the fence 
was loose and guards discovered sections of his cell's window had 
been taken apart, said prison spokeswoman Diana G. Baney. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnston, 48, was convicted in 1980 of committing the killings  
to cover up a multimillion-dollar burglary ring he ran with his two 
brothers. The film ``At Close Range,'' starring Sean Penn, was 
based on the case. 
</P>
<P>
	The prison, which holds more than 1,800 inmates, is next to a  
residential neighborhood in Huntingdon, about 100 miles east of 
Pittsburgh. A car was stolen Monday morning from a house across 
from the prison, but police didn't find any fingerprints at the 
scene. 
</P>
<P>
	It wasn't clear when Johnston escaped, although guards last saw  
him at 1 a.m., Ms. Baney said. Officials wouldn't give details on 
the window's construction or how it was dismantled. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnston's brothers, Bruce and David, were also convicted of  
killing the teen-agers and were also sentenced to life. Joe 
Carroll, a prosecutor who worked on the case, said the victims 
belonged to a group that gave the brothers stolen car parts to 
resell. 
</P>
<P>
	Bruce Johnston was also convicted of killing two potential  
witnesses. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
