<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> State Food Stamp Rules Found Unfair </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Some state and local governments have unfairly  
discouraged poor families from applying for food stamps, which 
contributed to a steep drop in the number of people getting the 
help, congressional investigators say. 
</P>
<P>
	A report released Monday by the General Accounting Office also  
faulted the Agriculture Department for failing to monitor the 
food-stamp program adequately and being too slow to write new 
regulations. 
</P>
<P>
	``There has to be a major educational campaign, and the states  
have to actively inform people of available programs,'' said Rep. 
Sander Levin, D-Mich., who requested the investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Food stamp participation has dropped by 27 percent over the past  
3 1/2 years to 18.5 million people. 
</P>
<P>
	While the drop is due largely to the strong economy and changes  
in eligibility requirements, demand has grown for food aid from 
other programs and nonprofit organizations. The report said that 
indicates families who need food stamps aren't getting them. 
</P>
<P>
	The number of children who get federally subsidized free lunches  
increased 6 percent from 1994 through 1997, while the number of 
children on food stamps dropped by 18 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal judge barred New York City this year from requiring a  
person to look for a job before applying for food stamps. Michigan 
was denying food stamps illegally to whole households when only one 
family member violated welfare regulations, said the GAO, Congress' 
investigative and auditing arm. 
</P>
<P>
	Other states and local governments have not publicized  
differences in eligibility requirements for welfare and food 
stamps, the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	USDA, meanwhile, has not written regulations to implement  
changes in the food-stamp program that Congress enacted three years 
ago and has yet to review application procedures in 10 states, the 
investigators said. 
</P>
<P>
	USDA officials say they will finish the regulations by the end  
of the year and are working on the state reviews. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is a great deal of confusion among working families,  
simply because they have gone to work and they don't know what 
their eligibility status is anymore,'' said Shirley Watkins, USDA's 
undersecretary for food, nutrition and consumer services. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, President Clinton announced the administration would  
streamline reporting rules for food stamp recipients and launch an 
educational campaign aimed at getting the working poor to sign up. 
</P>
<P>
	Nationwide, two of five working families eligible for food  
stamps actually apply for the assistance, according to USDA. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
