<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bus Driver in Louisiana Crash Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- The driver of a charter bus that crashed on  
Mother's Day, killing 22 people en route to a Gulf Coast casino, 
has died of heart failure, officials said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Frank Bedell, who had a history of heart disease and kidney  
problems, was suffering from cardiopulmonary arrest when he was 
brought to Charity Hospital on Sunday, hospital spokesman Jerry 
Romig said. He died at 9:11 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
	Bedell, 46, had been hospitalized for about a month after the  
May 5 crash. 
</P>
<P>
	Police last week sent results of their investigation into the  
crash to prosecutors, but Bedell's death means no criminal charges 
will be filed in the case. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our case was based on him as a driver and whether he was  
responsible or not,'' said Zully Jimenez, a spokeswoman for Orleans 
Parish District Attorney Harry Connick. ``It couldn't have been 
anything else.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Federal investigators have said there is no evidence to indicate  
the bus had mechanical problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Following the crash, authorities said they had found evidence  
that Bedell had lost two bus-driving jobs because of marijuana use, 
had failed a test for cocaine and was undergoing kidney dialysis. A 
personnel file contained a doctor's note saying Bedell had 
congestive heart disease, a condition that should have disqualified 
him from a commercial license, federal officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bedell had refused to be interviewed by investigators.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
