<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> John Huang's Hearing Postponed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A hearing for former Democratic Party  
fund-raiser John Huang was postponed Monday when a Republican 
congressman demanded that Huang testify before Congress prior to 
making a court plea bargain. 
</P>
<P>
	Huang, the Democrats' chief fund-raiser for the Asian-American  
community in 1996, brought in $1.6 million in questionable 
donations that later were returned. He has been cooperating with 
Justice Department investigators in their campaign finance probe. 
</P>
<P>
	The former executive of Jakarta-based Lippo Group, accused of  
making illegal campaign contributions, was scheduled to appear in 
federal court Monday to resolve his case. 
</P>
<P>
	Government prosecutors had recommended he be fined $10,000 and  
sentenced to 500 hours of community service. He could have been 
sentenced to jail for five years. 
</P>
<P>
	But Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind., chairman of the House Committee on  
Government Reform, wrote to U.S. District Judge Richard Paez asking 
for an indefinite delay. 
</P>
<P>
	Thom Mrozek, spokesman for the U.S. Attorney's office in Los  
Angeles, said Paez delayed the hearing until Aug. 12 and ordered 
attorneys in the case to begin submitting legal briefs on whether 
Huang's case should be postponed indefinitely. 
</P>
<P>
	Burton's press secretary, Mark Corallo, said Burton's concerns  
were covered in a July 28 letter he wrote to U.S. Attorney General 
Janet Reno. In that letter, Burton said he would seek postponing of 
sentences for both Huang and Democratic fund-raiser Charlie Trie 
because they had not yet testified before Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, the federal government asked that Trie's sentencing  
be postponed at least six weeks so that Trie's cooperation with the 
government can be assessed. 
</P>
<P>
	Trie has pleaded guilty to two counts involving campaign finance  
violations, one a felony and the other a misdemeanor, and pledged 
to cooperate in an investigation of campaign fund-raising. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors have recommended that Trie be given three years'  
probation. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
