<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cubans Shrug Off Defections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HAVANA (AP) -- Cuban baseball fans seemed to care little that  
some of their athletes, even a baseball player, defected during the 
Pan American Games. 
</P>
<P>
	Crowded around televisions in living rooms to watch Cuba beat  
the United States 5-1 Monday night for the gold medal in baseball, 
the only important thing was who stayed -- and played. 
</P>
<P>
	``Orestes Kindelan, home run!'' Teresa Menendez shouted at the  
small color television set in her modest living room as the slugger 
hit one of two during the game. ``That's the way to do it. Go, 
Cuba!'' 
</P>
<P>
	Menendez and her family shrugged off news that 19-year-old  
pitcher Danys Baez left the team on Sunday; some said they were not 
convinced it was true. 
</P>
<P>
	``The ballplayers never stay behind,'' said Menendez as she sat  
on the linoleum floor of the front room, scrunched between 
relatives and neighbors while a skeletal floor fan built from scrap 
metal and a washing machine motor hummed nearby. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even if it is true, we would have no way of knowing,'' added  
her 34-year-old son, Alejandro Duarte, an unemployed tourism worker 
who watched the win from a carved wooden rocking chair in his 
Adidas swim trunks. ``These things never come out on television or 
in the press here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Because all national media is controlled by the communist  
government, Cubans generally learn of such things through calls 
from relatives in the United States, unconfirmed rumors passed 
among co-workers and neighbors, or reports on the U.S. government's 
Radio Marti. 
</P>
<P>
	It wasn't until a few days ago that the Menendez-Duarte family  
heard about the defection of a group of Cuban basketball players in 
Puerto Rico last month. ``Oh, I thought that was in Winnipeg,'' 
commented a young neighbor. 
</P>
<P>
	Because baseball is Cuba's national sport, and because the  
players are considered especially loyal to President Fidel Castro, 
the defection of Baez was sure to sting more than the others. 
</P>
<P>
	Baez's departure brought to eight the number of Cubans to leave  
that nation's delegation during the games. Runner Michal Ortiz and 
shooter Abel Juncosa Reyes were among the others. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the gold medal win was likely to overshadow the  
defections in a country where baseball is so important that Castro 
postponed by one day a major speech originally scheduled for Monday 
evening. 
</P>
<P>
	Starter Jose Contreras pitched on one day's rest, fanning eight  
straight in the first three innings and allowing four hits in 
eight. He struck out 13. 
</P>
<P>
	The win, and Cuba's complaints that both Canada and the United  
States have been provoking the defections, were sure to come up 
during Castro's major speech Tuesday night in the central province 
of Matanzas. 
</P>
<P>
	During another speech on July 26, Castro complained at length  
how the Cuban delegation has been treated during the games. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have never seen so many tricks, so much filth in the Pan  
American Games,'' he said. ``We are competing in enemy territory.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Since then, Cuban sports officials in Winnipeg have protested  
the ``provocations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	During Cuba's 3-2 baseball semifinal victory over Canada, a man  
carrying a sign saying ``Human Right First,'' rushed onto the 
field. He eventually was decked by second baseman Juan Padilla and 
taken off by security. 
</P>
<P>
	``Cuban athletes will not permit anyone or anything to humiliate  
them ... if their dignity is at stake,'' said a statement from the 
Cuban delegation. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
