<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 10:10:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Construction Spending Rebounds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Construction spending rebounded slightly in  
June, rising 0.5 percent, after falling in two straight months. 
</P>
<P>
	The Commerce Department said today that spending rose to a  
seasonally adjusted annual rate of $699.4 billion, following drops 
of 1.4 percent in both May and in April. 
</P>
<P>
	The increases were fairly widespread with gains reported in  
office buildings, industrial buildings, hotels and motels and big 
government projects. However, spending on all residential 
construction fell 0.3 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The increase in overall construction spending was in line with  
many analysts' expectations. 
</P>
<P>
	And, in a separate report today, a survey of purchasing managers  
said the U.S. manufacturing sector grew in July for the sixth 
consecutive month, but not as strongly as most analysts expected. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Association of Purchasing Management said its  
monthly index of manufacturing activity registered 53.4 percent in 
July, compared with 57 percent in June. Figures above 50 percent 
indicate growth. 
</P>
<P>
	The purchasing managers group, which represents executives who  
buy raw materials and supplies for industry, also reported a 
slightly stronger rise in July raw-material prices than in June. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial markets, which had lost some ground last week over  
worries that the Federal Reserve would raise interest rates again, 
possibly as early as this month, rebounded today. 
</P>
<P>
	The markets were reacting positively to the purchasing managers'  
report, which suggested the economy has not expanded quite as fast 
as market watchers had feared, analysts said. The Dow Jones 
industrial average was up 125 points at midday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The report put a damper on any plan by the Fed to immediately  
raise interest rates,'' said Wells Fargo economist Sung Won Sohn, 
adding that the report is closely watched by Federal Reserve 
Chairman Alan Greenspan. But a report on the nation's employment, 
out this week, is likely to figure prominently into the Fed's 
decision making, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The purchasing managers' report shows that the manufacturing  
sector, hard hit by a global financial crisis, ``is taking a little 
bit longer to get up to speed and indicates that Asia and Latin 
America are not back to their full health,'' Sohn said. 
</P>
<P>
	Home building and other construction activity, driven by low  
mortgage rates, were a key contributing factor to the strong 
economic growth in the early part of the year. But the pace of 
construction spending has cooled. Construction of new homes and 
apartments, for instance, plunged in June to the lowest level in 
just over a year. 
</P>
<P>
	Builders and analysts largely blame this on shortages of skilled  
workers and some building materials, such as gypsum wallboard, 
insulation and, in some markets, bricks, which can delay 
construction schedules. 
</P>
<P>
	However, sales of existing homes hit a record high in June and  
new-home sales also went up as buyers scrambled to lock in the best 
deals to beat slowly advancing mortgage rates. The average interest 
rate on a 30-year fixed rate mortgage last week was 7.70 percent, 
up from 7.52 percent the week before. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Reserve nudged up interest rates June 30 in a  
pre-emptive strike against inflation. However, Greenspan has said 
the central bank is prepared to act again at the first glimpse of 
inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	The construction report showed that spending on all private  
construction projects rose 0.6 percent in June, after having 
reported declines in May and April, and was the main factor in the 
overall gain in June's construction spending. Private construction 
spending totaled $550 billion, on a seasonally adjusted annualized 
basis, in June. 
</P>
<P>
	Spending on government construction projects also rebounded in  
June, rising 0.2 percent to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 
$149.4 billion, after having fallen three straight months in a row. 
</P>
<P>
	Gains were reported on spending on schools and other educational  
buildings, conservation and development projects and water supply 
facilities. But spending on highways and streets and public housing 
projects was down. 
</P>
<P>
	However, spending on all residential projects fell 0.3 percent  
in June to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of $322 billion. 
Spending on single-family homes reported a decline, but spending on 
apartments rose just a little. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
