<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> SEC Accuses UnitedHealth Executive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- The U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission  
has accused an executive of UnitedHealth Group of making more than 
$274,000 through illegal insider trading while United was 
negotiating to acquire MetraHealth Cos. in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	The government alleges that Michael Mooney, now the company's  
senior vice president-health care and economics, had nonpublic 
information about the merger plan when he purchased options to buy 
company stock. 
</P>
<P>
	The SEC alleges that Mooney was United's vice president of  
underwriting and part of the due diligence team that was reviewing 
the potential acquisition when he traded in United stock options 
several times during May and June of 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	The SEC says Mooney paid a total of $258,283 for options he  
later sold for $532,482, more than twice the purchase price. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to violating the Securities Exchange Act of 1934,  
the SEC complaint alleged the trades violated the insider trading 
policy of the Minnetonka-based operator of managed health care 
plans, which then was called United HealthCare Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	The complaint says Mooney told United officials that he had not  
engaged in any prohibited trading during the MetraHealth 
acquisition talks and did not report the transactions to United's 
legal department. 
</P>
<P>
	Mooney, of Prior Lake, denies the allegations, said his  
attorney, John Hopeman. The attorney said he would not file a 
formal answer and would ask U.S. District Judge James Rosenbaum to 
dismiss the complaint. 
</P>
<P>
	Hopeman said the complaint is part of an ongoing legal dispute  
regarding what standard the SEC should use to define insider 
trading. 
</P>
<P>
	``The SEC wants very badly for this to be this rule which says  
if you possess information you can't trade, period. They're 
fighting this battle around the country,'' Hopeman said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hopeman believes the SEC must prove that insider information  
prompted Mooney's decision to trade. 
</P>
<P>
	``He didn't know that there was going to be a merger, but it  
didn't matter to him. He wasn't trading on that basis. He was 
trading on the basis of a separate investment strategy,'' Hopeman 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``He'd been trading in company stock for nine years and they  
have never questioned his trades before and this one's like many of 
the others. We're kind of at a loss,'' Hopeman said. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
