<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Eagles Fans Cheer McNabb at Camp </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BETHLEHEM, Pa. (AP) -- Now that contract negotiations are over,  
Donovan McNabb has some catching up to do. He wasted no time during 
his first day on the field at Eagles training camp. 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Andy Reid gave the team's top draft pick plenty of  
practice reps Sunday as McNabb begins the process of learning 
Philadelphia's new West Coast offense. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't feel like it's going to take me long to catch up,''  
said McNabb, who worked primarily with the second unit. ``I think 
the timing is pretty low right now. The receivers I worked out with 
(when he was unsigned) didn't have the speed or the route running 
that these guys have. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just an adjustment period that you go through when you  
report to camp. I'm patient and I'm just going to continue working 
on my conditioning,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	McNabb, taken with the second overall pick in the April draft,  
completed a hectic first weekend with the team. McNabb and the 
Eagles agreed to terms Friday on a seven-year contract worth $54 
million, including an $11.3 million signing bonus, but it wasn't 
until late Saturday that the 32-page contract was approved by the 
league offices and signed by McNabb. 
</P>
<P>
	With that behind him, McNabb stepped onto the field for the  
first time in training camp Sunday, intent on showing he was worth 
the high selection and big money. 
</P>
<P>
	He even heard his first cheers from Philadelphia fans after his  
selection was booed on draft day. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was rewarding to hear the fans cheer and clap for every  
completion that I had,'' McNabb said. ``They seemed to get excited 
about it. That helps out all the players.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reid is just glad McNabb is finally in camp.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm glad he's working,'' Reid said. ``We're catching him up on  
this thing. We're just working him right into the rotation. There 
were a lot of throws he had a chance to complete and they were 
either off the receiver's body or in a position where that receiver 
couldn't catch the football. 
</P>
<P>
	``The thing that I liked was, he finished strong. He came out  
and he was tired and that arm was tired and he worked that last 
series there and finished with some completions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McNabb goes into camp as the backup to Doug Pederson, already  
familiar with the Eagles offense after working with Reid in Green 
Bay. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
