<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> APME Announces Top Writing Awards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The killings at Columbine High School in  
Littleton, Colo., the dramatic rescue attempt of a fishing vessel 
crew in the Gulf of Alaska and an in-depth look at the tobacco 
industry's creation of a more addictive tobacco won top prizes for 
AP staffers in the Associated Press Managing Editors association's 
writing competition. 
</P>
<P>
	A package of photos on Kosovo by nine AP photographers was cited  
for the best news photography award, and the feature photography 
award went to famine coverage in the Sudan. 
</P>
<P>
	Members of APME's executive committee and board of directors  
selected the winners Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The sea rescue and the tobacco stories were written by AP  
national writer Todd Lewan and won in the feature writing and 
enterprise reporting categories respectively. It was the first time 
an AP staffer has won two writing awards in the annual competition. 
</P>
<P>
	AP's Denver bureau was cited for excellence in deadline coverage  
for the Columbine story. 
</P>
<P>
	Rex Huppke of AP's Indianapolis bureau won the John L. Dougherty  
Award, which recognizes an outstanding reporter with less than 
three years' service with the AP. Dougherty was the longtime 
managing editor of the Rochester (N.Y.) Times-Union and Democrat &AMP; 
Chronicle who died in 1981 while serving as APME treasurer. He was 
known for his emphasis on good writing and nurturing young 
journalists. 
</P>
<P>
	The nine photographers cited for their coverage of Kosovo are  
Peter Dejong, Jerome Delay, Eric Draper, John Gaps III, David 
Guttenfelder, Srdjan Ilic, Santiago Lyon, Enric Marti and Dimitri 
Messinis. 
</P>
<P>
	Honorable mentions were awarded to Khalil Senosi, who is based  
in Nairobi, Kenya, for a photo of the U.S. Embassy bombing in 
Nairobi, and Roberto Borea, of AP's Baltimore bureau, for his photo 
of the Clinton family as they departed the White House for a 
vacation in Martha's Vineyard during the Monica Lewinsky scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	The feature photo award was given to Brennan Linsley for a  
series of photos on famine in the Sudan. 
</P>
<P>
	Honorable mention was given to Guttenfelder for photographs of a  
fashion show in Niger, and to Lebanon photographer Saleh Rifai for 
a photo showing spectators in a building looking through openings 
of a large portrait of the late Iranian leader Ayatollah Khomeni. 
</P>
<P>
	In the writing awards, honorable mention in deadline coverage  
was awarded to Niko Price and Ken Guggenheim for stories out of 
Honduras and Nicaragua on the destruction done by Hurricane Mitch, 
which killed more than 9,000 people when it hit Central America in 
October. 
</P>
<P>
	Karin Davies was awarded honorable mention in the deadline  
category for coverage of the August bombing of the U.S. Embassy in 
Nairobi. 
</P>
<P>
	Honorable mention in feature writing went to national writer  
Helen O'Neill for her account of the first tourist dive in a small 
submarine to the wreck of the Titanic, and Marta Aldrich of AP's 
Nashville, Tenn., bureau for ``Roy's Walk,'' an account of how a 
3-year-old boy's wandering away from home stirred an unusual ``good 
Samaritan'' response. 
</P>
<P>
	In enterprise reporting, honorable mention was given to national  
writer John Hendren for his look at the fire danger in upholstery. 
</P>
<P>
	The writing and photography entries covered the period of July  
1998 through June 1999. They will be presented at APME's national 
conference in Memphis, Tenn., Oct. 13-16. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
