<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Packers' Robert Brooks Retires </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREEN BAY, Wis. (AP) -- Wide receiver Robert Brooks, a fan  
favorite who used to jump into the Lambeau Field stands to 
celebrate touchdown catches from quarterback Brett Favre, announced 
his retirement today, hampered by a painful back injury. 
</P>
<P>
	Brooks said he was hampered by injuries the last two seasons.  
</P>
<P>
	``I thank God for the opportunity He has given me,'' Brooks said  
at a news conference today. ``It was a dream come true to play in 
the NFL.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After a day in training camp, Brooks, 29, skipped workouts for  
two days, creating speculation that he would retire because of 
injuries. Then, this morning, the Packers in conjunction with 
Brooks scheduled a news conference for today. 
</P>
<P>
	Brooks underwent surgery during training camp last year to  
repair a herniated disc. He did not practice again until Oct. 11 
and played in the first five regular-season games. 
</P>
<P>
	The injury bothered him throughout the season. He finished with  
just 31 catches for 420 yards and three touchdowns, having been 
inactive for four games late in the season. 
</P>
<P>
	He had surgery again in January. He agreed to a $1.1 million pay  
cut in June, which the Packers said eased their salary-cap 
restriction. 
</P>
<P>
	Brooks' best season was 1995, when he caught 102 passes after  
the retirement of star receiver Sterling Sharpe. Brooks averaged 
14.7 yards for a team-record 1,497 yards. 
</P>
<P>
	He electrified fans that year by leaping into the outstretched  
arms of fans behind the Lambeau Field end zones to celebrate 
touchdowns, establishing a tradition known as the ``Lambeau leap.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Packers gave him with a five-year, $15 million contract in  
February 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	He injured his right knee against San Francisco in October 1996.  
He returned in 1997 and was named the NFL's ``comeback player of 
the year'' by the Pro Football Writers of America. 
</P>
<P>
	However, by the end of the 1997 season, he developed lower-back  
pain. He participated in every practice during the Packers' 10-day 
minicamp in June this year, raising hopes that he had recovered. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
