<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 18:10:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Vikings' Rookie Skips Practice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MANKATO, Minn. (AP) -- Minnesota Vikings rookie defensive end  
Dimitrius Underwood, the 29th overall draft pick, skipped Monday 
afternoon's practice and team officials did not know why. 
</P>
<P>
	``Dimitrius Underwood has left training camp without  
permission,'' coach Dennis Green said in a prepared statement. 
``The fair thing to do is to concentrate on the players that are 
here and give them all our energy. When there is something further 
to report on Dimitrius, we will.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Defensive coordinator Foge Fazio said the absence was unexcused,  
but that nobody knew why Underwood left after lunch. 
</P>
<P>
	Underwood, drafted out of Michigan State with the Vikings'  
second pick in the first round, worked out in the morning. But he 
was nowhere to be found at the dorm on campus after lunch. A team 
official said Underwood was neither ill nor injured. 
</P>
<P>
	His position coach, Andre Patterson, said the team was trying to  
track down the 6-foot-6, 276-pound rookie who signed a five-year 
contract on Sunday for more than $5 million with a signing bonus of 
$1,750,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Teammates heading to and from dinner declined to discuss  
Underwood's unexplained absence. 
</P>
<P>
	Underwood's agent, Craig Domann of Bolingbrook, Ill., didn't  
return phone calls from The Associated Press seeking comment, and 
Rob Brzezinski, the Vikings' chief negotiator, said he didn't know 
Underwood's whereabouts. 
</P>
<P>
	Before Underwood went AWOL, the Vikings were feeling good about  
having all their players in camp and under contract, including 
their nine draft picks and left guard Randall McDaniel, who 
reported to camp despite the team's unwillingness to renegotiate 
his contract. 
</P>
<P>
	``What's big is that everyone's in camp. Because if you've got  
even one person out of camp, then that becomes an issue and it's as 
big an issue to everyone as it is the other 80 guys that you've got 
in camp,'' owner Red McCombs said. ``So, it's really big to have 
everybody in camp. But to have a guy like Randall is super big 
because that would be the story of the camp if Randall were not in 
camp.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
