<DOCNO> APW19990802.0252 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 17:00:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Steelers' Bettis Undergoes Surgery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LATROBE, Pa. (AP) -- Pittsburgh Steelers running back Jerome  
Bettis had surgery on his left knee Monday, but is expected back 
for the team's season opener. 
</P>
<P>
	Bettis, who re-injured his left knee during private preseason  
workouts nearly two weeks ago in St. Louis, felt some discomfort in 
the knee Monday morning after a hard workout the previous day. He 
had been running on his own since training camp started Friday at 
St. Vincent College. 
</P>
<P>
	An MRI test performed in Pittsburgh on Monday revealed a tear in  
the lateral meniscus cartilage. Bettis later had arthroscopic 
surgery at UPMC-Shadyside in Pittsburgh. 
</P>
<P>
	``The surgery went very well,'' coach Bill Cowher said.  
</P>
<P>
	Bettis should be back within three to four weeks -- plenty of  
time for the Sept. 12 opener at Cleveland, Cowher said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope we're getting all these things out of the way early,  
and we're hoping for a complete recovery,'' Cowher said. 
</P>
<P>
	Cowher said it was unclear whether the new injury was related to  
the knee injury Bettis suffered last season. 
</P>
<P>
	``Whether it's old or new, the most important thing was that the  
prognosis is good for a complete recovery,'' he said. Cowher said 
he was reassured by the fact that Bettis came back in good shape. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't anticipate this setting him back a whole lot,'' Cowher  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bettis was put on the active non-football injury list Friday  
night. That prohibited him from participating in team drills during 
training camp, but he remained in good shape by running on his own 
and lifting weights. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
