<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NASA Reports on X-Ray Telescope </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- NASA's new X-ray telescope is in a  
slightly lower orbit than planned, but it's still acceptable for 
astronomical observations, officials said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	An engine firing over the weekend raised the high point of the  
Chandra X-ray Observatory's orbit to 86,433 miles, about one-third 
of the way to the moon. That's 559 miles lower than intended, but 
still well within the specifications. 
</P>
<P>
	Program manager Fred Wojtalik said one of two engines used to  
boost the telescope performed slightly below expectations. As a 
result, a backup pair of engines will be used to raise the low end 
of Chandra's orbit on Wednesday and again on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Astronauts released the $1.5 billion Chandra Observatory -- the  
world's most powerful X-ray telescope -- from space shuttle Columbia 
on July 23. The observatory will spend the next five years looking 
for black holes and studying stars, galaxies and quasars. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
