<HEADLINE> Suns Re-Sign Clifford Robinson </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- Clifford Robinson has decided to stay in Phoenix  
for $29 million, and the ``Big O'' is back, too. 
</P>
<P>
	Oliver Miller, who began his NBA career with the Suns in 1992,  
returned to the team Sunday when Phoenix signed him to a one-year 
contract. Hours later, the Suns announced they re-signed Robinson 
to a multi-year contract. 
</P>
<P>
	The Associated Press confirmed today that Robinson got a  
four-year, $29 million deal that will pay him about $6 million next 
season, while Miller got the veteran minimum salary of about 
$700,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Robinson had one-year deals with the Suns in 1997-98 and last  
season after playing the first eight seasons of his NBA career with 
Portland. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Robinson ranked in the top 30 in five different  
statistical categories. 
</P>
<P>
	He finished eighth in 3-point goal percentage with a career-high  
42 percent and also had a career-high 1.50 steals per game, which 
ranked 28th in the league. 
</P>
<P>
	Robinson also had 1.18 blocks per game (25th in the league) and  
his highest since 1993-94 and ranked 29th in scoring at 16.4 points 
per game and 29th in field-goal percentage at 47 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	``Cliff has given us two great years and has earned this new  
deal,'' Colangelo said. 
</P>
<P>
	Robinson, 32, signed a $1 million contract with Phoenix in 1997  
and another one-year deal for $3.5 million last season. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm glad to get it done,'' Robinson told The Arizona Republic.  
``Another summer of waiting to see what is going to happen wouldn't 
have worked for me. It's too stressful.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Miller, a free-agent forward and center, played only four games  
with Sacramento last season and spent most of the year on the 
injured list with back spasms. He was hampered by his weight, which 
was a reported 365 pounds. 
</P>
<P>
	The 29-year-old Miller has since lost some 50 pounds and has  
looked impressive for the Suns' entry in the Rocky Mountain Review 
games in Salt Lake City for rookies and free agents. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller averaged 10 points, 8.3 rebounds, 3.3 blocked shots and  
1.3 steals in the first three games including five blocks and 13 
rebounds last Thursday against Houston. 
</P>
<P>
	``Over the last two weeks, Oliver has shown great improvement in  
his physical conditioning and continues to display a desire for a 
fresh start both on and off the basketball floor,'' said Suns 
general manager Bryan Colangelo. ``This signing is the next step in 
Oliver's development.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Miller, who has also played for Detroit, Toronto and Dallas,  
said he wants to be down to 290 pounds by the time training camp 
starts Oct. 4. 
</P>
<P>
	He'd like to stay in the 295-300 range through the season.  
</P>
<P>
	``I've grown up. I've gone through a lot in these past five  
years,'' Miller told reporters last week. ``I'm just going to go 
out and show people that Oliver Miller means business. He still 
loves the game, and he's willing to do whatever is possible to 
win.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
