<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Phillips, Minor League Umps Part </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Richie Phillips parted ways with minor league  
umpires on Monday, although they disagreed on whether he was fired 
or quit. 
</P>
<P>
	While Phillips said he resigned because more than two dozen  
minor leaguers agreed to become permanent replacements in the 
majors on Sept. 1, two minor league umps, speaking on the condition 
they not be identified, said he was fired following a vote last 
weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	``We said from the beginning that if a significant number of  
minor league umpires decided or indicated they would work as 
replacement umpires, we could no longer represent them,'' Phillips 
said. ``We're very happy to have helped them to form the union. We 
wished them great luck.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Phillips, the head of the major league umpires since 1978, said  
the big league umps will file unfair labor practice charges against 
the American and National leagues on Tuesday in New York. He will 
ask the National Labor Relations Board to seek an injunction in 
federal court to prevent baseball from forcing out 22 umpires on 
Sept. 2. 
</P>
<P>
	``They engaged in a pattern of acts purposefully designed to  
break the umpires,'' Phillips said. ``It's part of a cynical 
strategy to undermine the unions that keep the game of baseball 
alive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The NLRB usually takes 4-to-6 weeks to investigate, meaning a  
decision is likely to come near the end of the regular season. If 
the New York regional director finds the case has merit and the 
agency's general counsel in Washington issues a complaint, the NLRB 
board could grant permission for its staff to seek a court order 
forcing baseball to take back the umpires. 
</P>
<P>
	In a similar process five years ago, baseball players filed  
charges and the NLRB won an injunction against owners that caused 
the union to end its 7 1/2-month strike. 
</P>
<P>
	Major league umpires are battling for a new labor contract to  
replace the one that expires Dec. 31, and their mass resignation 
tactic, aimed at forcing the start of negotiations, backfired when 
27 of the 68 either didn't resign or withdrew their resignations. 
</P>
<P>
	Baseball then hired 25 new umpires from the minor leagues,  
including many who had been vacation fill-ins, and told 22 major 
league umps their resignations had been accepted. 
</P>
<P>
	Phillips had been trying to organize the minor league umpires  
since last spring. 
</P>
<P>
	The minor leaguers still intend to unionize and will seek  
another lawyer, according to the two umpires. While Phillips said 
two weeks ago he would ask the NLRB to hold an election to certify 
the minor league union, he has not done so. Some of the minor 
leaguers have said they thought he was using them as leverage. 
</P>
<P>
	Some major league umps want to fire Phillips as their  
negotiator. Fourteen of the 66 unionized umpires issued a statement 
last week criticizing their leadership. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the American League confirmed it had accepted the  
resignations of umpires Drew Coble and Greg Kosc, effective Sept. 
2. According to management officials, the pair resigned last month, 
withdrew their resignations, then resigned again. Coble and Kosc 
maintain they didn't resign. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was indeed some confusion about their status,'' Phyllis  
Merhige, the AL's senior vice president, said Monday. ``Each of 
them were called by league officials and each of them confirmed 
their resignations. Now it's with the lawyers.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990802.0264 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 09:40:28 </DATE_TIME>
