<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 03:30:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NFL Camps Roundup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREEN BAY, Wis. (AP) -- Green Bay general manager Ron Wolf  
offered assurances that the Packers have replacements if they lose 
wide receiver Robert Brooks. 
</P>
<P>
	After a day in training camp, Brooks skipped workouts Saturday  
and Sunday, creating speculation that he would retire because of 
injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have the utmost confidence in our ability to develop  
receivers,'' Wolf said. ``It's something we've always done here and 
I think we'll continue to do that and we have some very talented 
people who are involved in that, so I'm not concerned with that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wolf and coach Ray Rhodes declined to say Sunday whether Brooks,  
29, planned to quit because of knee, back and hamstring injuries 
that have sidelined him over the last three years. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's certainly earned the opportunity to make up his own mind  
and let's not speculate as to what it is he's going to do,'' Wolf 
said. ``When he does, then we'll know what we're going to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Without Brooks and without contract-holdout Antonio Freeman,  
quarterback Brett Favre lacked two of his favorite receivers when 
he joined training camp Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It leaves a void,'' Favre said. ``We have a good corps of  
receivers, young receivers. I don't know if anyone can step up and 
fill those shoes right away.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Derrick Mayes, a fourth-year pro, could get the first  
opportunity at the starting job opposite Freeman. 
</P>
<P>
	Mayes and Bill Schroeder worked with the first team during the  
weekend while Corey Bradford and Jahine Arnold caught for the 
second team. 
</P>
<P>
	Brooks underwent surgery during training camp last year to  
repair a herniated disc. He did not practice again until Oct. 11 
and played in the first five regular-season games. 
</P>
<P>
	The injury bothered him throughout the season. He finished with  
just 31 catches for 420 yards and three touchdowns, and was 
inactive for four games late in the season. 
</P>
<P>
	He had surgery again in January. He agreed to a $1.1 million pay  
cut in June, which the Packers said eased their salary-cap 
restriction. 
</P>
<P>
	Brooks caught 102 passes in 1995 after Sterling Sharpe's  
retirement, averaging 14.7 yards for a team-record 1,497 yards. 
</P>
<P>
	He enchanted fans that year by leaping into the outstretched  
arms of fans behind the Lambeau Field end zones to celebrate 
touchdowns, establishing a tradition known as the ``Lambeau Leap.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Packers gave him with a five-year, $15 million contract in  
February 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	He injured his right knee against San Francisco in October 1996.  
He returned in 1997 and was named the NFL's ``comeback player of 
the year'' by the Pro Football Writers of America. 
</P>
<P>
	By the end of the 1997 season, he developed lower-back pain.  
</P>
<P>
	He participated in every practice during the Packers' 10-day  
minicamp in June this year, raising hopes that he had recovered. 
</P>
<P>
	``We always thought he was going to play,'' Wolf said. ``But if  
he can't play, we have to go on.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             *Steelers    	
</P>
<P>
	Dermontti Dawson suffered a mild sprain in his left knee and is  
expected to miss the next three to four weeks of the preseason. 
</P>
<P>
	Dawson was injured during a nine-on-seven inside drill less than  
one hour into the second practice session Saturday afternoon at St. 
Vincent College. The severity of the injury was revealed during an 
MRI performed Sunday morning. 
</P>
<P>
	Dawson has started 164 straight games for the Steelers since  
late in his rookie year. 
</P>
<P>
                              *Titans    	
</P>
<P>
	If nothing else, Tennessee will know how to get a play off  
without being called for delay of game. 
</P>
<P>
	The Titans were flagged for that penalty more often than any  
other NFL team last season. Coach Jeff Fisher has made fixing that 
tendency a priority in training camp. 
</P>
<P>
	A play clock was installed on the field, and the team worked on  
its timing during two drills in the first full practice of camp. 
</P>
<P>
                             *Patriots    	
</P>
<P>
	Rookie running back Kevin Faulk, hoping to replace the injured  
Robert Edwards in New England's backfield, got his first taste of 
NFL-style discipline during morning practice. 
</P>
<P>
	After fumbling two punt returns, Faulk received an earful of  
instruction and got some hands-on attention from head coach Pete 
Carroll. The pair spent the next several minutes running through an 
intensive fumble-recovery drill. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, after Faulk dropped a screen pass from backup quarterback  
John Friesz, Carroll ordered the second-round draft choice from LSU 
to the sidelines, where he caught 50 screen passes from rookie 
quarterback Scott Mutryn. 
</P>
<P>
                             *Dolphins    	
</P>
<P>
	In a spirited intrasquad scrimmage that featured a melee, rookie  
running back Cecil Collins vaulted to the forefront of Miami's 
overcrowded backfield. 
</P>
<P>
	Collins, the Dolphins' fifth-round pick whose draft value  
dropped because of several off-field transgressions, rushed for 63 
yards on 13 carries, including a 40-yard touchdown off-tackle 
burst. 
</P>
<P>
                            *Buccaneers    	
</P>
<P>
	Tampa Bay will open camp without first-round draft pick Anthony  
McFarland after talks failed to produce a contract agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	General manager Rich McKay said he was ``perplexed and a little  
disappointed,'' that the team had not been able to finalize a deal. 
</P>
<P>
	McKay said talks would continue, but that he was not optimistic  
about having an agreement that would enable McFarland to join the 
team in time for its first practice today. 
</P>
<P>
                             *Seahawks    	
</P>
<P>
	Seattle got a quick introduction to Mike Holmgren's practice  
philosophy at the opening of training camp. 
</P>
<P>
	Rather than allow the team to ease into camp the first day,  
Holmgren interrupted proceedings midway through a morning session 
and explained to the entire team what he expects to see in 
first-and-10 situations. 
</P>
<P>
	The chat session illustrated the new Seahawks' coach's emphasis  
on detail and his willingness to take time out from practice to 
discuss his philosophy. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to explain to them what the drill was. I want to  
explain to them what I expect of them,'' said Holmgren, whose 
predecessor, Dennis Erickson, typically took a more hands-off 
approach in practice. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
