<HEADLINE> Ripken Scratched With Back Pain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- Cal Ripken Jr., bothered by back  
stiffness, left the Orioles on Monday and returned to Baltimore, 
where he will be examined by the team's orthopedic specialist. 
</P>
<P>
	Ripken was scratched from the Orioles' lineup Sunday in Seattle  
because of lower back pain. The third baseman told manager Ray 
Miller on Monday morning that his back was still bothering him and 
it was decided to send him home for treatment. 
</P>
<P>
	Ripken, who will turn 39 on Aug. 24, was scheduled to see Dr.  
Michael Jacobs on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	A team spokesman said Ripken, who is listed as day-to-day, is  
unlikely to return to play in the Orioles' three-game series in 
Oakland, which ends Wednesday. He could rejoin the Orioles on 
Thursday, when they play host to Detroit at Camden Yards. 
</P>
<P>
	Ripken, who as baseball's iron man played in 2,632 consecutive  
games before ending the streak last Sept. 20, went on the disabled 
list for the first time in his career in April with a nerve 
irritation in his lower back. 
</P>
<P>
	He returned May 13 and is batting .335 in 69 games this season.  
He has 15 home runs, leaving him one shy of 400 for his career. 
With 90 hits this year, he is 32 shy of 3,000. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
