<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Victims in Mich Plane Crash Mourned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COTTRELLVILLE TOWNSHIP, Mich. (AP) -- Russ Turner, a skydiver who  
has jumped out of airplanes more than a thousand times, fought back 
tears as he remembered his childhood friend who loved roaming the 
sky. 
</P>
<P>
	Turner praised pilot Paul Myks, a DC-9 captain who was at the  
controls of the twin-engine Beech King Air that plummeted into a 
hayfield moments after takeoff Saturday, killing all 10 aboard. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've known him since he was 12,'' Turner said Sunday. ``He was  
a great father, a great husband, a great pilot, a great friend and 
a great jumper. He was professional about everything he did.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Several hundred people in this close-knit group attended a  
memorial service led by a Michigan State Police chaplain and held 
in full view of the wreckage. 
</P>
<P>
	The fatal flight was the first of what was to be several flights  
for skydivers to take to the air. More than 100 members of the 
Parahawks had gathered Saturday for their annual pig roast. 
</P>
<P>
	Myks, 40, who owned the plane, had logged more than 9,000 hours  
of flight time, making him ``very experienced,'' said George Black, 
a spokesman for the National Transportation Safety Board. 
</P>
<P>
	The crash does not appear to have occurred as a result of engine  
failure, Black said. But he could not rule it out pending further 
testing. 
</P>
<P>
	``From a very initial examination of the engines, there is no  
evidence of any sort of turbine failure,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1967 Beech King Air 65A-90 took off about 8:20 a.m. Saturday  
from Marine City Airport. It cleared a 90-foot-high power line, 
then veered left and plummeted into a hayfield, exploding into a 
ball of fire. 
</P>
<P>
	Black said the wreckage, which lies about 1,200 feet from the  
edge of the runway, will be taken by the engine manufacturer, Pratt 
&AMP; Whitney, for analysis. Some will be shipped to Washington, D.C., 
for analysis, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Heat and humidity can be factors in a plane's performance, but  
there were no indications that they were the cause of the crash, 
Black said. It was 82 degrees with 69 percent humidity Saturday 
morning. 
</P>
<P>
	Black said that the lack of a flight data recorder will make the  
investigation more difficult. ``We're not going to be able to say 
as much as we could about an airliner,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, friends, relatives and fellow skydivers grieved for  
the victims. 
</P>
<P>
	Among them were Bob and Caroline Johnson, both members of the  
Parahawks. They were supposed to be on Saturday morning's flight 
but arrived at the airport late. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a very sad day,'' Johnson, of Rochester Hills, told The  
Detroit News. ``It's the weekend when we all take off from 
everything else and come out and enjoy each other's company and be 
thankful for all the times we've had. 
</P>
<P>
	``We all know the risk, and it's something we expect. It's  
better than sitting home on the couch, scared of life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gary Cooper, regional director of the U.S. Parachute  
Association, said other members of his club also were ``hard hit by 
the deaths.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a real close community,'' he said. ``Everybody knows  
everybody. It's kind of like a motorcycle club.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The crash wasn't the first tragedy for the Parahawks club, the  
Times Herald of Port Huron reported. Since 1980, two members have 
died because their parachutes failed to open. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
